<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Spitak     02-23 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spitak,0935</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Town Prowled By Abandoned Pets, Disturbed Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Spitak, near the center of the Armenian
earthquake, became the focus of world attention when Soviet TV
commentators said it was ``practically erased from the face of the
Earth.'' Former Moscow correspondent Carol J. Williams was one of
the first Western journalists to get into the city then, and she
recently returned. Here is her report.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPITAK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scrawny cats and packs of dogs prowl for
food in the ruins of this city that bore the brunt of Armenia's
deadly earthquake.
   The only human contact they have is an occasional petting or
shooing from Soviet soldiers and Armenian volunteers sorting twisted
metal from broken brick.
   Residents have been evacuated. The new Spitak will be built three
miles away from its present site, the confluence of three seismic
faults.
   There are some, though, who refuse to leave. A handful of elderly
Armenians still in shock from the Dec. 7 disaster wander aimlessly
among the paths cleared to allow cranes and bulldozers to chip away
at the sprawl of ruins that were once the homes of 25,000 people.
   One woman shod in socks and sandals, protected from the freezing
weather by only a flowered scarf and stretched-out sweater,
approaches workers passing by to show them her withered hands. She
speaks in broken sentences that fellow Armenians say are
unintelligible.
   ``She's crazy. She lost everyone,'' a young Russian soldier said
somberly after the woman tried to communicate with visiting Red
Cross volunteers from West Germany. ``We give her food, but she
refuses to go anywhere else.''
   Central Spitak is eerily still, save for the occasional roar of a
diesel engine or the grinding of gears as trucks haul away debris
through the winding mountain roads. There is also the cackling of
crows fluttering between the abandoned skeletons of apartment
houses, darting in through the jagged glass clinging to twisted
window frames.
   On the outskirts of the crumbled city, orderly rows of tents and
tube-like housing stretch out across the parched saddle of land
between the towering, snow-covered Caucasus Mountains.
   More than 4,000 people live in the camps, waiting and hoping for
the day when their lives can resume.
   ``I came here to help and I just do what I'm told,'' said Sambak
Azizyan, a crane operator from the nearby village of Dzhryashen who
lost his 4-year-old daughter in the quake. ``As soon as there is a
crane available for me, I'm ready to work day and night to rebuild.''
   Idleness has been a widespread consequence of the earthquake that
destroyed all factories as well as housing. And the absence of work
to take Armenians' minds off their suffering has slowed the healing
process.
   ``We lost our daughter, our home, our jobs, everything,''
lamented Sizush Danelyan, eyes welling with tears even 10 weeks
after the disaster. ``We're being taken care of and have no
complaints. But the new city will be somewhere else, and we cannot
leave. I couldn't abandon my daughter.''
   She motions toward the nearby hillside that at first glance
appears to be covered with small metal huts and high fences. The
miniature village is the city cemetery, where the cremated remains
of some earthquake victims have been laid to rest with other
departed relatives in shrine-like enclaves.
   There are isolated attempts to force life back to normal. Two
workers in a metal kiosk nestled among the concrete clutter in
Spitak's center sell newspapers and magazines, although the trade is
far from brisk. A shepherd drives a flock of two dozen sheep along
the roadside north of the city, and farmers from the neighboring
republic of Georgia stake out the city's inroads, selling greenhouse
fruit and flowers for prices that exceed a week's wages.
   ``It's a healthy sign that commerce has returned to the region,''
said Manfred Blum, general secretary of the West German Red Cross,
who has spent six weeks in the disaster area. ``A pack of Marlboros
is the currency of trade. They cost 10 rubles (about $16), but they
can buy a pair of warm socks.''
   The tons of clothing sent to Armenia from foreign countries are
not visible on the backs of the earthquake victims, as most of the
homeless and displaced continue to wear the clothes they had on
their backs when the quake struck.
   Aid agencies like the Red Cross and church organizations have
concentrated on providing food, shelter and medical care, while
clothing and household goods shipped to the stricken republic
without distribution directions likely were pilfered after being
stranded at Yerevan's airport for days or weeks.
   Despite occasional corruption and chaos, Armenians are learning
to cope with the crisis and start the long work of recovery. Food
distribution points are marked with hand-painted signs and purified
water is piped to the tent cities from treatment stations near the
Soviet army encampment.
   ``Our priority is to rescue people from the cold and outdoor
life,'' Spitak's Communist Party leader, Norik Moradyan, told the
Red Cross visitors in his container-office near the biggest grid of
tents.
   Negotiating from his desk overshadowed by a poster soliciting
bank donations to ``Help Armenia,'' Moradyan offered his West German
interlocutors an inducement to choose his region as the place to
spend millions in donations.
   ``If you help us rebuild,'' he said, ``we could name the new
housing region after Beethoven.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
