<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0861 02-23 0998</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0861,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Arrives in Japan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf pvs with 3 grafs to UPDATE with color, quote.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush arrived in Japan on Thursday to begin
his first overseas trip as chief executive, after voicing American
determination ``to stay a Pacific power'' and strenthen
relationships with allies in the region.
   Bush touched down aboard Air Force One shortly after 1 p.m. local
time Thursday, or just after 11 p.m. Wednesday back in Washington.
Bush and his wife, Barbara, were greeted on the Haneda Airport
tarmac by Keizo Obuchi, the chief Japanese Cabinet secretary, and
other government officials.
   Asked if she and her husband were able to get any sleep on the
more than 16-hour flight from Washington, Mrs. Bush replied,
``Lots.''
   Disregarding jet lag, the president headed immediately into
meetings with world leaders gathered in the Japanese capital for
Friday's funeral of Japanese Emperor Hirohito.
   First up was a planned luncheon meeting with French President
Francois Mitterrand.
   Earlier, Bush had spoken briefly to a group of U.S. servicemen
and their families during a refueling stop at Elmendorf Air Force
Base in Alaska, a traditional departure point for presidential trips
to the Far East.
   Speaking inside a hangar as snow fell outside, Bush said the aim
of his five-day, 18,095-mile trip is to ``strengthen key
relationships with our friends and partners in the Pacific region.''
   ``Alaskans understand that America is as much a Pacific nation as
it is an Atlantic one, and that the Pacific region is of great and
growing importance in international affairs,'' he said.
   Saying that his visit would also include talks of ``important
policy decisions'' with foreign leaders from the Middle East and
other areas, Bush declared: ``But we don't ever want to neglect our
friends.''
   ``And, yes, things in the Pacific seem to be going reasonably
well. But we are a Pacific power and this visit will demonstrate
that we intend to stay a Pacific power.''
   Bush spoke before several thousand airmen in blue, Army
infantrymen in camouflage uniforms and schoolchildren in parkas at
the air base. He recalled that one of his predecessors, President
William Henry Harrison, spoke at his inauguration for 3{ hours,
caught pneumonia and was dead within a month. Bush added: ``I will
be brief.''
   Bush's 90-minute refueling stop came at roughly the midway point
in his 16-hour flight on Air Force One.
   In Tokyo, Bush was to meet with various foreign leaders and
attend the funeral of Emperor Hirohito on Friday.
   He was also to visit China on Saturday and Sunday and make a
five-hour stopover in Seoul, South Korea, on the way home Monday.
   Bush's marathon day began at 5 a.m. EST Wednesday in Washington
and was to last until after 7:30 a.m. EST Thursday.
   Although his arrival in Tokyo was to be near midnight, East Coast
time, it came at early afternoon in Japan.
   Bush planned a full day's work, including the luncheon with
Mitterrand, a ``courtesy call'' on Japanese Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita and separate face-to-face meetings with leaders of Jordan,
Israel, Egypt, Portugal and Thailand.
   Press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush would try to nap some
on the plane but planned no other steps to offset the effect of jet
lag. ``We're going to tough it out all the way,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said Bush did paperwork in his cabin en route to Alaska
and spent some time going over briefing books with Secretary of
State James A. Baker III.
   Fitzwater also hinted Bush might have time during the trip to
make a few phone calls to senators to lobby for his nomination of
John Tower as defense secretary, but said there were no specific
plans for Bush to do so right now.
   ``We feel he (Tower) should be confirmed and will be confirmed,''
Fitzwater said.
   Also traveling with Bush were his wife, Barbara; National
Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft, and White House staff chief John
Sununu.
   Mrs. Bush told reporters the president ``slept like a baby'' for
seven hours before leaving Washington.
   In his airfield remarks, Bush noted that the late Japanese
emperor had visited the base 18 years bfore. ``It was here, at
Hangar 5 at Elmendorf, that he became the first emperor in Japan's
long history to set foot outside his homeland.''
   Bush, a combat pilot who fought against Japan in World War II,
was to join 10,000 other foreign and Japanese officials in attending
the funeral. Hirohito died in January at the age 87.
   Bush said his visit to Japan was also ``a measure of our respect
for a valued ally.''
   Of other stops on his journey, Bush said: ``In China _ a nation
whose path I have long found fascinating _ I hope to build on the
friendly, stable and enduring relationship that now exists.''
   Bush was envoy to China in 1974-75.
   ``In Korea,'' he continued, ``I'll meet with leaders of a nation
that is rapidly joining the ranks of the world's first-tier
economies, and one where democratic institutions are gaining
strength each day.''
   The pace of Bush's visit to Asia contrasts with the last
presidential trip, then-President Reagan's journey to the 1986
economic summit in Tokyo. Reagan stretched the trip out to nearly
two weeks.
   Meanwhile, Bush voiced opposition to a free-trade pact with Japan
and suggested Japan might expand its defense capability.
   The comments were included in series of responses to questions
submitted by a Japanese news service, Kyodo, and released Wednesday
by the White House.
   Even though the United States recently entered a free-trade
agreement with Canada, Bush suggested a similar pact with Japan _
the United States' second-biggest trading partner after Canada _ was
not in the cards.
   ``We will stress the multilateral approach,'' he said.
   In the remarks, Bush also said that, while some Americans feel
Japan isn't paying enough for its own defense, ``we are fully
satisfied'' with the current arrangement.
   Still, Bush said, there is ``room for greater improvement.''
</TEXT>
