<FIRST>r a BC-Grammys-SpecialAwards     02-23 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Grammys-Special Awards,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Awards Voted By Recording Academy Trustees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Along with the 76 categories of winners in
Wednesday night's 31st annual Grammy Awards, honorary awards were
voted to entertainers, composers, producers and other professionals
who influenced the American music industry over the years.
   The National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences' trustees'
awards went to:
   _Walt Disney, for his advancement of recording techniques and
unification of music to action on film.
   _Quincy Jones, the superproducer who has worked with artists from
Michael Jackson to Glen Campbell.
   _Cole Porter, the songwriter who best reflected Depression-era
America's desire to forget its blues with such tunes as ``You're The
Top.''
   _Richard Rodgers, who wrote scores for 27 Broadway musicals,
including ``Oklahoma,'' ``South Pacific'' and ``The Sound of
Music,'' among others.
   The Academy's lifetime achievement awards, voted by the national
trustees for performers who have made contributions to the recording
field, were to:
   _Fred Astaire, whose dancing combined with his self-described
modest voice to sell some of America's most famous songs, including
``Night and Day,'' ``They Can't Take That Away From Me'' and ``A
Fine Romance.''
   _Pablo Casals, the Spanish cellist whose solo interpretations of
Bach and Beethoven brought his single instrument to a new level of
respect.
   _``Dizzy'' Gillespie, the jowly trombone player who was a
co-creator of bop jazz.
   _Jascha Hiefetz, the renowned violinist whose career spanned 55
years.
   _Lena Horne, the stylish vocalist whose more than 50 years in
show business has slowed neither her style nor power as a singer.
   _Leontyne Price, the operatic star.
   _Bessie Smith, known as the empress of the blues.
   _Art Tatum, the jazz pianist.
   _Sarah Vaughan, whose vocal styles range from pop to jazz to
semi-classical material.
</TEXT>
