<FIRST>u a AM-U.S.-JapanesePoll     02-23 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-U.S.-Japanese Poll,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Americans And Japanese With More Favorable View Of Each
Other</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans and Japanese are looking at the
relationship between their nations more favorably after a period of
strain over economic relations, according poll results reported
Wednesday.
   A survey by The New York Times, CBS News and the Tokyo
Broadcasting System also found that majorities in both countries
agree on the rise of Japanese power and are equally split over
whether U.S. might has declined.
   About relations, 79 percent of Americans said they were somewhat
or very friendly, up from 72 percent in May 1987. The Times said 68
percent of Japanese said relations were somewhat or very friendly,
up from 43 percent two years ago.
   In Japan, the Times said the poll found that 77 percent support
the emperor system today, with 73 percent saying they now view the
emperor as a national symbol and only 2 percent still see him as a
god.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. poll found that 63 percent of Americans
believe it is appropriate for President Bush to attend the funeral.
The Times added, however, that 66 percent of people under 30 approve
of the trip while it draws approval from only 41 percent of those
over 64, with adult memories of World War II.
   The poll, based on telephone interviews with 1,060 Japanese
adults from Feb. 16 to Feb. 19, and 1,233 U.S. adults on Feb. 18-19,
had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</TEXT>
