<HEAD>Government Protests Fatal Shooting At Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has lodged a protest
with East German officials over border guards' reported fatal
shooting of a man who was trying to flee to the West over the Berlin
Wall.
   Chief government spokesman Friedhelm Ost said Wednesday that East
Berlin's envoy to West Germany was summoned and advised of the
official protest.
   On Tuesday, the mass-circulation Bild newspaper said a
22-year-old man was killed in the escape attempt Feb. 6. The
newspaper said a companion was severely wounded when East German
troops opened fire on the pair.
   The West Berlin Senate on Wednesday said that evidence collected
so far appears to substantiate the report.
   At least 77 people have died trying to flee over the wall into
West Berlin, according to Working Group August 13, named after the
day in 1961 that East Germany's Communist authorities began building
the wall.
