<FIRST>u a AM-SameSexMarriages     02-23 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Same Sex Marriages,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bar Association of San Francisco Endorses New Marriages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of directors of the 8,000-member
Bar Association of San Francisco on Wednesday called for an end to a
state law banning same-sex marriages, a legal newspaper reported.
   Such bans were called ``invidious discrimination'' by the
association's president, Peter G. Keane.
   According to Thursday editions of the San Francisco Banner Daily
Journal, the association's directors unanimously urged that the
current state civil code mandating marriages between ``a man and a
woman'' be changed to read ``marriage is a personal relation arising
out of a civil contract between two people.''
   Such a change would give partners of both homosexuals and
heterosexuals many of the same rights now enjoyed as part of legal
marriage.
   Keane said banning same-sex marriages was a ``clear denial of
equal protection under the 14th Amendment to the Constitution by
singling out an identifiable class of people.''
   He added that a new definition of marriage is needed to correct
``invidious discrimination against non-heterosexuals who choose to
have a relationship that has the same quality and definition that a
husband and wife have.''
   Members of the board said the same-sex marriage law could
eliminate the need for so-called domestic partners legislation.
   Harry Britt, an openly gay member of the city council, has
proposed the legislation to make medical and other benefits
available to live-in companions.
</TEXT>
