<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmCredit     02-23 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Credit,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cut Loose Failing Farmers, Panel Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government should recognize that farming is
a business, not a ``way of life,'' and should stop propping up
farmers who can't make it on their own, a national commission says.
   The National Commission on Agricultural Finance said Wednesday
that programs that support farmers whose operations are not viable
will end up making American agriculture less competitive in the
global marketplace.
   It urged Congress to revise farm programs to eliminate farmers
who cannot make a go of their business, and to separate farm credit
programs from social policy.
   ``Agriculture is a business, it is not a way of life,'' said
commission chairman Harold B. Steele of Princeton, Ill. ``We should
not disguise a social program under a credit agency.''
   The panel, established by Congress in 1985, also urged lawmakers
to choose between crop insurance or disaster payments, saying
``using both won't work.''
   Congress last summer passed a $4 billion drought relief bill to
help farmers whose crops were scorched by the record drought of 1988.
   The commission, however, said that ``the answer to natural
disasters is not more credit.''
   The panel of mostly academicians, farmers and bankers sharply
criticized federal policies that use subsidized credit to solve farm
income problems.
   ``In essence, policy attempts to enhance the welfare of farmers
while maintaining low grocery bills for the consumer,'' the report
said. ``Although possible, this reactive approach is an impediment
to agriculture as it tries to compete in world markets.''
   The report said keeping all who want to farm in business,
regardless of capacity and ability, ``leads to antagonism by other
farmers and other sectors of the economy.''
   Keeping non-viable farmers in business even hurts those very
farmers, the study said. ``They waste critical years of their very
productive lives,'' it said.
   The commission did, however, endorse the idea of a ``safety net''
for farm families whose business fails.
   Commission members also advocated universal loan application and
accounting standards for farm businesses, blaming the farm credit
crisis in the early 1980s in part on differing lending standards
that proved inadequate in determining whether a farmer could repay a
loan.
   Congress bailed out the Farm Credit System, a cooperatively owned
network of banks and lending institutions, in 1987. Hundreds of
rural banks also failed throughout the decade because of the farm
credit crisis, which was prompted by falling land values, high
farmer debt and bad loan decisions.
   Lenders may have made better decisions in the go-go borrowing era
of the late 1970s if they and farmers had all been looking at the
same criteria _ balance sheets and cash flow statements, rather than
at collateral and escalating land values, the commission said.
   ``While an increasing number of borrowers do make available good
coordinated records, many borrowers still do not have adequate
records or financial statements from which to make informed credit
analysis decisions,'' the report said. ``This situation may stem
from the fact that lenders historically made credit decisions based
on collateral and not coordinated financial statements.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     02-23 0894</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recurrence of Drought Unlikely, Though Some Areas Remain Dry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and snow have helped improve soil
conditions in parts of the winter wheat belt, but parts of the Great
Plains wheat area are still gasping for moisture.
   After last year's devastating drought, moisture conditions are
being watched closely for signs of an unwanted encore in 1989, a
siege that a government economist said Wednesday could trigger a new
round of higher food prices and add to the farm debt burden.
   The federal Joint Agricultural Weather Facility said rain during
the week of Feb. 13-19 helped winter wheat in Oklahoma and parts of
Texas. But in Kansas, the crop needed snow cover and moisture.
   ``Snow cover was mostly adequate in the northern plains,'' the
report said. ``Additional snow improved cold weather protection in
Michgan; winter wheat was mostly good to fair in Illinois.''
   The facility is operated by the Agriculture and Commerce
departments to provide weekly updates on weather and crop conditions.
   Mark Drabenstott, assistant vice president and economist at the
Federal Reserve Bank in Kansas City, Mo., told the Senate Commerce
Committee in written testimony that the effect of the drought of
1988 on farmers, agribusiness, farm lenders and consumers ``was not
as great as had been expected.''
   He said, however, that ``much of agriculture's adjustment
capacity was depleted in 1988, and the effects of continued drought
in 1989 would be more severe.''
   Norton Strommen, the USDA's chief meteorologist, says a
recurrence of last year's severe drought is unlikely.
   Drabenstott agreed that the odds are against a repeat of the 1988
drought this year. But he added that if another drought did occur,
sharply reduced grain stockpiles would push crop prices to ``record
or near-record levels.''
   ``Many crop producers added to their 1988 income by selling grain
inventories built up in earlier years, an option that will not be
available in 1989,'' Drabenstott said in his written testimony.
   ``Thus, despite the very high grain prices that would accompany
continued drought, smaller crops and depleted inventories would
probably mean smaller farm income.''
   Higher crop prices also would deliver a ``severe blow to the
livestock industry'' by driving up feed costs, Drabenstott said.
Consumers, he added, would feel the effects of lower meat production
for some time.
   As for the drought of 1988, Drabenstott said ``financial
reserves'' from recently good farming years and a $3.9 billion
federal assistance program helped producers minimize the effects of
last year's poor harvests.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pollination of crops by honeybees is worth
at least $9.7 billion a year in added value, says a study by Cornell
University.
   Honeybees are used by the millions to pollinate major crops of
fruits, berries, vegetables, tree nuts, oilseeds and legumes. Their
keepers rent them out commercially, trucking the bees to crop areas.
   The study, released Wednesday, was prepared by Cornell for the
National Honey Board, which was authorized by Congress and
established by the Agriculture Department in 1986 to promote honey
and honey research. The board is financed by producers.
   About a million colonies of bees are involved in commercial crop
pollination, about a third of all U.S. managed colonies, the report
said. That is about double the number estimated in the early 1980s.
   ``To a significant degree, because of the hard work of the
honeybee we have abundant food supplies at reasonable prices,'' said
Dan Hall, manager of the National Honey Board, based in Longmont,
Colo.
   Commercial pollination ranges from blueberries and cranberries in
New England to apples in the Northwest and New York to almonds in
California and some citrus in Florida.
   Other major examples cited included alfalfa seed in the West,
melons in Texas, cucumbers in the Carolinas and Michigan, sunflowers
in Minnesota, and seeds for onions, carrots, celery and other
vegetables in many states.
   Frederick Hoff of USDA's Economic Research Service said that many
consumers are unaware that honeybees are used to pollinate foods
they are dependent upon. He said the study shows that pollination is
``even more important than we thought.''
   The Cornell study was based on 1985 information and showed that
the $9.7 billion in direct benefits represented the dollar value of
increased crop yields and quality as the result of honeybee crop
pollination.
   ``Crop quality improvements include larger and more uniform size,
desirable shape, uniform maturation date, and all result in higher
market value,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the long-time
slide in the U.S. cattle inventory has ended and that producers are
beginning to expand their herds.
   A USDA report on Feb. 8 showed that the nation's cattle inventory
as of Jan. 1 was virtually the same as it had been a year earlier.
Many private analysts had been saying the herd numbers would show
another significant decline.
   ``This expansion dramatically changes the beef outlook for 1989
and beyond,'' the department's Economic Research Service said
Wednesday. ``Beef cows number 2 percent above a year earlier, and
beef replacement heifers were up 5 percent.''
   Moreover, the report noted that the Jan. 1 figures showed last
year's calf crop was 672,000 head larger than was projected last
summer.
   Including dairy animals, the U.S. herd of cattle and calves
totaled a 28-year low of 99,484,000 head on Jan. 1, down only 40,000
head from a year ago.
</TEXT>
