<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     02-23 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Press Administration on New Budget Spending</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democrats wrestling with
President Bush's fiscal 1990 budget are trying to put White House
officials on the defensive by forcing them to admit they can't
explain how new initiatives will be paid for.
   Budget director Richard G. Darman and Transportation Secretary
Samuel K. Skinner, dispatched to Capitol Hill on Wednesday to sell
Bush's $1.16 trillion spending proposal, became the latest victims
of the Democrats' strategy.
   Each man ran into hostile questioning from Democrats seeking to
learn which programs Bush wants to cut in order to pay for the
spending increases he is seeking.
   Skinner told the House transportation appropriations subcommittee
that Bush's proposals to boost the budgets of the Coast Guard and
the Federal Aviation Administration should ``come out of somebody
else's pot.''
   Bush is seeking to boost the Coast Guard's budget for anti-drug
efforts by 9 percent next year to $690 million. He also wants to
enable the FAA to hire more air traffic controllers and safety
inspectors, and to modernize its equipment and make other
improvements, by increasing its budget 16 percent to $6.6 billion.
   ``Transportation has paid long enough,'' Skinner told the
lawmakers.
   But this prompted Rep. William H. Gray III, one of the House's
Democratic leaders and a former budget committee chairman, to press
him on where the additional money would come from.
   ``You'd want it to come out of interior or education or somebody
else's committee,'' Gray told the cabinet member. ``We all want to
go and give wonderful statements about wonderful new spending
programs we want, but we all point our fingers and say, `Let's take
it from another pot.'''
   At a hearing held by the House Budget Committee, White House
budget director Richard Darman fended off Democratic attempts to
define the specific spending levels Bush seeks for various domestic
programs.
   In a spirited exchange with Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., Darman
refused to say how much money the president seeks for programs such
as care for poor pregnant women, veterans' education, mass transit,
or even the Job Training Partnership Act _ the bill Bush cited in
choosing Dan Quayle for his vice presidential nomination.
   ``President Bush's position is that he wants to negotiate the
answer to that, and you don't like that apparently,'' Darman said.
   Boxer told Darman that while Bush's proposals to increase some
spending in some areas, ``we haven't really seen the bad parts.''
   In the budget he presented to Congress on Feb. 9, Bush proposed
allowing defense spending to grow at the rate of inflation and
giving slight boosts to several priority areas such as acid rain and
scientific research. He made no cuts in Social Security and proposed
no general tax increases, but did seek limited tax extensions, new
user fees and asset sales to bring in about $17 billion in new
revenue next year.
   Perhaps most infuriating to the Democrats, however, was his
creation of what lawmakers have dubbed the ``black box.'' Bush
proposed limiting more than 1,000 programs, mostly in domestic
areas, to the $136 billion spent for them this year, and left it to
Congress to decide how the money would be distributed.
   Budget committee chairman Leon Panetta criticized Darman for
outlining options but not Bush choices in the hundreds of pages of
documents he was presenting to Congress.
   ``There have been too many games played with the deficit issue in
the past,'' Panetta said. ``My concern is when you strip the
rhetoric aside... some of the same games are being played.''
</TEXT>
