<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AFL-CIOMeeting 1stLd-Writethru a0428 02-23 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AFL-CIO Meeting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0428,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kirkland Tackles Teamsters, Showgirls Questions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes typo, `help' sted `help,' in 5th graf, `Several women...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland defended
Teamsters leaders set for trial next week and dismissed a question
about whether using showgirls as hostesses for a union reception
reflected poorly on labor's image.
   Kirkland addressed the questions Wednesday after the president of
the union that held the reception, the National Association of
Letter Carriers, said he thought the women would ``help improve''
the image of his union.
   ``Don't you take some things too seriously?'' Kirkland said when
asked about the Monday night gathering, at which two women in body
tights and mesh tops greeted guests, mostly union officials, and
posed for photographs with some of them.
   Earlier, Vincent R. Sombrotto, president of the 315,000-member
NALC, said, ``I think it improves the image of the letter
carriers,'' when asked about the hostesses.
   Several women labor officials at the AFL-CIO's annual convention
here complained privately Tuesday and Wednesday about the hostesses,
including one who said she found it hypocritical for the union
leaders to promote expanded child care and parental leave policies
designed to help working parents.
   Kirkland, at his daily briefing, renewed his attack on the
government's use of racketeering laws to seek to take over the
Teamsters union.
   The suit, set for trial next week, alleges the union for years
has been influenced by organized crime and names as defendants most
of the union's leadership, including President William McCarthy.
   But Kirkland, while not disputing mob influence in the union in
the past, said, ``I do not think it is a problem of any significance
in the Teamsters at this moment.''
   And he complained anew that the use of the racketeering statute
was inappropriate and there are other laws that call for the removal
of any union official convicted of most felonies.
   ``I think the approach of a government trying to put a labor
organization under trusteeship is a violation of the basic principle
of freedom of association,'' Kirkland said.
   The labor federation's Executive Council, which has a light
agenda today and Friday, focused on international affairs Wednesday,
issuing four statements condemning anti-labor efforts by the
governments of Chile, Burma, Korea and Poland.
   The weeklong meeting has been a relatively low-key event, not
unusual for a post-election year. Much of the focus has been on the
threatened strike at Eastern Airlines by 9,000 members of the
International Association of Machinists.
   The planned March 4 walkout has kept AFL-CIO officials busy
arranging for other unions to support the machinists while at the
same time asking President Bush to delay the strike deadline by
naming an emergency board to mediate the dispute.
   On Wednesday, however, Eastern pilots issued a statement saying
they would cross Machinist union picket lines if there's a strike,
provided the troubled carrier's owner grants them concessions in
their own contract.
   Kirkland and other council members were attending a rally late
today with Eastern machinists based in Miami, the airline's
headquarters.
</TEXT>
