<DOCNO> AP890223-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BudgetReport     02-23 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget Report,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fiscal 1989 Budget Deficit Smaller than 1988's Red Ink-So Far</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest update on the federal budget shows
the deficit for the first four months of fiscal 1989 was smaller
than during the comparable period a year earlier, but analysts
expect the good news won't last.
   The Treasury Department reported Wednesday that for the first
four months of fiscal 1989, which began Oct. 1, the budget gap was
$64.8 billion, 2.3 percent smaller than for the comparable period in
fiscal 1988.
   Economists nevertheless expect the fiscal 1989 deficit to exceed
the $155.1 billion shortfall posted in 1988 as interest rates rise
and the pace of spending increases.
   The Bush administration is projecting the deficit will hit $163.3
billion, which would be a 5.3 percent increase from the level of red
ink in fiscal 1988.
   Economist Paul Denoon of Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. in New
York said the fiscal 1989 deficit is likely to be in the $160
billion-$165 billion range.
   ``As we get later in the year, we'll start seeing some stronger
outlay figures,'' Denoon said. He said expenses associated with the
financial failures in the savings and loan industry and rising
interest rates will contribute to the larger deficit.
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, in congressional
testimony this week, indicated the central bank was likely to
continue to push up interest rates in an effort to slow economic
growth and thus restrain inflation.
   Worries about inflation were heightened by the release Wednesday
of the Consumer Price Index for January, which posted a 0.6 percent
increase.
   The government actually posted a $2.8 billion surplus in January
due to a surge in revenue caused by quarterly tax payments from
individuals.
   Government revenues reached $89.4 billion last month, up 9.3
percent from the same period a year earlier. Spending, meanwhile,
was up 31.4 percent from January 1988 to $86.6 billion.
   Spending in January 1988 had been artificially low because Social
Security checks, which normally go out on the third day of that
month, were mailed out on Dec. 31 because of the New Year's holiday.
The change in benefits payments resulted in a $15.9 billion surplus
in January 1988.
   The biggest government spending categories last month were the
military, Social Security, other programs in the Department of
Health and Human Services, interest on the national debt and farm
subsidies.
   Military spending totaled $19.3 billion last month and $96.6
billion for the past four months, up 3.3 percent from the year-ago
period.
   Interest on the national debt totaled $15.9 billion in January
and $84.2 billion for the first four months of the fiscal year, up
11.1 percent from a year earlier.
   Spending for Social Security was $18 billion in January and $72.6
billion so far in the fiscal year, up 5.7 percent from the
comparable period in fiscal 1988.
   Other HHS programs, including Medicare and Medicaid, cost $13.5
billion in January and $53.5 billion for the first four months of
fiscal 1989, up 5.9 percent from the comparable period a year
earlier.
   Spending by the Agriculture Department totaled $4.6 billion last
month and $20.6 billion so far this fiscal year, down 2.2 percent
from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
