<FIRST>r w PM-FBIRecruiters     02-23 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FBI Recruiters,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>University of Michigan Law School's Decision Decried by FBI</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI says the University of Michigan law
school's decision to ban its recruiters because of a discrimination
case will deprive the agency of applicants able to handle civil
rights cases.
   ``How are we to get top quality FBI agents on board if we are not
allowed to come on to top quality campuses?'' Milt Ahlerich,
assistant FBI director for congressional and public affairs, said
Wednesday.
   Lee Bollinger, dean of the University of Michigan law school,
said Wednesday by telephone he imposed the ban in December after the
FBI lost a class-action discrimination suit in Texas brought by
Hispanic agents. The ban will last through the end of the school
year in May.
   The discrimination suit was filed by FBI agent Bernardo Matias
Perez on behalf of 311 Hispanic agents. U.S. District Judge Lucius
D. Bunton, who found last September that the FBI had discriminated
against the Hispanic agents, is holding a hearing to determine how
much the FBI should pay them as compensation for denial of
promotions and assignments to unrewarding and hazardous duties. The
agents are seeking $9.2 million.
   Bollinger said students at the law school had brought the case to
his attention in September, saying ``it was in violation of our
placement anti-discrimination policy'' for such an organization to
be allowed to recruit at the school.
   Of the FBI's 9,500 agents, about 1,300 graduated from law
schools, he said. Over the past three years, the FBI has hired about
1,855 special agents, of whom about 320, or 17 percent, are trained
in law, according to figures provided by Ahlerich.
   ``If the bureau is to be sensitive and particularly able to
handle challenges of sophisticated crime problems that we have in
this country today, including handling of civil rights
investigations, we need very capable, sensitive applicants, and
lawyers fill that role in many instances,'' Ahlerich said. He said
he knows of only one agent who graduated from the University of
Michigan law school.
   The Ohio State University law school dean, Francis X. Beytagh,
told The Washington Post for a story in Wednesday's editions that
his school also banned FBI recruiting on campus although it allows
the agency to continue distributing employment information.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
