<DOCNO> AP890223-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0351EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-IndianInvestigation     02-23 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Investigation,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turnover in BIA Helps Perpetuate Abuse Problem, Witnesses Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy turnover in the government's Indian
affairs bureau has created a bureaucratic nightmare and official
neglect of child sexual abuse cases on reservations, witnesses at a
special Senate hearing say.
   ``I was put there to keep the administrative portion going,''
Robert Delaware, acting chief of social services for the Bureau of
Indian Affairs, testified Wednesday. Delaware told Senate panelists
he was the sixth acting chief in the social services division since
August 1986 and was unfamiliar with sex abuse cases.
   ``I don't care if you are acting director for one day or three
months, the impression you leave is that it is not your job _ leave
it to someone else,'' Sen. Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., angrily responded.
   ``I can understand the frustration of the people on the
reservation,'' Daschle said. ``We're failing at this.''
   Linda Guy, social services specialist in the BIA, told the
special panel of the Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs there
have been so many changes in leadership in the division that it is
nearly impossible to handle child sex abuse cases.
   Margaret Allen, child welfare supervisor for tribal services in
the Gila River Indian Community, in Arizona, said she has never been
able to find an official within the BIA or the Indian Health Service
responsible for treating sex offenders.
   Witnesses also said investigation of sex abuse allegations is
difficult.
   Penny Coleman, attorney advisor in the solicitor's office of the
Interior Department, said the FBI, rather than local police,
investigate the crimes on reservations. She said the FBI lacks
specific training for handling child abuse cases, and has
comparatively small staffs for the volume of work in Indian crime.
   Other witnesses said the problem of child abuse was compounded by
jurisdictional problems, the isolation of the reservations and a
simple lack of money.
   Dr. Jane Burnley, director of the office for victims of crime in
the Justice Department, said child sex abuse is not inherently worse
among Indians than in the rest of society.
   But the federal government, which has jurisdiction over Indian
reservations, lacks mechanisms to respond to the problems the way
states do, she said after her testimony.
   Dr. Eidell Wasserman, director of a special child sexual abuse
project on the Hopi reservation in Arizona, said that for the last
10 months she has been trying to find money to keep her program from
going out of business.
   The project was set up in 1987 to treat members of the
reservation who were victims of a former teacher in the BIA school
who molested 142 boys during a 9-year period.
   After the teacher was convicted and imprisoned, the federal
government provided $200,000 for therapy and other programs. But the
funding is set to expire in June.
   Some of the boys who were abused now have become offenders,
compounding the original problems brought on by the teacher's
actions, said Wasserman.
   Burnley said victims' compensation has grown tremendously as a
way of funding treatment for victims of child abuse in the states.
   ``But not in Indian country,'' she told the committee.
   She said about $2 million for fiscal 1989 was earmarked by the
federal government for such cases among Indians, and Indians are
eligible to apply to state governments for money from their victims'
funds. But she said Indian reservations are usually in remote areas
where communications and transportation are poor, making therapy
much more difficult than in other parts of society.
</TEXT>
