<FIRST>r w PM-Press-Awards     02-23 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Press-Awards,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eugene Roberts of Inquirer Honored by Foundation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The winner of the National Press Foundation's
top award urged his fellow members of the media to protest the spate
of defamation lawsuits against private citizens who speak out on
issues.
   Accepting the Distinguished Contributions to Journalism Award,
executive editor Eugene L. Roberts Jr. of The Philadelphia Inquirer
said such defamation suits could squelch public debate.
   ``Many American citizens are being intimidated by defamation
suits,'' he said Wednesday night at the awards banquet.
   Since Roberts joined the Inquirer in 1972, the paper has won 14
Pulitzer Prizes, including the Gold Medal for Public Service. The
paper has received more than 150 other major national awards.
   Others cited by the foundation were N. Christian Anderson, editor
of The Orange County, (Calif.) Register; Brian Lamb, founder of
C-SPAN; and Terry Anderson, an Associated Press correspondent who
has been held hostage in Lebanon since March 1985.
   Terry Anderson received a special citation for his dignity and
forbearance in captivity. One of nine American hostages in Lebanon,
Anderson has been in captivity longer than the others.
   Peggy Say, Terry Anderson's sister, accepted the award for her
brother. ``Terry's greatest fear is being forgotten,'' Mrs. Say
said, explaining she learned about his fears from former captives.
``This award sends a message to the world that he is not forgotten.''
   The Register's Anderson was recipient of the $5,000 George David
Beveridge Editor of the Year Award for transforming a suburban daily
into a dominant newspaper in the area, winning awards for design,
sports, photography and news.
   Lamb, recipient of the $5,000 Sol Taishoff Award for excellence
in broadcasting, was honored for creating the nation's first public
affairs television network. Lamb conceived of C-SPAN, and then
convinced the cable industry to finance it as a public service.
   Lamb said C-Span, which is celebrating its tenth anniversary,
reaches 21 million households and is popular abroad as well as in
the United States.
   Roberts, the son of a weekly newspaper editor, began his career
as a farm reporter for the Goldsboro, N.C., News-Argus. He also
worked at the Norfolk Virginian-Pilot; the News and Observer of
Raleigh, N.C.; and the Detroit Free Press before he joined The New
York Times.
   Roberts covered the civil rights movement in the 1960s and the
war in Vietnam for The New York Times before he served as national
editor.
   In 1986, Roberts was named president of Philadelphia Newspapers
Inc.
</TEXT>
