<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     02-23 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Shares Hit Another High, Dollar Off 0.33 Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose sharply and finished at yet
another high Thursday on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the U.S.
dollar inched up after opening lower against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 126.29 yen, down 0.33 yen from Wednesday's
126.62-yen finish. After opening at 126.13 yen, the currency moved
in a range of 126.10-126.37 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 331.85-point
gainer for a record 32,311.93-point closing Wednesday, added another
140.56 points, or 0.44 percent, finished at 32,452.49, a new high.
   The market's main index started lower after a sharp drop in the
Dow Jones industrial average in New York, dealers said. The Dow fell
42.50 points to 2,283.83, the biggest drop since Nov. 11, when the
widely followed index shed 47.66 points.
   After the initial loss, the market reversed and began to climb as
buy orders started coming in, dealers said.
   Participants showed strong buying interest because Thursday is
the first day of the March account, said one trader with a major
securities firm in Tokyo.
   The index's dip in early trading followed the release of figures
showing a jump in U.S. consumer prices and a remark by U.S. Federal
Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan that he was disturbed by
inflation's strength.
   The U.S. Labor Department reported Wednesday that the nation's
consumer prices rose at an annual rate of 7.2 percent in January.
   Greenspan, in his second day of testimony Wednesday before the
U.S. House Banking Committee, said the Federal Reserve is determined
to resist any rise in inflation this year.
   In currency dealings, Greenspan's remarks that the Federal
Reserve has no intention of raising discount rates discouraged
market players by raising fears of inflation and prompted their
dollar selling, dealers said.
   Trading Thursday morning was light as Japanese investors stepped
to the sidelines to avoid major moves ahead of a three-day weekend
starting Friday, said one dealer with a Japanse commercial bank,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Friday is a public holiday for the state funeral for the late
Emperor Hirohito.
</TEXT>
