<NOTE>Navy Dolphin Program Cleared</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has been cleared of allegations it
mistreated dolphins and sea lions being trained for various
underwater surveillance duties.
   The Marine Mammal Commission review team, after what it described
as an extensive survey of Navy facilities and practices, sharply
criticized a former Navy trainer and other unidentified sources who
charged in November the service was guilty of animal abuse.
   ``The review team found the allegations to be substantively
lacking,'' states the commission's report, released Wednesday by the
Navy.
   The team ``concluded that allegations had been put forward in
such a way as to create an inaccurate picture,'' the report
continued.
   ``Furthermore, the team concluded that, had the sole motivation
underlying the allegations been concern for the health, welfare and
care of the animals, the former trainer would have made better use
than he did of the Navy's Animal Care Committee.''
   The program now includes about 115 animals, the majority of them
dolphins and the remainder of them beluga whales. The service trains
the mammals to detect enemy scuba divers and to hunt for underwater
mines. The program began more than 20 years ago.
</TEXT>
