<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ProgramExclusivity     02-23 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Program Exclusivity,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Reaffirms Syndication Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by the Federal Communications
Commission to let TV stations buy exclusive rights to syndicated
programs will create chaos in the cable channels, a representative
of the cable industry says.
   The FCC on Wednesday upheld its May 1988 decision to readopt
``syndicated exclusivity,'' intended to give broadcasters the right
to retain exclusive rights for programming they buy.
   Under the rules, only the local TV station that buys the rights
to a particular program can air that program in the local market.
The station can prevent a local cable operator from showing the
program carried by an out-of-town station.
   In a statement following the FCC's action, James P. Mooney,
president of the National Cable Television Association, said the
rules ``will lead to widespread program blackouts and substantial
viewer confusion and frustration.''
   For example, he said, a cable company operator will have to black
out a syndicated program _ ``Star Trek,'' for example _ from an
out-of-town station if a local station holds the rights.
   ``The impact of this on consumers will be that if you're
expecting a popular show like Star Trek to be on an out-of-town
channel at 7 p.m., it won't be there,'' he said. ``Some filler
program _ or a blank screen _ will be there instead, and if the
cable operator finds it too impractical to make all the deletions
and additions, he may be forced to drop the out-of-town channel
entirely.''
   Syndication refers to the free marketing of programs, usually
discontinued network series.
   In its decision Wednesday, the FCC also extended the date for
compliance from Aug. 18 to Dec. 31 to give the cable and broadcast
industries more time to prepare for the new arrangement.
   Cable operators had wanted more time to prepare for the change,
arguing that new switching equipment will be necessary to make the
program deletions and find available programming to fill the holes
created by the rules.
   Broadcasters, however, wanted a shorter transition time, saying
substitute programming is already available and the electronic
switching equipment is readily available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
