<FIRST>r w PM-MIARemains     02-23 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MIA Remains,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Navy Fliers Identified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of six Navy aviators who died in
Vietnam have been identified.
   The six were identified by the Army's Central Identification
Laboratory in Honolulu after being repatriated to the United States
by Vietnam last November, the Pentagon said in a statement.
   The remains of five of the six servicemen were scheduled to be
transported back to the mainland today, the Pentagon said. The
remains of the sixth Navy officer have already been returned to
California.
   At the request of the families, the Navy said it was withholding
the identities of two of the six men. It identified the other four
as:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Cmdr. Charles E. Barnett, born on Jan. 18, 1935, lost over North
Vietnam on May 23, 1972. He listed his home of record as Houston,
Texas.
   _Cmdr. Clarence O. Tolbert, born on June 4, 1939, lost over North
Vietnam on Nov. 6, 1972. He listed his home of record as Tishomingo,
Okla.
   _Lt. Cmdr. Robert T. Hanson Jr., born on Dec. 28, 1942, lost over
North Vietnam on Feb. 3, 1966. He listed his home of record as
Toledo, Ohio.
   _And Lt. Frederick M. Kasch, U.S. Navy Reserve, born on Oct. 24,
1940, lost over North Vietnam on July 2, 1967. He listed his home of
record as San Diego, Calif.
   The six men are the first from a group of 23 remains repatriated
by the Vietnamese on Nov. 3 to be identified, the Pentagon said.
   With the latest identifications, 2,377 Americans continue to be
listed as missing in Indochina as a result of the Vietnam war, of
whom 1,741 are listed as missing in either North or South Vietnam.
   All told, the remains of 178 Americans have been repatriated to
the United States from Vietnam and subsequently identified by the
Army lab since the end of the war.
</TEXT>
