<FIRST>r a PM-StrandedBallet     02-23 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stranded Ballet,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fiasco to Good Fortune for Stranded Soviet Dancers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet ballet company that was left on shaky
footing when its original backers pulled out made its New York debut
thanks to an outpouring of support from the business and dance world.
   Lead dancer Vadim Pisarev said Wednesday night's performance was
everything the group had hoped for.
   ``We got a 10-minute standing ovation. Everything went very well.
We are extremely pleased,'' he said.
   New York arts patron Howard Gilman, averting an embarrassing
international incident, mobilized the business and dance worlds when
the Donetsk Ballet's original backers bailed out in mid-tour,
leaving the visiting performers stranded and penniless in Baltimore.
   ``These people started out in Baltimore eating pizzas donated by
theater ushers,'' Gilman said. ``I think everybody understood there
was something more at stake than just a company that wasn't able to
perform. It was everyone's reputation.''
   Businesses, ballet lovers and even a New Jersey firehouse pitched
in with free meals, cash and messages of hope. The artistic director
of the American Ballet Theatre, Mikhail Baryshnikov, provided
technical and moral support; Eliot Feld, founder of the Feld Ballet,
treated the dancers to dinner.
   With the help of I.C.M. Artists, a concert management firm based
in New York City, Gilman booked the Donetsk into New York's City
Center, with a Wednesday night debut. Future appearances were
scheduled at the National Theater in Washington and the Shubert
Theater in Philadelphia.
   ``We were doing what ordinarily can't be done: putting together
an engagement and a tour in less than a week. Most often, it takes
six months or a year,'' Gilman said. ``This disaster was about to
happen and I thought someone should do something.''
   The Donetsk is a lesser-known but well-regarded classical company
from the Ukraine with 59 dancers, most under age 25, plus a handful
of support staff.
   The first performance was Feb. 2 in Baltimore on a tour that was
also to include Columbus, Ohio; Detroit; Chicago; Kansas City, Mo.;
and other cities.
   Disaster struck Feb. 5 when the California-based promoter, Heart
of Art, announced that Californian and Mexican investors had
withheld $200,000 because dancers from better-known companies like
the Kirov Ballet couldn't leave their country to join the tour, as
promised.
   ``I was totally broken _ like a bird that had flown into an
obstacle,'' said the 24-year-old Pisarev.
   Members of the company feared that if they were sent home after
only five performances in Baltimore, the tour would be construed as
an artistic rather than a managerial failure.
   Robert M. Pomory, president of the Lyric Opera House in
Baltimore, donated daily rehearsal space and paid for hotels and
meals while the troupe was in limbo. A benefit performance Feb. 8
brought in $4,200. A Baltimore hospital donated its services after
dancer Alexander Boytsov, 36, broke his foot.
   Gilman stepped in to revive the tour on Feb. 9.
   Wednesday's debut attracted nearly a full house that included
many well-known faces, among them actresses Joanne Woodward and
Isabella Rossellini.
   ``The audience gave us the kind of welcome and applause we had
not experienced before,'' Pisarev's wife, prima ballerina Inna
Dorofeyeva, 22, said in her native Ukrainian. ``They applauded for
10 minutes. We were so pleased.''
   ``We were very nervous. How could we not be. It was our first
time in New York,'' Pisarev said.
   To those who helped turned things around for the troupe, Pisarev
added in his limited English: ``Thank you very much.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
