<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-23 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Hit Another Record High, Dollar Down Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index closed
today at a record high for the second consecutive day, while the
U.S. dollar declined against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 140.56 points, or 0.44
percent, closing at 32,452.49. The index had gained 331.85 points
for a record 32,311.93-point close Wednesday.
   In early trading, the index fell slightly, in part because of a
sharp overnight drop in the Dow Jones industrial average in New
York, said a dealer with Nomura Securities in Tokyo. The Dow fell
42.50 points to 2,283.83, the biggest drop since Nov. 11, when the
index shed 47.66 points.
   But the Nikkei soon began to rise and continued upward amid
expectations for a consistent rise in the Tokyo index, the dealer
added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Because today is the first day for March accounts, market
players were very motivated to buy,'' he said. Share prices usually
rise in March as securities firms try to boost sales before the new
business year starts in April.
   Even on the eve of Emperor Hirohito's state funeral, trading was
heavy, he said. An estimated 2 billion shares were traded on the
first section, where auto and electrical shares were among gainers.
   ``Since economic factors, including foreign exchange rates, are
stable now, nobody was afraid of buying issues before the three-day
weekend,'' he said.
   Friday has been declared a public holiday for the emperor's
funeral.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 126.29 yen, down 0.33
yen from Wednesday's close of 126.62 yen. After opening at 126.13
yen, the dollar ranged between 126.10 yen and 126.37 yen.
   The dollar's slip in early trading followed a similar trend in
New York overnight. The dealers said the dollar was affected by a
rise in a U.S. consumer prices and a remark by Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan that he was disturbed by inflation's
strength, dealers said.
   The Labor Department reported Wednesday that U.S. consumer prices
rose at an annual rate of 7.2 percent in January, fueled by higher
costs for gasoline, poultry, fish, eggs and tobacco.
   Greenspan, in his second day of testimony before the House
Banking Committee, said Wednesday that the Federal Reserve is
determined to resist any rise in inflation this year.
   But Ichiro Ikeda, a trader with Chemical Bank, said trading in
Tokyo was inactive as market players remained on the sidelines ahead
of the three-day weekend.
   ``The dollar moved very little against the yen because there were
no incentives to create a market trend,'' he said.
</TEXT>
