<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-JobAction     02-23 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Job Action,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Traffic Controllers Demand Wage Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 350 air traffic controllers in Moscow have
been refusing their salaries for more than two months to protest low
wages and outdated equipment, Soviet media reported.
   Initially, all 550 controllers at Moscow's central flight control
installation were involved in the protest, but 200 gave up because,
as the Tass news agency said, ``it is not easy to live without
getting any salary.''
   The official news agency, citing an article in Literaturnaya
Gazeta, said Wednesday that the controllers want the government to
modernize control towers and buy new radar equipment.
   It said they want to know what is being done with $56 million in
hard currency they earn the government annually by directing foreign
aircraft to Soviet airports.
   The controllers emphasized that they are not on strike, but are
carrying out a job action to embarrass aviation authorities into
agreeing to raise their pay and upgrade their equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ThatBook     02-23 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-That Book,0897</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Lyrical, Satirical _ And Bewildering _ `Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie's ``Satanic Verses'' is a dizzying
547-page journey through countless plots, subplots, satire and
philosophical discussions.
   It also is That Book, the work that has so enraged the Islamic
world that the author has been condemned to death. The controversy
has revived age-old questions of censorship and freedom of religion.
   Lyrical, scathing, inquisitive and at times bewildering, the
novel deals with preconceptions of good and evil, Britain's
treatment of illegal aliens, the desire by Indians to become
assimilated into British culture and, most notably, the birth of the
Islamic faith.
   Rushdie, a 41-year-old Bombay native of Moslem parents, writes in
a stream-of-consciousness style that leaves the reader alternately
exhilarated, bewildered and _ depending on one's religious and
political orientation _ outraged.
   The novel has been condemned by Moslems for its dream sequences
that portray the prophet Mohammed as a womanizer, a coward willing
to compromise his faith for general acceptance and a conniving
businessman who makes up laws to suit his own purposes.
   It also contains a sequence in which a Persian scribe alters the
holy laws as dictated by Mohammed, who is referred to in the book as
Mahound.
   Moslems revere Mohammed as the prophet who brought them Allah's
revelations in the Koran, the holy book of Islam.
   The book prompted Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini to put a
price on the author's life, sending Rushdie into hiding, along with
his wife.
   ``The Satanic Verses'' begins with terrorists blowing up a jet en
route to London. Two passengers _ Gibreel Farishta, an Indian actor
who specializes in religious roles, and Saladin Chamcha, a British
radio star able to reproduce a myriad of voices _ fall from the
plane and survive. Rushdie writes:
   ```To be born again,' sang Gibreel Farishta tumbling from the
heavens, `first you have to die. Ho ji! Ho ji! To land upon the
bosomy earth, first one needs to fly. Tat-taa! Taka-thun! How to
ever smile again, if first you won't cry? How to win the darling's
love, mister, without a sigh? Baba, if you want to get born again
...'''
   The two men emerge on an English coast. Gibreel begins to assume
an ``angelic glow,'' while Saladin grows horns and hooves and is
arrested as an illegal immigrant.
   The novel's turning point comes when Gibreel, whose halo dazzles
police, denies to authorities that he knows Saladin. By having
Gibreel commit an evil act wearing a halo and subjecting Saladin to
the brutal treatment of the English police, Rushdie confounds
reality. Which one is evil? Which one is good?
   The book's second, fourth and sixth chapters, ``Mahound,''
``Ayesha'' and ``Return to Jahilia,'' contain the most controversial
elements.
   Gibreel dreams about the city of Jahilia, built entirely of sand.
One of Jahilia's citizens is Mahound, a
``businessman-turned-prophet'' who is starting a new religion.
Unfortunately for Mahound, the city already has 360 gods and little
use for more.
   Mahound's chance for recognition comes when the head of the
city's ruling council proposes a deal: If Mahound's Allah (the
Islamic god) will accept three of the local gods (Lat, Uzza and
Manat) as archangels in his sect, his religion will receive
certification and Mahound will have a seat on the council.
   Mahound, always the practical businessman, sees the deal as a
good opportunity to attract converts. So he climbs a mountain to
consult with the archangel, none other than Gibreel himself. Rashdie
writes of Mahound's moral dilemma:
   ```The souls of the city, of the world, surely they are worth
three more angels? Is Allah so unbending that he will not embrace
three more to save the human race?''
   Although he does not actually hear an answer, Mahound undergoes
what he considers a revelation in the archangel's presence,
believing he should make the deal.
   But he soon learns that the supposedly divine message did not
come from Gibreel but the Devil, who had been impersonating the
archangel. Mahound renounces the satanic ``verses'' and substitutes
these words, which closely follow the spirit of the actual Koran,
about Lat, Uzza and Manat:
   ``They are but names you have dreamed of, you and your fathers.
Allah invests no authority in them.''
   Rushdie takes the story a step further by having Gibreel claim
that both answers came from him, blurring the distinction between
God and Satan.
   Mahound and his followers eventually settle in the ``friendly
oasis'' of Yathrib, just as Mohammed journeyed from Mecca to Medina.
In Yathrib, Mahound proceeds to dictate to the Persian scribe Salman
the rules of the new religion as proscribed by Gibreel.
   However, Salman becomes convinced that Mahound is making up the
rules himself and decides to test his leader by deliberately
changing what is recited to him. The scribe, fearing for his life if
Mahound discovers his trick, flees Yathrib and concludes his part of
the story by stating, ``It's his Word against mine.''
   Rushdie has said his characters ``seek to become fully human by
facing up to the great facts of love, death and (with or without
God), the life of the soul. Outside it, the forces of humanity are
on the march.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Grammys-TV     02-23 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grammys-TV,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Don't Worry, Be Happy' Somewhere Else, Please</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Grammys, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is musical variety dead on network television? If
you really want to know, just ask anyone who watched ``The 31st
Annual Grammy Awards'' _ assuming you can wake them up.
   ``Don't Worry, Be Happy,'' a smile button of a song that
apparently represents the cutting edge of current Western musical
culture, seemed to be the theme of an abnormally dull awards program
Wednesday night. But for viewers of the three-plus hours on CBS, the
operative lyric might have been Tracy Chapman's ``You've got a fast
car, I want a ticket to anywhere.''
   It looked at first as if Chapman might walk off with the show,
but quiet thoughtfulness was not the order of the night, and the
sequin-bedecked proceeding clearly was not her scene. She quietly
accepted her Grammys and ducked off stage, coming back later to sing
her hymn of dead-end poverty, ``Fast Car,'' in front of a crowd
whose aggregate wardrobe pricetags probably equalled the gross
national product of any three Third World nations.
   The show was enlivened only occasionally by performances from
Chapman, Sinead O'Connor, Toni Childs and Melissa Etheridge who
apparently didn't know better than to care.
   Otherwise, it was snore city, though you couldn't tell from the
glitterati, who, perhaps sated with sponsor Pepsi's product, gave
standing ovations at every opportunity, regardless of whether they'd
been regaled by Whitney Houston or Itzhak Perlman.
   Maybe it's something in the water out there in L.A. At least last
year in New York, there was a little creative tension in the air.
Remember Little Richard taking the show hostage when it suddenly
occurred to him, hey, I practically invented rock 'n' roll and I
never got a Grammy? They stuck him in the audience this time around.
   It was also last year that Michael Jackson showed up to rivet the
crowd with his performance.
   If they're going to insist upon televising this thing, somebody
better give the academy some plot advice. Don't put O'Connor,
Etheridge and Childs on stage to sing their hearts out, then give
the award to Tina Turner who wasn't even there.
   Do, however, have venerable old-timers show up kids, and that's
just what lifetime achievement award winners Leontyne Price, Dizzy
Gillespie and Sarah Vaughan did. You won't see this on MTV.
   It was just so hard to pick a trend for the night from the many
possibilities. Perhaps ``Blind Date from Hell.'' The producers
seemed to delight in pairing bizarre presenter couples, such as Kris
Kristofferson and Minnie Pearl, Henry Mancini and Olivia Newton-John
or Steve Winwood and Randy Travis, all of whom had the good sense
not to try to talk to each other.
   But ``Don't Worry, Be Happy,'' Bobby McFerrin's mindless _ and of
course highly honored song _ did so nicely set off the evening's
too-tired-to-reach-for-the-remote-control sensibility.
   McFerrin was charming, however, when he teamed with host Billy
Crystal on an amusing ``history of music'' that thankfully took up
several minutes of the tedious show. Blues and gospel begat soul,
said Crystal, ``which begat the cover and two-drink minimum.''
   Crystal, for his part, better watch it or he will be that which
he satires. After three years as host of the show, he's becoming
rather smug. Still, he showed himself a pro by turning a faulty
sound system into a routine, and he dished one-liners as if he meant
it. He also dusted off the ol' Sammy Davis Jr. impression to great
effect on Chapman's ``Fast Car.''
   The Grammy Awards do provide something of a smattering of musical
updating for network audiences who might have missed George
Michael's latest or haven't had the pleasure of being exposed to the
smoke, hair and leather of Metallica. The network mandate, after
all, IS public service. And now, thankfully, we're all caught up
until next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
