<FIRST>r a PM-Grammys-Dixon     02-23 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grammys-Dixon,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Master Bluesman Willie Dixon Finally Wins a Grammy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Grammys, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE M. PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was, as Willie Dixon put it, about time.
   The 73-year-old blues master won his first Grammy from the
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences on Wednesday for the
album ``Hidden Charms,'' which was named best traditional blues
recording.
   Dixon, whose songs have been recorded by the Rolling Stones, Led
Zeppelin, the Doors and many others, was given a standing ovation as
he went to the Shrine Auditorium stage, aided by a cane, to receive
the coveted trophy.
   ``I've been in the music business for 50 years. It's about time,
don't you think?'' said Dixon in his trademark raspy voice. ``Better
late than never.''
   Promoting the blues has been his whole career, Dixon said, and
now he had something to show for it.
   ``I give in and I give out but I never give up,'' he said.
   Dixon had been nominated four times previously and never won.
   Songs written by Dixon include ``I'm Your Hoochie Coochie Man,''
``I Can't Quit You Baby'' and ``Built for Comfort.''
   The Rolling Stones recorded his ``Little Red Rooster'' and ``I
Want to be Loved,'' and Rod Stewart performed his ``Good Morning,
Little Schoolgirl.''
   The Doors recorded ``Back Door Man,'' and Cream had a hit with
Dixon's ``Spoonful.''
   One of 14 children, Dixon was born in Vicksburg, Miss. and raised
in both Vicksburg and Chicago. He won the Golden Gloves amateur
heavyweight boxing title as James Dixon in 1936, then became a
professional musician based in Chicago the next year.
   Among other blues giants Dixon played with or wrote for during
his long career were Elmore James, Otis Rush, and Memphis Slim. He
also worked as an artist and repertoire man, producer and writer for
Chess Records in the early 1950s.
   Dixon's competitors for the Grammy were Johnny Copeland for
``Ain't Nothing But a Party,'' James Cotton for ``Live at Antone's
Nightclub,'' Rockin' Dopsie for ``Saturday Night Zydeco'' and Guitar
Slim Jr. for ``The Story of My Life.''
</TEXT>
