<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0532EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DuBoisBirthday     02-23 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Du Bois Birthday,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Hopes To Make Black Pioneer's Home a Memorial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All that remains of civil rights
pioneer W.E.B. Du Bois' childhood home is ``a cellar hole'' marked
by a plaque, but a group meeting on his 121st birthday today wants a
more prominent tribute.
   ``It is in stark contrast to Paul Revere's house, Faneuil Hall in
Boston and other places that are national landmarks,'' said Robert
Paynter, a University of Massachusetts archaeologist excavating the
homestead.
   At a university luncheon commemorating Du Bois' birthday, state
Secretary of Economic Affairs Grady Hedgespeth was to announce a
study for a memorial at the plot of land, which has been listed with
the National Register of Historic Places.
   Du Bois, a social scientist, helped found the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People and is revered in
Africa as the father of black nations.
   School officials said the state has promised a grant to study
ways to create a bigger tribute to him. The memorial would be at the
site of Du Bois' childhood home in Great Barrington, which today is
``a cellar hole in the woods,'' Paynter said.
   Scholars have long lamented the lack of homage paid to the man
who laid the foundation for Pan-Africanism and planted the seeds for
the independent African nations that sprang up in the 1960s.
   ``The irony is that he is better known internationally than in
America,'' said university Afro-American studies Professor William
Strickland.
   Du Bois spent his final years in Ghana, which has turned his
bungalow into a national shrine. Among guests scheduled to attend
today's birthday luncheon was Victor Gbeho, Ghana's missionary to
the United Nations.
   For four years after his birth in 1868, Du Bois lived in the
Great Barrington house, which archeologists believe had been in his
mother's family for a century. The long history of the black
Burghardt clan from which Du Bois is descended is lovingly detailed
in his autobiographies.
   The house was purchased by friends as a 60th birthday gift in
1928, and Du Bois used it as a summer retreat for more than 25
years. He sold it because of financial and political pressures.
   He had been under government surveillance since 1919 for his
writings on black rights, and in the 1950s his passport was taken
away. Embittered, he toured Eastern Bloc capitals, and in 1961 he
moved to Ghana and applied for membership in the Communist Party.
   The University of Massachusetts arranged for the state to buy the
homestead last year.
   Du Bois admirers bought the property after his death in 1963 and
wanted to preserve it as a memorial, but their efforts were met with
hostility. A 1968 memorial observation there was opposed by veterans
groups and the local Knights of Columbus because of Du Bois'
politics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
