<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Peace     02-23 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Peace,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warring Cambodian Factions Looking To Beijing-Moscow Parley</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP New Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The formidable task of ending 10 years
of jungle war in Cambodia moves on to other arenas, including the
first Sino-Soviet summit in 30 years, now that peace talks held in
this country have broken up without new agreements.
   Despite the bare results at Jakarta this week, attempts at
rapprochment by the United States, China and the Soviet Union and
unprecedented recent dialogue among the warring Cambodian factions
have created momentum toward peace.
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach of Vietnam said it was ``like
the last 15 minutes of a football (soccer) match, with everyone
trying to score a point.''
   Prince Norodom Ranariddh, a leader of guerrillas fighting
Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia, said the Jakarta meeting had been
destined to fail because settlement lies with two countries that did
not attend _ the Soviet Union, which arms Vietnam, and China, which
arms the guerrillas.
   The Cambodian conflict is likely to top the agenda when Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev meets Chinese leaders in Beijing on
May 15-18 in the Communist giants first summit in three decades.
   The two nations have declared their commitment to settling the
major conflict blocking normalization of their relations.
   Indeed, officials fear Moscow and Beijing might rush into an
agreement that, as in Afghanistan, would wash their own hands but
leave basic internal conflicts unresolved and condemn Cambodia to
even more chaotic civil war.
   Last year, the two powers held their first talks solely on the
Cambodia issue. Then in December, China's Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen discussed it in Moscow in the first visit by a top Chinese
official there in 31 years.
   In February, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze made his
country's highest-level visit to China in three decades to set the
date for the summit.
   During the Shevardnadze visit, the two countries reached broad
agreement on many aspects of the Cambodian problem. But a joint
statement also cited their differences over what is also the major
disagreement between the respective Cambodian adversaries they
support.
   Beijing came out in support of the guerrillas' call for formation
of a provisional coalition government that would comprise the three
guerrilla groups and the pro-Vietnamese Cambodian government.
   But Moscow backed the Phnom Penh government's offer of a
four-party provisional body that apparently would be charged only
with implementing a peace agreement and organizing a general
election.
   Persistent but unconfirmable reports say the Soviets _ seeking
better relations with China and the non-communist Southeast Asian
nations and an end to costly foreign military involvements _ have
been pressuring Vietnam for a speedier withdrawal and peace talks.
   More obvious have been signs of increased albeit limited Chinese
flexibility in the past year or so.
   Most importantly, Beijing finally has joined the international
community in publicly declaring its opposition to a return to power
of its main guerrilla ally, the Khmer Rouge.
   China's once unequivocal support for the group _ which murdered
hundreds of thousands of people when it ruled Cambodia from 1975
until Vietnam's late 1978 invasion _ had blocked peace efforts for
years.
   After a decade of dismissing all Vietnamese attempts at
high-level dialogue, Beijing held talks on Cambodia in January with
Vietnam's First Deputy Foreign Minister Dinh Nho Liem. The parties
informally agreed that Vietnam would withdraw its troops by
September in exchange for an end to Chinese aid to the guerrillas.
   There is the prospect of a meeting soon between the Chinese and
Vietnamese foreign ministers.
   The United States, which provides the resistance with diplomatic
support and non-lethal aid, also has been more active in discussing
ways to settle the conflict in talks with the Soviet Union and with
China.
   President Bush is expected to discuss the issue when he visits
China this weekend. A group of 31 U.S. congressmen has written Bush
a letter asking that he urge the Chinese to halt aid to the Khmer
Rouge.
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, a signatory and the influential chairman
of the House subcommittee on Asian affairs, calls blocking a Khmer
Rouge return ``one of the major political and moral challenges'' of
the new administration.
   The Chinese in turn may press Washington to increase aid to the
non-communist guerrilla groups, the forces of Prince Norodom
Sihanouk and of Son Sann.
   A statement from participants at the Jakarta talks urged the
Cambodian factions to engage in dialogue until the next such talks
can be arranged.
   Their antagonism in Jakarta, however, has dimmed prospects that
the Cambodians will make progress in talks among themselves. Three
rounds of talks between the principal leaders of the two sides,
Sihanouk and Premier Hun Sen of the pro-Vietnamese government, have
sharpened mutual recriminations.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Peter Eng has been based in Bangkok for five years
and has made frequent trips to Indochina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
