<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AirForceCrash     02-23 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Force Crash,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official: Crashed Plane Was Coming in Without Radar Assist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HURLBURT FIELD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of an Air Force cargo jet
that crashed, killing all eight people on board, was trying to land
in stormy weather without ground-radar assistance, an official said.
   The C-141B Starlifter from Norton Air Force Base, Calif., went
down Monday night amid heavy thunderstorms about four miles short of
Hurlburt Field's main runway in Florida's panhandle.
   Officials have not determined the cause of the crash, but
Hurlburt spokeswoman Victoria Hanson said the pilot was relying on
cockpit instruments. Ground radar is the favored method in bad
weather.
   A team of safety investigators arrived Wednesday at the crash
site in a heavily wooded swamp on neighboring Eglin Air Force Base's
military reservation about 40 miles east of Pensacola. Ms. Hanson
said a final report could take three to four months.
   Searchers, meanwhile, found two more bodies Wednesday. The
remains of four people were discovered Tuesday, and the search for
the final two bodies was to continue today. The remains were taken
to Eglin for identification.
   The crash site was on a remote portion of Eglin's 720-square-mile
military reservation used for weapons testing and maneuvers.
   The four-engine transport had departed Monday morning from Norton
and stopped in Colorado Springs, Colo., en route to Hurlburt. It had
a crew of seven and had picked up a passenger, retired Air Force
Capt. John G. Galvin of Jacksonville, during the refueling stop in
Colorado, Ms. Hanson said.
   The crew members were identified as Capt. Mark J. Chambers, 30;
Capt. John F. Young, 30; Master Sgt. Robert E. Wright Jr., 37; Tech.
Sgt. Ronald D. Grubbs, 29; Staff Sgt. Karl M. Kohler, 32; Airman 1st
Class Scott Craig, 22, and Staff Sgt. John W. Remerscheid, 33.
</TEXT>
