<DOCNO> AP890223-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-QuakeVictim     02-23 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake Victim,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Armenian Earthquake Victims Leaving Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old Armenian girl whose forehead was
crushed in the devastating earthquake that shook the Soviet republic
has been released from a hospital after reconstructive surgery made
possible through a U.S. program.
   Gayane Gasparian, one of four children being treated at
Massachusetts General Hospital, was released Wednesday and joined
her mother at an apartment paid for by the city.
   The lanky, dark-haired girl was among 37 children and their
guardians flown in Feb. 9 by the Virginia-based organization Project
HOPE after the Dec. 7 earthquake in which 25,000 people were killed
and 500,000 were left homeless.
   ``At least 10 are outpatients now and many more are slowly coming
out,'' said Martha Desrosiers, the organization's director of
humanitarian assistance. ``In general, they are all adapted and
happy. Some of them are still frightened, but some are speaking
English.''
   Miss Gasparian's surgery was a week ago, and Dr. Michael
Yaremchuk said the girl will spend several days recuperating before
beginning a series of operations on her hand, which was also smashed.
   He said it was unlikely any of the other three children under
treatment in Boston would be released soon.
   ``Their spirits are good but they all have very difficult
problems,'' Yaremchuk said. ``Our reconstructive efforts won't bring
them back to normal but we can approach that as our goal.''
   Many of the reconstructive operations were complicated by the
delay in treatment following the disaster, Yaremchuk said.
   ``If a similar injury had occurred in the United States, the
reconstruction would have been as soon as possible after the
accident,'' he said. ``But the priorities are different in a crisis
situation.''
   The other children were treated at hospitals in Illinois,
Pennsylvania, Virginia, New York, Florida and Ohio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
