<DOCNO> AP890223-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BombDetector     02-23 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bomb Detector,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami Airport Installs Bomb-Exploding Detector</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miami International Airport has joined several other
major U.S. airports in installing an anti-terrorism device capable
of detecting bombs similar to the one that destroyed Pan Am Flight
103, an airport spokesman said.
   The $770,000 decompression chamber guards against barometric
bombs, detonated by pressure changes at high altitudes, said airport
spokesman Chris Mangos. It is the first such device to be installed
in Florida, he said.
   If such a bomb is hidden in the cargo or luggage, it will explode
within the thick concrete walls of the chamber, Mangos said
Wednesday.
   Miami International officials built the narrow 89-foot-long
chamber at the insistence of Israel's El Al Airlines, known for its
strict security measures.
   Los Angeles International Airport, O'Hare International Airport
in Chicago and New York's John F. Kennedy Airport, all serviced by
El Al flights, already have decompression chambers.
   ``Our utmost concern is to take care of our customers and make
sure they are safe and sound in our planes,'' said David Shein, El
Al's general manager for North and Central America.
   El Al said it may double its cargo business out of Miami, but had
agreed to proceed with expansion plans only if the chamber was
installed to deal with security threats, Shein said.
   Investigators think a barometric bomb was used to blow up Pan Am
Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December, killing all 259
people on board and 11 on the ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0064 </DOCNO>
