<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major currencies in
early European trading today as expectations of higher U.S. interest
rates receded, dealers said. Gold prices were higher.
   Traders said the dollar's gradual decline in recent days
reflected a growing belief that the U.S. Federal Reserve Board will
not raise interest rates.
   Higher interest rates would make the dollar a more attractive
investment.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.33 Japanese yen to a closing 126.29 yen. Later, in
London, it fell further to 125.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8252 West German marks, down from 1.8380
   _1.5565 Swiss francs, down from 1.5667
   _6.2295 French francs, down from 6.2625
   _2.0625 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0725
   _1,344.75 Italian lire, down from 1,350.50
   _1.1940 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1965
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7565 from $1.7465 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $388 a troy ounce, up
from $386.30 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $389.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $389.15, up from $386.25 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.99 to close at a bid $389.50.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.97 a
troy ounce, unchanged from Wednesday's late bid.
