<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-Hirohito     02-23 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Hirohito,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Bows To Pressure From War Veterans On Lowering Flag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outraged war veterans forced the
government to back down today on its decision to fly the national
flag at half-staff over the Australian War Memorial during Friday's
funeral in Japan for Emperor Hirohito.
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke intervened after a wave of protest from
war veterans, who inundated radio talk shows with protests of plans
to lower the flag on all government buildings in respect for the
late emperor.
   Hawke said he was aware of the sensitivities of war veterans and
their families and agreed to exempt the War Memorial, which
commemorates all Australians who died in wars.
   ``It's an affront to all those who were killed fighting the
Japanese, to all ex-POWs of the Japanese who were brutally treated
and tortured, and to their widows,'' said Brig. Alf Garland,
president of the Returned Services League, representing some 300,000
veterans of World War II and Vietnam.
   ``It is clear to me that the government is completely out of
touch with public opinion and puts trading relationships with Japan
ahead of the feelings of Australian veterans and war widows,''
Garland said before Hawke intervened.
   The row surfaced as Australia's new Governor-General, Bill
Hayden, flew to Japan to join other foreign dignitaries for the
funeral.
   Many Australians regard Hirohito, who died Jan. 7 at age 87, as
an unrepentant war criminal who died without explaining his war-time
role.
   A government spokesman said flags always are lowered at half-mast
in recognition of any head of state who dies in a country with which
Australia has full diplomatic relations.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that in
recent years flags have been lowered in Australia for three Soviet
leaders and the president of Vietnam.
</TEXT>
