<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-S&amp;Ls-TwinsAccused     02-23 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-Twins Accused,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Twins Accused in Alleged Multimillion-Dollar S&amp;L Regulatory
Scam</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-S&amp;L-Hiring Crooks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They looked out of place as they sat on a hard,
government-issue wood bench in a federal courtroom alongside drug
peddlers and Social Security thieves.
   Tall and trim, the twin brothers in the European gray suits and
silver handcuffs sat in identical positions, right leg slung over
left knee, as they awaited their arraignment on fraud charges.
   Philip and Thomas Noons had been arrested with the FBI and
charged with conspiring to embezzle money from the Federal Savings &amp;
Loan Insurance Corp., for which Philip Noons worked.
   Noons is one of hundreds of officials from the troubled S&amp;L
industry hired to untangle a mess they helped to create. In the
process, officials say, they may have helped to make it worse.
   The case against the Noons brothers is part international
intrigue and part plain ol' bank robbing, prosecutors say.
   The 31-year-old twins, who are British citizens, worked for
Mainland Savings, a thrift that has been declared insolvent and has
been the object of two years' worth of FBI investigation.
   When Mainland failed in 1986, Philip Noons went to work at the
FSLIC, trying to sell all the bad Mainland assets the government
suddenly had inherited.
   Thomas Noons went to work for a real estate firm that had a
contract with FSLIC to dispose of Mainland property.
   They even helped the FBI in its investigation of Mainland.
   On Feb. 8, the same FBI agent who had worked with the two
arrested them on charges of conspiring to embezzle money from the
FSLIC by grossly undervaluing Mainland loans and then selling them
to two Houston companies on behalf of themselves.
   One package of 16 loans was valued by Philip Noons at $1,500 and
sold for $50,000, allegedly with money diverted from another
transaction handled by Noons, prosecutors said. The FSLIC said the
package is actually worth $1.6 million, not $1,500.
   In another case, the brothers allegedly paid $692,821 for a loan
on a shopping center, the FBI said. That loan, which was up-to-date
on its payments, was really worth $4 million, the government
charged. The money to buy it came from a mysterious account in
Britain's Channel Islands called the Unicorn Trust, the FBI said,
and was sent through the Cayman Islands, making it harder to trace.
   Although charged and released on bail, the Noons brothers have
yet to be indicted. The FBI had them arrested out of concern they
might flee the country.
   The case is just ``one facet broken off that (Mainland)
investigation,'' said assistant U.S. Attorney John Braddock, who has
spent two years on Mainland and anticipates at least two more.
   The brothers' attorney, David Berg, says his clients are
innocent, and that the government has overreacted.
   Berg said some FSLIC employees who helped build the case against
the twins were simply being vindictive, that Philip Noons helped the
government get a good price for the loans, and that the case rests
on only ``the thinnest reed of evidence.''
   ``I really think these guys are being victimized by ex-employees
at Mainland,'' the attorney said. ``And I think there is a great cry
and hue to expose S&amp;L scandal and so we got this rush to judgment. I
think the government simply jumped the gun on this one.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Scott McCartney is the AP Southwest regional
reporter, based in Dallas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
