<SECOND>PM-Germany-Verses,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>German-Language Edition of `The Satanic Verses' To be Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOGNE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reversing itself, a prominent
publishing house said today it will publish the German-language
edition of ``The Satanic Verses,'' whose author is the target of an
Iranian assassination order.
   The Kiepenheuer und Witsch publishing house of Cologne said
Salman Rushdie's novel, which many Moslems consider blasphemous,
will appear some time in the fall after it is translated from the
English.
   The publishing house last week said it would not publish the
novel because it feared reprisals against its employees. But the
union of West German writers and other cultural institutions
appealed for the book to be published, saying free speech should not
be compromised by terrorist threats.
   Though Kiepenheuer und Witsch owns the German-language rights to
``The Satanic Verses,'' brief excerpts from the book have been
appearing in the leftist West Berlin newspaper Tageszeitung.
   A spokesman for the Union of West German Publishers, Klaus Kluge,
said the newspaper's move was unauthorized and could result in legal
action by Kiepenheuer und Witsch.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's fundamentalist patriarch,
nine days ago ordered Moslems to seek out and kille Rushdie and the
book's publishers.
   Several Iranian clerics have since put a price on the head of the
British author, who was born to a Moslem family in India and is now
in hiding.
</TEXT>
