<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Jacuzzi 1stLd-Writethru a0509 02-23 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Jacuzzi, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0509,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Chairman of Jacuzzi Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to restore Ark. to dateline; SUBS last graf to include
day of death.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aldo Joseph Jacuzzi, the head of a
family company whose whirlpool bath became a symbol of indulgence in
the 1970s, has died. He was 67.
   The chief product of the Jacuzzi Brothers Inc. became virtually
synonymous with hot tubs _ ``jacuzzi'' is listed in Webster's New
World Dictionary _ and a symbol of the Southern California lifestyle
during the disco era and into the 80s.
   In 1954, Jacuzzi Brothers developed a hydro-massage unit to treat
a relative who was an invalid. This unit developed into the
whirlpool that propelled hot-tub waters of the affluent around the
world.
   Jacuzzi Brothers was formed in 1915 when the family bought a
machine shop. Its first major product was the ``toothpick''
propeller adapted for airplanes during World War I. After developing
the nation's first cabin-style monoplane in 1920, the company
abandoned the aircraft business when a relative died testing an
airplane. The family then concentrated the development of the
Jacuzzi injector pump used to propel water in the whirlpool bath.
   Aldo Jacuzzi joined the family company in Berkeley, Calif., in
1939. He held several positions there until the international
headquarters was moved to Little Rock, Ark., in 1963.
   Jacuzzi was named vice president in charge of purchasing and held
that post until 1970 when he was appointed chairman.
   In 1979, the family sold the business to Kidde Inc. of Saddle
Brook, N.J., which was acquired in 1987 by Hanson Industries, the
United States arm of a British corporation.
   The Little Rock company continues to be operated under the name
Jacuzzi Brothers.
   Jacuzzi, who died Tuesday, is survived by his wife, Granuccia
Amadei Jacuzzi, and two sons. The funeral is Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Algeria     02-23 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Algeria,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation Votes To Open Way To Political Liberalization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RACHID KHIARI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Algerians voted today on a new
constitution that would open the way to a multi-party system,
protect civil liberties and spell the end of two decades of
socialism.
   Polling booths opened at 8 a.m. for 12 hours of voting by this
North African nation's 13 million eligible voters, who were casting
ballots for the third time in less than four months.
   Voters overwhelmingly adopted a first set of political reforms in
November, and in December they re-elected President Chadli
Bendjedid, 59, to a third five-year term.
   Bendjedid's proposal to change the constitution is the highlight
of a process of political and social reform under way since a week
of bloody riots in October.
   The unrest was largely blamed on the oil-producing nation's
struggling economy, jolted by a world oil glut and straitjacketed by
the one-party socialist state.
   While Algerian voters are expected to overwhelmingly approve the
constitution, there have been only limited public calls on its
behalf. The ruling party has remained prudently silent.
   Islamic groups have been divided over the merits of the new
document. In an interview published Wednesday in the daily Horizons
said, Ali Bel-Hadj, a leader of a fundamentalist faction, said, ``If
(ethnic) Berbers, communists and all the others have a voice,
Algeria will become a field of ideological confrontations in
contradictions with the beliefs of the Algerian people.''
   The proposed constitution does not overtly authorize competing
political parties to replace the ruling National Liberation Front,
currently the only legal political organization in this nation of 25
million people. But it does recognize ``the right to create
associations of a political character.''
   It also guarantees freedom of expression and the right to strike,
within some limits.
   The new constitution would restrict the power of the army to
defending the ``national independence, the unity and territorial
integrity of the country.''
   Under the current document, the army had a role in ``the
development of the country and the building of Socialism.''
   Also dropped is a declaration that ``the Algerian state is
socialist.'' The new text contains no reference at all to socialism.
   Islam would remain the state religion and Arabic the official
language.
   The proposed document would supercede the 1976 constitution drawn
up under Houari Boumedienne, Marxist president from 1965-78.
   For years, Bendjedid has quietly moved Algeria away from orthodox
socialism to a free market economy but has faced determined
resistance from the ruling party and the government bureaucracy.
   The October riots, in which government offices were a main
target, quickened the process. Officials said 176 people died in the
fighting, but the figure was widely considered low.
   A Nov. 3 referendum that dealt with the separation of powers
between the president, prime minister and National Assembly, or
parliament, was approved by 92 percent. Bendjedid was re-elected
Dec. 23 with 81 percent of the vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Flight103-Probe     02-23 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103-Probe,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Flight 103 Crash Probe Focuses on 30 Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators probing the explosion of Pan
Am Flight 103 have eliminated all but 25 to 30 names from the list
of passengers with baggage that could have contained the bomb, a
newspaper reported today.
   The Syracuse Post Standard reported that a U.S. official, which
it didn't identify, made the disclosure but did not name the
passengers.
   About 49 of the 259 passengers and crew members aboard the Boeing
747 that crashed into the Scottish town of Lockerbie Dec. 21 boarded
in Frankfurt, West Germany, where Flight 103 originated. All aboard
the plane were killed, as well as 11 people on the ground.
   Scottish police last week released a photograph of the bag that
contained the bomb, believed to have been hidden in a radio cassette
player. Authorities said the baggage likely originated in Frankfurt.
   Most of the luggage from Germany had been placed in an aluminum
baggage container that was loaded into the front cargo hold on the
left side of the aircraft.
   Investigators know which container carried the bomb but have not
pinpointed the suitcase. The containers hold between 40 and 50 bags.
   The newspaper's source said Scottish authorities, who are being
assisted by U.S. and German experts, have reduced the list further
through background checks and other efforts.
   In Lockerbie, Police Inspector John McLean would not comment on
the investigation.
</TEXT>
