<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BabyCalvin     02-23 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Calvin,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Infant Who Received Rare Liver-Intestine Transplant Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-month-old Florida boy who underwent a
rare liver and small intestine transplant on New Year's Eve died
from a combination of medical problems involving multiple organ
failures, officials said.
   Calvin Oliveira died Wednesday at University of Wisconsin
Hospital and Clinics, where the surgery was performed, said
spokeswoman Greer Sutter.
   Dr. Munci Kalayoglu, who performed the historic liver-intestine
transplant, said the problems were triggered by respiratory failure.
   ``He's been really sick and basically failing the last two weeks
despite everything we could think of to do for him,'' said Dr.
William Perloff, head of the hospital's intensive care unit. ``In
the last 72 hours, he took a significant turn for the worse.''
   Kalayoglu said doctors ``undertook the operation in an effort to
save Calvin's life and unfortunately we were unable to succeed
despite our best efforts.''
   Calvin, from Deerfield Beach, Fla., gained national attention
after his father, Carlos Oliveira, made a tearful plea to Florida
Gov. Bob Martinez for help in saving the boy's life.
   Money for the down payment on the operation was quickly raised
from private and corporate donors.
   Only 5 percent of Calvin's intestine worked at birth. The
intravenous feeding that kept him alive caused his liver to
deteriorate so severely by December that his only hope was the
experimental operation.
   Kalayoglu had expected Calvin to be able to use the new intestine
and go off intravenous feeding a few weeks after the operation, but
a mysterious lung ailment developed.
   Kalayoglu said Calvin had been the only survivor of five children
who underwent the operation.
</TEXT>
