<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Flight103     02-23 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight 103 Relatives Blame Government For Not Issuing Warning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives and friends of Britons who died aboard
Pan Am Flight 103 demanded today that Transport Secretary Paul
Channon resign for failing to alert airport authorities to a bomb
threat against the airline.
   In a letter published in The Independent newspaper, they urged
Channon to ``accept ministerial responsibility'' for failing to pass
on to London's Heathrow Airport a bomb threat reported by U.S.
authorities.
   ``His resignation will not bring back the people we have lost,''
the 22 signatories said. ``It will, however, ease our sense of
betrayal at the actions and omissions of our government.''
   The New York-bound Boeing 747 jet blew up over the Scottish
village of Lockerbie on Dec. 21, killing all 259 people aboard and
11 on the ground.
   Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt with a Boeing 727 but
passengers and baggage were transferred to the doomed jumbo jet at
Heathrow.
   The Independent reported last week that Channon's department
received 16 security bulletins last year from the U.S. Federal
Aviation Administration.
   The letter said Channon had given the impression in Parliament
and to the media that the bomb threat against Pan Am ``was one of
such a large number of warnings and, in terms of quality, was so
insignificant, that he saw no need to inform'' Heathrow Airport.
   ``We have since learned that the Americans issue only a small
number of bulletins, and that they considered the bulletin in
question to be one of the most specific to be passed on to the
British government,'' the letter said.
   ``We have been further angered by the fact that the same
information led to the authorities at Frankfurt doubling their own
security,'' it said.
   The State Department said an unidentified person telephoned the
U.S. Embassy in Helsinki, Finland, on Dec. 5 and said an attempt
would be made that month to bomb a Pan Am aircraft flying from
Frankfurt, West Germany, to the United States. The FAA notified the
British government.
   The government said it took no action because it believed
security at British airports was already strict enough.
   British police said last week the bomb was hidden in a
radio-cassette player and probably was loaded onto the plane in
Frankfurt. German police say there is no evidence for such a
conclusion.
</TEXT>
