<FIRST>r a PM-StolenCarScam     02-23 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stolen Car Scam,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thief Drives Off With Former Police Chief's Porsche</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car thief posing as a car buyer got what he went
after, but he probably didn't know who his victim was.
   Don Byrd, former Dallas police chief and Dallas County sheriff,
says the man got away with a white Porsche 944 Turbo valued at
$26,500.
   Byrd said Wednesday the thief responded to a newspaper ad, came
by and inspected his car and asked for a test drive.
   ``My stepson took him for a test drive, and they came back OK,''
Byrd said.
   He said the man then asked to have the car checked by a mechanic.
Byrd sent his house man to accompany the phony buyer to a Porsche
dealership.
   At the dealership, the house man got out of the car, and when the
mechanic opened the garage door to let the man drive the car inside,
the thief shifted into action.
   ``Instead of driving it forward into the garage, he put it in
reverse, backed to the street and drove away,'' Byrd said.
   It didn't even do the former lawman any good to have the man's
car at his home while the theft was taking place. That car turned
out to have been stolen in suburban Irving, Byrd said.
</TEXT>
