<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-DurableGoods     02-23 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Durable Goods,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Orders for Druable Goods Down 3 Percent in January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to factories for ``big ticket'' durable
goods declined 3 percent in January, the first decrease in four
months and the biggest drop since last July, the government report
today.
   The Commerce Department said demand for durable goods, items
expected to last three or more years, totaled a seasonally adjusted
$128.06 billion in January, down from $132.06 billion in December.
   Orders in virtually all major industry categories were down,
particularly in the volatile transportation and defense categories.
   Much of last month's decline was due to a 7.2 percent fallback in
transportation orders, which had surged 22.1 percent in December due
to high demand for aircraft and autos.
   Excluding transportation, orders in all other categories were
down 1.2 percent last month.
   Overall, orders had been up a robust 7.3 percent in December, the
biggest increase since last June. Orders for all of 1988 had been up
10.9 percent from 1987, the best showing since 1984, as
manufacturers enjoyed an export-fueled rebound thanks to the decline
of the dollar against foreign currencies.
   January's 3 percent decrease was the biggest decline since a 7.4
percent drop last July and the first drop since a 2.8 percent
decrease in September.
   Orders in the erratic defense category, subject to wide swings
depending on when government contracts are signed, plunged 33.5
percent in January after a 24.2 percent increase in December.
   Excluding defense, all other orders were down 0.4 percent after
rising 6.1 percent in December.
   Orders in the key category of non-defense capital goods,
considered a good sign of business intentions to modernize and
expand, were up 1.5 percent to $39.96 billion last month. The
category had increased 9.9 percent in December.
   In other industries, orders for primary metals were down 1.2
percent after a 4.4 percent jump in December.
   Orders for non-electrical machinery were down 0.8 percent after a
1.1 percent increase, and orders for electrical machinery were down
2.3 percent after falling 1 percent in December.
   Shipments of durable goods were unchanged in January at $124.18
billion, following a 3.5 percent increase in December.
</TEXT>
