<FIRST>r a PM-MultipleKillings     02-23 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Killings,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simmons Won't Appeal Second Death Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R. Gene Simmons, sentenced to death
after being convicted of killing 14 family members, will not appeal
the sentence, one of his attorneys said.
   ``I talked to Mr. Simmons this morning and he said he has no
desire to appeal this case,'' attorney John Harris said Wednesday.
   Authorities discovered the bodies of Simmons' wife, seven
children, two of the children's spouses and four grandchildren in
and around Simmons' Pope County home on Dec. 28 and 29, 1987.
   Harris said a hearing was scheduled this afternoon for Johnson
County Circuit Judge John S. Patterson to determine whether Simmons
``knowingly and intelligently decided to waive his right to all
appeals.''
   A jury convicted Simmons, 48, in the slayings Feb. 10 and then
sentenced him to death. Patterson set March 16 as the date for
Simmons to die by lethal injection.
   It was the second death sentence for Simmons. He received the
first one last year after a Franklin County Circuit Court jury
convicted him in the shooting deaths of two Russellville residents
in December 1987. The deaths were part of a crosstown shooting
rampage that preceded the discovery of the bodies at Simmons' home.
   Simmons also said after the first conviction that he did not want
to appeal.
   The Rev. Louis J. Franz, chairman of Arkansas Churches for Life,
who argues that appeals should be mandatory in all capital cases,
has intervened in the case.
   Both the Arkansas Supreme Court and U.S. District Judge G. Thomas
Eisele have ruled that Franz did not have legal standing to
intervene. However, Eisele ordered a psychological evaluation for
Simmons and for an independent lawyer to review transcripts of the
trial. That lawyer will advise Simmons of his rights.
</TEXT>
