<FIRST>r a PM-SpyCamera     02-23 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spy Camera,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Chief Placed Camera in Officers' Restroom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hidden camera placed in a police station
restroom to catch a vandal has been removed after officers
complained that their privacy had been invaded.
   ``Looking back on it, I wish it hadn't been done,'' police Chief
George Straka said Wednesday.
   On Straka's orders the camera was planted in the ceiling of the
second-story restroom in July 1986. It remained there until officers
learned about it three weeks ago, said Gary Primavera, president of
the Concord Police Officers Association.
   ``A lot of guys feel their right to privacy has been violated,''
Primavera said.
   Detective Ken Bunch said he was shocked when he learned about the
camera.
   `If this were another job _ say Bank of America _ if they put a
camera in a women's bathroom, what do you think the reaction would
be?'' he asked.
   The chief said he had hoped to catch a vandal who plugged a
urinal on several occassions. Water from the clogged urinal flooded
the bathroom and leaked into other rooms on the floor below,
including Straka's office and a computer center.
   No one was caught.
   The association board is investigating possible legal action
against the chief, Primavera said.
   ``In order to do what he did, you would have to get a court
order,'' Primavera said. ``It's like a wire tap. You have to have
probable cause.''
</TEXT>
