<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--SameSex-Marriages     02-23 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Same Sex-Marriages,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Francisco Bar Association Endorses Same Sex Marriages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state law banning marriages between people
of the same sex should be repealed because it discriminates against
homosexuals, says the board of directors of the 8,000-member Bar
Association of San Francisco.
   Banning same-sex marriages was a ``clear denial of equal
protection under the 14th Amendment to the Constitution by singling
out an identifiable class of people,'' association president Peter
G. Keane told a legal newspaper.
   The directors decided unanimously on Wednesday that the current
state civil code mandating marriages between a man and a woman be
changed to read ``marriage is a personal relation arising out of a
civil contract between two people,'' the San Francisco Banner Daily
Journal reported.
   A change would give partners of both homosexuals and
hetereosexuals many of the same rights now only enjoyed by legally
married couples.
   The new definition of marriage is needed to correct ``invidious
discrimination against non-heterosexuals who choose to have a
relationship that has the same quality and definition that a husband
and wife have,'' Keane said.
</TEXT>
