<SECOND>PM-People-Muller,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Johns Hopkins President Announces Retirement Date</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johns Hopkins University President Steven
Muller, one of the nation's longest-serving university presidents,
says he will resign June 30, 1990.
   ``I've made a contribution here,'' Muller told the school's Board
of Trustees on Wednesday. ``I think there are other things I could
do.''
   Muller, Hopkins president for the past 17 years, declined to say
what he will do after he leaves. He was inaugurated as president
Feb. 1, 1972. He was under contract until 1992.
   Muller's ``dynamic and enlightened leadership was instrumental in
moving the university into new and productive areas of education and
research,'' said George Radcliffe, chairman of the board of trustees.
   Muller, 61, had been expected to retire in 1990 after a major
fund-raising drive for the university, and in November, he turned
over day-to-day affairs at Hopkins to the provost and vice
president, John Lombardi.
   Plans to search for a successor have not been finalized, but
Muller said he will help in the process.
