<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-USDoctors     02-23 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-US Doctors,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Vietnamese Doctors Operate On 50 Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of American doctors on a
humanitarian mission to Vietnam has helped local surgeons operate on
more than 50 children with congenital mouth deformities, a
Vietnamese news report said.
   The surgeons operated to correct cleft lips and palates at the
Olof Palme Institute for the Protection of Children's Health in
Hanoi, the official Vietnam News Agency said Wednesday in a report
monitored in Bangkok.
   The doctors, the first group of American physicians to visit
Vietnam since the communists took power in 1975, traveled there last
week and planned to do reconstructive surgery on 100 children. They
are to stay until Saturday.
   The group, Operation Smile, is based in Norfolk, Va., and is one
of several private, non-profit organizations responding to the U.S.
government's recommendation that Vietnam be given private aid on
humanitarian fields.
   ``When you smile to each other, you'll begin to love another
naturally,'' William Magee, the group's founder, was quoted by the
news agency as saying.
   The United States and Vietnam have no diplomatic relations, but
Washington has encouraged more humanitarian aid since Vietnam
pledged in August 1987 to speed up an accounting of Americans
missing from the war.
   The agency quoted Tran Van Truong, deputy head of the
Odonto-Stomatology Institute, as saying more than 1,000 babies are
born in Vietnam each year with mouth deformities but less than half
are treated. Vietnam is short of plastic surgeons, medical equipment
and facilities, he said.
</TEXT>
