<FIRST>r a PM-SentenceVoided     02-23 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sentence Voided,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Sentence Overturned Because Jurors Asked for Bible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has overturned a murderer's
death sentence because the jury that convicted him 10 years ago had
asked for a Bible and because the trial judge improperly instructed
jurors on the charges.
   Prosecutors can appeal U.S. District Judge Charles A. Moyes'
ruling, agree to a life prison term, or seek a new sentencing
hearing for Brandon Jones, 31, of Chicago, who was convicted of
murder committed during a 1979 service-station robbery. Co-defendant
Van Roosevelt Solomon was electrocuted in 1985.
   Moye, in a ruling handed down Feb. 16, said it was a
``constitutional error'' for jurors to be allowed access to a Bible
during deliberations. He said the jury ``had a duty to apply the law
of the state of Georgia ... not its own interpretation of the law or
its own interpretation of precepts of the Bible.''
   Moye also ruled that former Cobb Superior Court Judge Luther
Hames didn't instruct the jury about the difference between armed
robbery and burglary, and that the jury wasn't fully informed about
the definition of aggravated murder.
   Prosecutors have 30 days from Moye's ruling to decide what
they'll do.
</TEXT>
