<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Woodbury     02-23 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Woodbury,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joan Woodbury, Leading Lady of `B' Movies, Dies at 73</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DESERT HOT SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Joan Woodbury, who
starred in dozens of low-budget films before turning to local stage
productions, has died at her home at age 73.
   Miss Woodbury, who was married to actor and radio personality Ray
Mitchell for 25 years, died Wednesday of respiratory failure caused
by an avian strain of tuberculosis, the Riverside County Coroner's
Office said.
   The actress once recalled that she broke into the entertainment
business by dancing in a Los Angeles restaurant in exchange for free
dinners for herself and her mother.
   She appeared in her first film, ``Eight Girls in a Boat,'' in
1933 and went on to play a wide range of roles, from a saloon girl
in ``Luck of the Roaring Camp'' to a nun in ``Melody Lingers On,''
gaining recognition as Hollywood's leading lady of ``B'' movies.
   She also had the title role in a 13-part serialization of the
``Brenda Starr'' comic strip in 1945.
   She concluded her film career with ``Time Travelers'' in 1963,
and that year helped found the Valley Players Guild in Palm Springs,
working in more than 120 productions over 25 years.
   Funeral arrangements were pending.
</TEXT>
