<FIRST>r p PM-ChicagoMayoral     02-23 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vrdolyak Back as GOP Write-In Candidate in Chicago Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Alderman Edward Vrdolyak, a battered
veteran of Chicago's political wars, has jumped into the mayor's
race as a write-in Republican candidate.
   Vrdolyak joined the race just six days before Tuesday's primary
election, telling a multiracial crowd of cheering supporters at a
restaurant that the endorsed GOP candidate, Dr. Herb Sohn, was
``being thrown to the wolves.''
   The campaign in this heavily Democratic city has been dominated
by the Democratic primary contest between chief rivals Richard M.
Daley and Mayor Eugene Sawyer.
   Vrdolyak said Wednesday at the campaign kickoff rally that Sohn
was ``a decent gentleman'' but was left to run with no financial
support.
   Sohn, a physician and lawyer, expressed no thanks for Vrdolyak's
``help'' and called him ``the Count Dracula of politics.''
   Vrdolyak, 51, a former Democrat, joined the GOP in 1987 soon
after he unsuccessfully sought the mayor's chair as a third-party
candidate against his arch-foe, the late Harold Washington. Vrdolyak
waged another losing battle in November for Cook County court clerk.
   Tuesday's primaries and the April 4 general election are to
complete the final two years of Washington's second term. Washington
died of a heart attack in November 1987.
   Mike Royko, the Pulitzer Prize-winning syndicated columnist based
at the Chicago Tribune, said Vrdolyak ``could sure create problems,
the most obvious effect of which would be to siphon off white votes
from Rich Daley.''
   Daley and Vrdolyak are white; Sawyer is black.
   Vrdolyak rejected the ``spoiler'' label.
   ``The very essence of the word `spoiler' means that we have to
have a racial quota on who can run for office,'' he told the crowd
of about 400, ``and the very essence is racist, and we should put it
out of any campaign.''
   But Daley, Cook County state's attorney and son of late Mayor
Richard J. Daley, said he thinks he is the target.
   ``I think they're all out to stop me,'' he said.
   Sawyer denied that he could benefit significantly from Vrdolyak's
entry. ``He could be siphoning some (votes) from me,'' the mayor
said.
   The GOP and Democratic primary winners will face third-party
candidate Timothy Evans, a black alderman, in the general election.
</TEXT>
