<FIRST>u i PM-Mideast-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0561 02-23 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mideast-Soviets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0561,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Resumption of Israeli Ties Depends On Peace Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Shevardnadze saying Israeli
ties could be resumed, comment from Shamir, Arafat. Pickup 10th graf, ``In
today's...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union may resume ties with Israel
if the Jewish state takes part in an international peace conference
that includes the PLO, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
said today.
   In a speech to Egyptian political leaders at the end of a
four-day visit, Shevardnadze also made what he called his ``first
critical remark about the new president of the United States,''
saying George Bush was trying unjustly to limit the Soviet role in
the Middle East.
   His comments about Soviet ties with Israel, where were severed by
Moscow during the 1967 Middle East war, came one day after he met
with Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens in Cairo.
   ``We would like the government of Israel to know that once it
opts for the conference and agrees to a dialogue with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, our two countries could take yet another
step toward re-establishing full diplomatic relations,'' he said.
``The beginning of the conference would be a starting point for
resumed relations.''
   On Wednesday, Arens rejected the idea of a conference with the
PLO. However, he told reporters afterward the Soviets have a role to
play in Middle East peacemaking even without diplomatic ties with
Israel.
   However, in Paris today, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel
said the Soviet Union must first establish normal relations with
Israel before it can play a role in solving the Mideast conflict.
   ``We wait for this act on the part of Moscow,'' Shamir told a
news conference. ``I hope it will be forthcoming.''
   In Jerusalem, Deputy Foreign Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
today that Arens and Shevardnadze agreed to expand their nations'
relations through delegations that will meet in the next few weeks.
A Foreign Ministy official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
without elaboaration that the delegations will focus on the Middle
East conflict.
   Israel's Hadashot newspaper said Arens and Shevardnadze also
agreed to advance ties by making the consular offices in each
country permanent.
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat today said in Cairo the Soviet Union's
new dialogue with Israel is giving him a channel for ``indirect
negotiations'' with Israel.
   Speaking to reporters one day after he met with Shevardnadze,
Arafat rejected direct negotiations between Israel and the PLO
outside of the proposed international peace conference.
   In today's speech, Shevardnadze warned Israel that it ``has no
right to deny freedom of choice to the Palestinian people.''
   ``Unless a peaceful, comprehensive political settlement is found
... developments in the region would follow a spiral wound by the
logic of military confrontation,'' he said. ``The region faces the
threat of an arms race which sooner or later would degenerate into a
nuclear face-off.''
   Shevardnadze alluded to Israel's reported possession of a
substantial nuclear arsenal and possible efforts by Arab states to
acquire nuclear or chemical weapons.
   The speech appeared to sum up his visits to Syria, Jordan and
Egypt. He later left for Iraq and planned to visit Iran before
returning home.
   Shevardnadze was in Egypt when Bush made remarks Tuesday
relegating the Soviet Union to a ``limited role'' in the Middle East.
   ``He made a qualification that I didn't like. He said the role of
the Soviet Union should be limited. That is very sad because it
injects an element of rivalry that is unnecessary,'' Shevardnadze
said.
   He added with as smile: ``This is my first critical remark about
the president of the United States.''
   Shevardnadze spoke in Russian, and Arabic and English
translations of his remarks were available.
   Shevardnadze over the weekend unveiled a Soviet proposal that the
five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council prepare for an
international conference to negotiate an Arab-Israeli peace
settlement.
   The PLO would attend as a full partner.
</TEXT>
