<HEAD>Today's Developments on `Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Satanic Verses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are today's key developments involving Salman Rushdie's
novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Pro-Iranian militants holding three Americans
hostage in Lebanon vowed revenge for the publication of ``The
Satanic Verses.'' Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine
released a photograph of hostages Alann Steen, Jesse Turner and
Robert Polhill but did not specifically threaten the men or other
hostages.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BONN, West Germany _ The federal government announced it has
suspended plans to help rebuild Iran's war-ravaged economy and won't
resume credit talks until the execution order against Rushdie is
withdrawn. The country is Iran's biggest trading partner.
   Parliament calls Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's death sentence a
``declaration of war'' against Western values.
   The Kiepenheuer and Witsch publishing house of Cologne said it
will publish the German-language edition of ``The Satanic Verses,''
reversing an earlier decision not to publish it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LONDON _ Rushdie was in hiding for a ninth straight day with his
wife, American novelist Marianne Wiggins.
   London's Observer newspaper said it has received from Rushdie his
review of fellow novelist Phillip Roth's autobiography and will run
the piece Sunday. The review, which arrived a week late, ``rather
carefully and subtly'' makes known Rushdie's feelings about his
predicament, said literary editor Blake Morrison.
   Former pop singer Cat Stevens, who gave up a successful music
career in 1977 after becoming a Moslem, spoke out in support of
Khomeini's death order. ``The Koran makes it clear _ if someone
defames the prophen (Mohammed), then he must die,'' said Stevens,
whose hits included ``Peace Train'' and ``Wild World.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OTTAWA _ Canadian authorities increased security around the
Iranian Embassy following a bomb threat received Wednesday. A search
turned up no bomb.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PARIS _ The Christian Bourgois publishing house announced it had
reversed a decision and will publish the French translation of ``The
Satanic Verses.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ Foreign Trade Minister Pertti Salolainen
announced he was postponing a scheduled trade visit to Iran because
of the ``repulsive execution order.''
   The WSOY publishing company announces plans to publish the
Finnish translation of the book.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The Parliament of Yugoslavia's most
liberal republic, Slovenia, condemned Iran's death threat against
Rushdie and criticized Belgrade's hosting of Iranian Pesident Ali
Khamenei in the midst of the controversy.
</TEXT>
