<FIRST>u i PM-China-Indonesia     02-23 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Indonesia,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>China, Indonesia Agree To Restore Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China and Indonesia today agreed to normalize
relations, 22 years after they suspended ties over allegations that
China supported a communist coup attempt against the Indonesian
government.
   Indonesian President Suharto and Chinese Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen reached the agreement after meeting for more than two hours
at a Tokyo hotel, said Max Lapod, spokesman for the Indonesian
Embassy in Tokyo.
   ``We are going to go through the process of normalizing relations
based on the five principles of non-interference, non-aggression,
mutual respect, beneficial relations and peaceful coexistence,''
Lapod said in an interview.
   ``Both sides are very satisfied with their statements,'' he said.
   Suharto and Qian are in Tokyo to attend Friday's funeral for
Emperor Hirohito, who died of cancer Jan. 7.
   Indonesia suspended relations with China in 1967, two years after
an attempted communist coup in Jakarta in which Indonesia alleged
Chinese backing.
   ``We don't call it severed, we say relations were frozen,'' Lapod
said. ``We've been talking at international conferences in Jakarta
and at the United Nations.''
   Suharto and Qian accepted invitations for the Indonesian and
Chinese presidents to exchange visits, which could take place as
early as this year, Lapod said.
   Meanwhile, China's state-run news agency Xinhua reported that
Qian and Suharto ``agreed upon future efforts for normalization of
bilateral relations.'' The meeting with Suharto marked the beginning
of the normalization process, Xinhua quoted Qian as telling
reporters.
   ``They agreed that the two countries should make further efforts
toward the normalization of bilateral relations, which they said
should be achieved on the basis of the five principles of peaceful
coexistence,'' the news agency quoted an unidentified official as
saying.
   China long has been pressing for normalization of relations with
Indonesia, but Jakarta has held back largely because of fear China
would use its influence among Indonesia's ethnic Chinese to foment
unrest.
   About 4 million of Indonesia's 168 million people are ethnic
Chinese, many of them wealthy businessmen.
   China has repeatedly assured Indonesia it will follow a hands-off
policy.
   Last spring, Vice Foreign Minister Liu Shuqing visited Jakarta
and told Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas that China would not
interfere in the internal affairs of other countries, including
Indonesia.
   Direct trade, which the two countries resumed in 1985, reached
$611 million in 1987, with Indonesia enjoying a more than $100
million surplus.
   Indonesia's move is certain to be studied in Singapore, which has
said it will not establish ties with Beijing until Indonesia does.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
