<HEAD>Arctic Air, Snow Covers Much of East; Snow Hits South</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with record lows, snow across
South, storm expected tonight, picks up 5th graf, ``A heavy ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bitterly cold air rushed across the Deep South today, with snow
falling almost as far south as the Gulf of Mexico, and heavy snow
fell around Chicago.
   Temperatures crashed to record lows across the Midwest and as far
south as Tennessee, and wind chill factors fell below zero deep in
the South. Pensacola, Fla., fell to 30 degrees.
   Snow flurries were reported in Alabama as far south as northern
Mobile and Baldwin counties on the Gulf coast. The snow accumulated
in northern Alabama and state authorities said Interstate 59 north
of Trussville and Interstate 20 near Leeds were closed.
   An inch of snow fell at Athens, Ga., with flurries across Georgia
to the Florida border, and visibility was as low as one mile in snow
at Meridian, Miss.
   Record lows today included 17 at Memphis, Tenn.; 2 at Kansas
City, Mo.; 13 below zero at Norfolk, Neb.; 13 below zero at Spencer,
Iowa; and 10 below zero at Traverse City, Mich.
   A combination of cold and gusty wind produced wind chill values
of 11 degrees below zero at Memphis Naval Air Station in Tennessee,
14 below at Harrison, Ark., and 22 below at Springfield, Mo.
   The National Weather Service said temperatures tonight would fall
to the teens in Alabama from Huntsville to Mobile, and said many
efforts to save crops would be fruitless because of strong wind and
the duration of freezing temperatures.
   Schools were closed in sections of Tennessee, South Carolina and
Georgia, including the University of Georgia. One Georgia traffic
death was blamed on icy pavement.
   A low pressure system was expected to develop off the Carolina
coast tonight and spread snow from North Carolina across eastern
sections of the mid Atlantic states toward southern New England, the
weather service said. Winter storm watches were posted from North
Carolina up the coast to New York City.
   Snow also fell around the Great Lakes, with the heaviest
accumulations around the southern tip of Lake Michigan.
   Porter County in extreme northwest Indiana reported 13 inches of
snow and 6 to 10 inches were reported in Lake County, Ill., just
north of Chicago. High winds caused near blizzard conditions in some
areas.
   A heavy snow warning was in effect for portions of northwest
Indiana and northeast Illinois.
   Snow advisories were in effect for northeast Alabama, eastern
Tennessee, the northern mountains of North Carolina, portions of
Ohio, and along Lake Ontario in western New York state.
   Temperatures along the East Coast were dropping, reflecting the
forward edge of the arctic air, but readings were still above
freezing as far north as southern New England.
   Early morning temperatures were mild in the West, with readings
in the 30s and 40s in most places, 50s in California, and 50s to mid
60s in the Desert Southwest.
   Showers were widely scattered over the northwest quarter of the
nation.
   Today's forecast called for light snow over much of the East from
New England to northern Georgia and into the Appalachians. Rain was
expected directly along the coast. Rain also was forecast for the
Pacific Northwest, and rain or snow was predicted for the northern
Plateau and northern Rockies.
   Highs were expected to be in the single digits and teens over the
Great Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley; the 20s and 30s over
most of the eastern half of the nation, with lower 40s along the
Carolina coast; the 40s to lower 60s over central and southern
Florida; and the 40s and 50s in most of the nation from the Plains
to the Pacific Coast, with 60s in southwest Texas, New Mexico and
much of California, and 70s to mid 80s in Southern California and
the Desert Southwest.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 17 degrees below zero at
Hibbing, Minn., and Sioux Falls, S.D., to 67 degrees at Key West,
Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 27 fair; Boston 37 cloudy; Buffalo 18 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 42 cloudy; Cincinnati 17 partly cloudy; Cleveland
17 snow; Detroit 7 fair; Miami 58 fair; New York 36 windy;
Philadelphia 35 fair; Pittsburgh 19 snow; Portland, Maine 32 cloudy;
Washington 38 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 7 fair; Chicago 11 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 28
fair; Denver 30 cloudy; Des Moines -5 fair; Indianapolis 12 fair;
Kansas City 5 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul -8 fair; Nashville 20 snow;
New Orleans 38 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 40 fair; Anchorage 19 fair; Las Vegas 50
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 57 fair; San Diego 58
fair; San Francisco 49 fair; Seattle 43 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 14 fair; Toronto 7 windy.
</TEXT>
