<HEAD>Man Admits Stealing Books Eights Years Ago, Sends Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STILLWATER, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who says he stole books and a
calculator from a book store eight years ago has apologized to the
store and sent a check for $300.
   ``I just think it was such a neat thing. We had such a hoot when
we got it,'' said Paula Roberts, manager of the Smith Book Store.
   Rick Lawson admitted swiping the goods while he was a student at
Oklahoma State University in 1981. He said he took the materials
because he did not have the money to buy them at the time.
   In his letter, received by the store Feb. 16, Lawson said he
``recently surrendered my life to the Lord'' and asked store
officials for their forgiveness.
   Lawson, who now lives in Saginaw, Texas, said in a telephone
interview that ``it was a tough decision, but it had to be done.''
   ``I could tell it was the right thing to do,'' he said.
   ``I think it took a lot of courage to write that letter,'' Ms.
Roberts said, adding that she plans to commend Lawson for his action.
</TEXT>
