<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan     02-23 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Resumes Sudan Airlift; Government Confirms Shelling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Red Cross said today it resumed an
airlift of food and medicine to tens of thousands of starving people
in southern Sudan after a two-week interruption caused by
``technical problems.''
   The government confirmed the rebel shelling of an important
southern provincial capital and said 11 civilians died.
   Bernard Juler, acting director of the International Committee of
the Red Cross, told The Associated Press the airlift resumed
Wednesday and that three planeloads had already reached Wau, capital
of the southern Bahr el-Ghazal region, 625 miles south of Khartoum.
   The Red Cross was able to get approval from the government and
the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army, or SPLA, in December to
airlift supplies to both government-held and rebel-held areas in the
south.
   It had been difficult to get relief to the south because the
rebels were shooting at civilian and military flights there,
claiming the army was using relief planes to transport its supplies.
   The airlift was abruptly stopped two weeks ago.
   ``It was only technical questions and we have overcome that. We
have supplied both the government and the SPLA with new (flight)
programs and schedules and we obtained the okay,'' Juler said.
   Juler said that airlift would continue as long as it was needed
and conditions were favorable. He said there would be two flights a
day, each carrying about 17 tons of food and medicine.
   The flights to the government-held towns leave from Khartoum, and
those for the rebel-held areas leave from airports in northeast
Kenya.
   The rebels took up arms against the government in 1983, demanding
more autonomy and administrative and economic reforms.
   In a broadcast over National Unity Radio, monitored Wednesday
night in Nairobi, the Sudanese government said the Sudan People's
Liberation Army shelled the southern city of Juba on Monday, killing
11 civilians.
   More than 50,000 refugees have crowded into Juba in the past
year, seeking relief from famine and civil war.
   The rebels announced the artillery attack in an earlier broadcast
over their clandestine radio station, saying the shelling was
confined to military targets. Juba, a city of 150,000 about 80 miles
north of the Ugandan border, is the capital of Sudan's southernmost
province of Equatoria.
</TEXT>
