<SECOND>PM-Hospital Workers, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0534,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Rhode Island Hospital Employees Return to Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7, ``Benedict said ...' with 4 grafs to update
with court hearing, state not pressing for fines; Picks up 8th graf, `DiPrite
called ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRANSTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most striking employees at a state-run
hospital that had been staffed by National Guard troops returned to
work today under a court order and their union leader's suggestion,
the hospital's administrator said.
   ``The numbers are good. This reflects a complete turnaround from
the past couple of days,'' General Hospital Administrator James P.
Benedict said after the 7 a.m. shift began work.
   Seventy-four of the 85 attendants scheduled to work showed up, as
did eight of 10 licensed practical nurses and virtually all of the
registered nurses. Benedict said the remaining number of workers
absent was normal for that shift.
   The National Guard, which had been helping to care for more than
400 chronically ill patients since the strike began Sunday night,
will remain at the facility for the rest of the day to help with the
transition, Benedict said. He said the Guard has been costing the
state $20,000 a day.
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete said Wednesday workers who failed to
return by 7 a.m. would be fired, and termination letters were
prepared overnight.
   Benedict said the letters had not been sent.
   At a hearing in Providence Superior Court, a state attorney, John
Breguet, told Judge Antonio S. Almeida the state would not seek to
fine Local 1350 of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees even though the union did not immediately obey
the judge's order to return to work at 3 p.m. Wednesday.
   ``We believe 1350 is actively encouraging workers to return to
work,'' Breguet said.
   Almeida said he was annoyed that his order had not been obeyed,
but accepted the state's recommendation. He scheduled a new hearing
for March 15 and continued the back-to-work order until then.
   DiPrete called both sides to his office for three hours of
negotiations Wednesday, the first in five days, and said after the
talks that a settlement was near, but only if the union returned to
work.
   Union President Jospeh Fargnoli said he ``encouraged them to go
back to work,'' but it was up to each member whether to return.
   Some workers chanted, ``No work. No work,'' as they left the
union hall Wednesday. More than a dozen union members picketed near
the hospital's entrance.
   Nearly half of 66 scheduled attendants and 19 of 29 nurses
reported for their 3 p.m. shifts, said Benedict. Thirty acute-care
patients have been transferred to other facilities, he said.
   Union members walked out over claims that the state refused to
fill contract-mandated positions. The state, in an effort to cut
overtime, has refused to call in additional staff in many cases
where workers are sick.
   DiPrete said the state's offer of a 53-cents-an-hour pay raise,
rejected overwhelmingly by union members, was still available. The
increase would have raised attendants' starting salaries from
$16,600 to $17,600 and nurses' starting wages from $18,800 to
$20,000.
   Wednesday's negotiations ended with some concessions on staffing
levels after ``a ward-by-ward analysis,'' said Gerard P. Cobleigh, a
union attorney. Fargnoli said there was ``nothing concrete at all.''
   No new negotiations were scheduled but Fargnoli and Cobleigh said
they would return to the table if necessary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
