<FIRST>u a PM-MummyTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0578 02-23 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mummy Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0578,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses One of Two Charges Against Man Who Tended Mummy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to CORRECT age from 58 to 57 and update with
defendant testifying, defense rests; picks up 3rd graf, ``Roberts' rulings...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge acquitted a dentist today of one
charge in a scheme to conceal the death of a man whose family tended
his mummified corpse for nine years, but ordered the trial to
continue on another charge.
   Knox County Judge Daniel J. Roberts dismissed a charge of cruelty
to children against Richard G. Kunce, 57. Kunce, who also faces a
forgery charge, is accused of helping conceal the 1979 death of Carl
Stevens, 39, of rural Knoxville.
   Kunce later took the stand and denied committing any crime, and
the defense rested its case.
   Kunce, a live-in guest at the Stevens' home since 1986, said he
had met Stevens both before and after Stevens' death at age 39, and
described himself as a ``nutritional adviser'' to the family.
   ``I met him (Carl) once before he went down and I met him many
times after he went down,'' Kunce said.
   When he first saw Stevens' body in May 1980, Kunce said, ``Carl's
body was totally black, and Carole had been putting liquid vitamins
in his belly button.''
   Roberts' rulings today were in response to a defense motion to
dismiss both charges against Kunce, of Aurora. The trial began
Tuesday.
   The cruelty charge stemmed from allegations that Kunce taught
Stevens' teen-age children about suicide, black magic and
communication with the dead.
   ``I have come to the conclusion there is no showing what effect
(Kunce's) actions had on the children,'' Roberts said. ``There's no
evidence of injury to the children, therefore I must dismiss the
cruelty charge.''
   The judge said he did not dismiss the forgery charge, however,
because of contradictory testimony he felt jurors should consider.
The trial resumed after he issued the rulings.
   Authorities discovered Stevens' corpse last year when his cousin
saw it and called police. Authorities later learned that Stevens'
widow, Carole, had tended the corpse as if it were alive.
   On Wednesday, Kunce's attorney, John Pepmeyer, acknowledged his
client had helped Mrs. Stevens forge a power of attorney to
refinance her house, but he said Kunce signed the document ``to help
a friend, not to defraud anyone.''
   ``I didn't hear anything sufficient to prove criminal acts beyond
a reasonable doubt,'' Pepmeyer said. ``They (prosecutors) don't have
enough ammunition to get to first base.
   ``It has long been the law that fraudulent intent is an essential
element of forgery,'' Pepmeyer said.
   Knox County prosecutor Jonathan Schlake argued that Kunce helped
Mrs. Stevens deceive bankers in obtaining a new mortgage.
   ``The power of attorney document was capable of being used to
defraud someone on its face,'' Schlake said.
   Earlier Wednesday, police detectives testified that Kunce told
them he regularly spoke with Carl Stevens during the nine years his
corpse was in the home.
   Kunce said ``Carl was happy and content,'' according to the
detectives.
   One conversation took place just days before Kunce was arrested,
said investigator Dick Flanagan.
   ``Kunce said he was working out ... walked into the bedroom and
Carl said, `Good workout, Richard,''' the investigator said.
   Flanagan and Stephen Johnson, a Knox County sheriff's detective,
told of entering the Stevens home and finding the body dressed in
blue pajama bottoms and white socks, lying in bed with sheets pulled
up around his chest.
   Also Wednesday, forensic pathologist Larry Blum of McHenry said
he found no evidence of homicide when he performed an autopsy on
Stevens' corpse. The body had been naturally mummified.
   ``My opinion is that Mr. Stevens died of complications of the
disease of diabetes,'' Blum said, adding that the body could have
remained in its mummified condition indefinitely, if protected from
the elements.
   ``I've never seen a body completely mummified like Mr. Stevens,''
Blum said. ``This was a first for me.''
   Mrs. Stevens, 43, pleaded guilty last March to forgery and
failure to report a death. She was sentenced to 12 days in jail and
placed on two years' probation.
   Kunce faces up to five years in prison and a $10,000 fine if
convicted of forgery.
</TEXT>
