<FIRST>u w PM-EPA-Superfund 1stLd-Writethru a0451 02-23 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EPA-Superfund, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 10 grafs new with testimony; picks up 5th graf pvs, The
report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency was
criticized at a House hearing today for using skilled contract
employees as office workers, even though they were hired to inspect
hazardous waste sites.
   ``These contract rates are not minimum wage,'' but sometimes more
than $30 per hour, said Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., chairman of
the civil service subcommittee of the House Post Office and Civil
Service Committee.
   Sikorski, conducting the hearing to review EPA contracting
practices, also criticized EPA for giving contractors undeserved
monetary performance awards _ for paying contract workers for
attending conferences.
   He based his remarks on findings by EPA Inspector General John C.
Martin, who testified before the panel.
   Sikorski accused the EPA of taking a ``don't worry, be happy''
attitude, in which the agency views the criticism as ``perception
problems.''
   Henry L. Longest II, director of EPA's office of Emergency and
Remedial Response, told Sikorski, ``I'm not saying we don't have any
problems.'' But he also defended agency contracting, especially in
the Superfund hazardous waste cleanup program.
   The skilled inspection employees were working in the office, he
said, because ``we had data in-house'' on the hazardous waste sites
they would have inspected in Massachusetts, Longest said.
   He added that the incentive award fees are based on a
contractor's overall work, and can be given out even if certain
parts of the work are below standards.
   Martin described to the committee his findings on the EPA's
contract with NUS Corp.
   The agency hired the company, of the Washington suburb of
Gaithersburg, Md., to provide field inspection teams to inspect
potential Superfund cleanup sites in four of the agency's regions:
Atlanta, Boston, New York City and Philadelphia. The inspector
general's report estimated the five-year contract will cost $125
million by its finish.
   The report said the contract turned sour within a month of its
Nov. 1, 1986, beginning when the Boston-based Region I stopped
preliminary on-site inspections of hazardous waste areas. The region
ordered the contract employees to get data from state officials and
information supplied by the polluters of the sites.
   The contract employees' ``morale was affected since almost all
... activity was office work,'' the report said. During the 10
months the policy was in effect, 41 percent of the NUS professional
staff resigned or was transferred, the report said.
   The inspector general said the policy of paying for NUS employees
to attend conferences was questioned internally by at least one EPA
official, who wrote the practice ``might not hold up too well under
any type of scrutiny _ congressional, inspector general, or
otherwise.''
   A separate inspector general's report given the subcommittee
criticized the Philadelphia-based Region III management of EPA's
emergency Superfund response program _ which uses contract employees
to respond to environmental emergencies.
   The report found that members of a team of groundwater
hydrologists, toxicologists, chemists, and environmental scientists
often were used as file clerks.
   The inspector general's reports included comments from the EPA,
which defended its actions.
   The agency said the audit covered only the first 13 months of a
five-year contract and failed to list ``major accomplishments'' of
the site inspection program that occured near the end of the first
year.
   The EPA also disagreed with the emergency response team report,
emphasizing that maintaining good records was within the contract's
scope of work. But the agency said that to avoid the appearance of
wasteful work, the clerical tasks will now be handled by people from
the American Association of Retired Persons.
   Donald Couchman, the NUS vice president for administration,
declined comment, calling the report ``internal review of EPA
management.''
   The nation's Superfund program is designed to clean up hazardous
waste sites. More than 30,000 potential sites have been identified,
with 1,175 designated on a national priority cleanup list. Remedial
action has been completed at 48 sites, with some work under way at
more than half the priority sites, according to EPA.
   The NUS report said EPA was too lenient in evaluating company
work, and gave the company undeserved performance awards.
   One unit of contract employees received praise and award fees of
over $90,000 even though the team did not perform field work and had
transferred a large segment of the team to do work on a state
contract.
   At the top Superfund site in the country, the Lipari Landfill in
Pitman, N.J., the EPA paid a nominal award fee even though an EPA
official was sharply critical of the company's work, the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Japan-Glance     02-23 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Glance,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hirohito Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Facts and figures on Japan:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TERRITORY _ An archipelego of volcanic origin; four main islands
and more than 3,900 others off the east coast of the Asian
continent. Over two-thirds mountainous. Total area is 151,120 square
miles, about the size of Montana.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PEOPLE _ Seventh-most populous country with 122 million
inhabitants, 60 percent in urban areas. Koreans are the largest
minority at 680,000; aboriginal Ainu number 24,000 by official
count, up to 100,000 by own estimates. Literacy rate 99 percent; 35
percent of high school graduates go to college.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POLITICAL SYSTEM _ Administrative power is vested in Cabinet
consisting of prime minister and 20 ministers. Postwar politics
dominated by the ruling Liberal Democratic Party. Parliament,
elected by secret ballot, is the 512-seat House of Representatives
and the 252-seat House of Councillors.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   IMPERIAL FAMILY _ The oldest hereditary monarchy in the world, by
legend dating from Feb. 11, 660 B.C., and by historical accounts
from the 5th century A.D. Today the emperor is a constitutional
monarch with ceremonial duties.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ECONOMY _ World's second-largest after the United States, with a
gross national product of about $2.5 trillion in fiscal 1987. The
growth rate for the period was 4.9 percent and per capita GNP
reached $19,642. Unemployment is 2.5 percent, the lowest in the
industrial world, because Japan does not count defense personnel and
those working more than one hour per week. The trade surplus on
customs clearance basis was $77.4 billion in calendar 1988. Exports
rose 15.6 percent in one-year period to $265 billion in 1988;
imports climbed 25.4 percent to $187.5 billion.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AGRICULTURE _ Main crops are rice, other grains, vegetables and
fruit. Imports supply 67 percent of Japan's cereals, 20 percent of
its fruit and 22 percent of its meat.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DEFENSE _ Japan's $29 billion defense budget in fiscal 1987 was
1.013 percent of GNP. The all-volunteer Self Defense Forces number
more than 240,000 and are strictly limited to a defensive role.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RELIGION _ Buddhism is predominant with more than 30 million
followers. Many also follow customs of the indigenous Shinto faith,
which was devised into a state cult based around worship of the
emperor for six decades until 1945.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Records date back to 300 A.D. with the rise of Yamato
court in Nara, western Japan. By the mid-seventh century,
Chinese-style rule had been established. Incessant clan warfare
prevailed from about 900 A.D. until the Shogun Tokugawa unified the
country in 1603 and closed it off to the outside. After the arrival
of U.S. ships in 1853, Japan adopted a constitutional monarchy in
1868 headed by Emperor Meiji, as well as a European-style
bureaucracy and a military. Militarists expanded Japanese rule in
Asia from the turn of the century until World War II, which ended
with the U.S. atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in August
1945. U.S. occupation forces dissolved Japan's family-run financial
combines, purged military influence, tried war criminals and
introduced a democratic constitution. The late Emperor Hirohito
renounced his divine status after the war's end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
