<FIRST>r i AM-BarbaraBush     02-23 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Will No Longer Express Differences With Bush in Public</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush has decided to keep any disagreements
with President Bush within the family after a public difference over
whether military-style assault weapons should be outlawed, it was
announced on Thursday.
   Under a new policy revealed as Mrs. Bush arrived here for the
funeral of Emperor Hirohito, the first lady no longer will talk
about controversial issues such as gun control and abortion.
   ``They are not the issues where she wishes to have a focus,''
said Anna Perez, her press secretary.
   ``It doesn't mean she doesn't have a right to an opinion. It
means she has a right to discuss them or not,'' Ms. Perez said.
   Mrs. Bush and her husband appeared at odds after she said in a
recent interview with The Associated Press that she ``absolutely''
favors a ban on military-style assault weapons, such as the one used
in the recent schoolyard massacre in Stockton, Calif., where five
children were killed and more than two dozen were wounded.
   Questioned separately, the president said he does not favor a ban
on semiautomatic weapons because they are used by sportsmen and
hunters. It was a semiautomatic AK-47 that was used in the Stockton
incident.
   Bush, a lifetime member of the National Rifle Association, the
nation's largest gun lobby, said police should do more to enforce
the laws.
   Ms. Perez quoted the first lady as saying ``there isn't that much
of a difference of opinion'' between Bush and his wife over the
issue of assault-style weapons.
   ``If there is, they will discuss it among themselves,'' Ms. Perez
added.
   The press secretary said Mrs. Bush wants to highlight issues such
as the homeless, the deadly disease AIDS and illiteracy instead of
controversial matters.
   Emphasizing that Mrs. Bush does not want to take the limelight
from her husband on important subjects, Ms. Perez said, ``She's not
the one that makes policy. She doesn't lobby Congress. She's not the
president.''
   Ms. Perez added, ``The opinions that are important, that require
the spotlight, are those of her husband.''
   Meanwhile, Mrs. Bush had tea with Naoko Takeshita, wife of
Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and expressed sympathy over
the death of Hirohito, who died of cancer at the age of 87.
   In turn, Mrs. Takeshita offered her congratulations on Bush's
election as president.
   The two women met at the official residence of the Takeshitas,
although the family actually lives in a private home in Tokyo. They
talked in a small, green-carpeted room decorated with flowers and a
pastel painting of Mount Fuji.
   For the occasion, Mrs. Bush wore an elegant black suit and her
trademark strand of imitation pearls. Mrs. Takeshita wore a navy
blue suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
