<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Lebanon     02-23 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Lebanon,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli-Backed Militiamen Kill Three Palestinian Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli-backed militiamen patrolling in southern
Lebanon today killed three Palestinian guerrillas about a mile north
of Israel's border, the Israeli army said.
   Armed forces radio and the Itim news agency reported the
guerrillas had planned to stage an attack inside Israel.
   An army official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he did
not know whether they planned an attack, but he said they carried
wire cutters, indicating they might have planned to sneak through
the border fence.
   A South Lebanon Army patrol spotted the guerrilla squad about a
mile north of the village of Al Jibbayn in Israel's self-declared
security zone in southern Lebanon, the official said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The patrol opened fire, killing the guerrillas, he said. Fighters
of the South Lebanon Army did not suffer casualties.
   Documents found on the guerillas' bodies showed they were members
of Naif Hawatmeh's Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine,
a Marxist faction of the PLO, the official said.
   The guerrillas carried three Soviet-designed Kalashnikov rifles,
a rocket-propelled grenade launcher and grenades, the army official
said.
   On Wednesday, the Hawatmeh faction celebrated its 20th
anniversary, and underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip urged Palestinians to mark it
with a ``day of confrontations.''
   Today's clash was the second involving a PLO faction since
December, when the Palestine Liberation Organization chief, Yasser
Arafat, renounced terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   On Feb. 5, Israeli troops killed five guerrillas on the northern
border of security zone, and the army said the squad planned an
attack in Israel. Three of the guerrillas were from the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   The South Lebanon Army, a predominantly Christian militia
financed and trained by Israel, assists 1,000 Israeli troops in
patrolling the security zone. Israel declared the six-to-10 mile
strip in 1985 after withdrawing most of its troops from Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
