<FIRST>u w PM-Sullivan 4thLd-Writethru a0606 02-23 0973</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sullivan, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0606,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Says He Opposes Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with committee vote; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Sullivan apologized.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee voted 17-0 today
to confirm the nomination as secretary of health and human services
of Dr. Louis Sullivan, who testified that he opposes abortion except
in three circumstances.
   ``I am opposed to abortion, except when the life of the mother is
threatened, or cases of rape or incest,'' Sullivan told the Senate
Finance Committee.
   One member of the committee, Sen. William Armstrong, R-Colo.,
replied ``present'' when the vote was taken.
   Sullivan apologized to Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., for having
``misspoken'' when they discussed Sullivan's position on abortion
last month.
   ``I support a human life amendment, embracing the exceptions just
noted. Like President Bush, I would welcome a Supreme Court decision
overturning Roe vs. Wade,'' the 1973 ruling that legalized abortion,
he said.
   Packwood, a pro-choice advocate, said that though he disagrees
with Sullivan's position on abortion, he will support his
nomination. He said the important decisions concerning abortion will
be made in Congress and the courts, not at HHS, which spends only a
small fraction of its funds on abortions.
   ``I think you're a whale of a guy,'' Packwood said.
   Sullivan said that if confirmed as HHS secretary, he would work
to encourage adoption and other alternatives to abortion.
   Abortion opponents were upset when Packwood reported that
Sullivan had told him during a meeting that the nominee favored
retaining the Supreme Court abortion ruling. Before his nomination,
Sullivan was quoted in an Atlanta newspaper as saying he favored a
woman's right to abortion.
   Sullivan, the only black Bush has nominated to his Cabinet,
outlined for the committee his goals in running the largest federal
bureaucracy.
   ``Bringing a new spirit of kindness and compassion to a vast
federal department _ one with 114,000 employees and a $400 billion
budget _ may seem excessively idealistic. But it is an ideal we can
and must attain. Nothing less shall be my goal as secretary of
HHS,'' Sullivan said.
   Among the things he hopes to achieve, he said, are finding ways
to contain rapidly rising medical costs in federal programs without
sacrificing quality of care for the poor and improving programs that
help the poor work their way out of poverty.
   He also said he wants to find ways to strengthen family life and
continue research efforts to find a cure for AIDS, as well as
cancer, heart disease and other debilitating diseases.
   Anti-abortion activists demanded assurances from the Bush
administration that Sullivan's policies would follow those of the
president on abortion, and he later asked the White House to
nominate three administrators known for their anti-abortion views to
top positions at the agency.
   Despite the controversy, Sullivan's confirmation appears to be a
certainty. Members of the Senate Finance Committee are expected to
approve his nomination after the hearing, and the full Senate is
scheduled to vote on Tuesday.
   His hearing was postponed three weeks ago because an FBI
background investigation was incomplete and questions remained about
his finances.
   But two weeks ago he put to rest concerns about conflicts of
interest when he decided to forfeit nearly $300,000 in severance pay
due him if he cut his ties with the Morehouse School of Medicine,
the Atlanta medical school he founded and has served as president.
   Sullivan told the panel that he will step down as president of
the school if he is confirmed by the Senate. He said he would take
an unpaid leave of absence as a professor of medicine and would
receive no compensation from the school. However, he would continue
to participate in fringe benefit programs offered by the school,
including life, health and disability insurance.
   He said he will not take the severance pay due him under his
contract with Morehouse in order to set to rest any concerns about
potential conflicts of interest. ``I felt it was more important to
clear up those questions by the action I took,'' he said.
   Sullivan, a blood specialist, will run the the federal
government's largest department. Its budget of nearly $400 billion
covers Social Security, Medicaid, Medicare, the Food and Drug
Administration, the Public Health Service and the National
Institutes of Health.
   Sullivan faced questioning on the Bush administration's fiscal
1990 budget proposal and about many of the more than 200 programs
the department runs.
   In response to questioning, Sullivan said the Morehouse school
made a mistake when in 1984 it hired a Fulton County commissioner as
a part-time lecturer. That commissioner, Reginald Eaves, was paid
more than $34,000 over four years while he used his seat on the
commission to promote issues that benefited the school. In an
unrelated matter, Eaves during that period was convicted of
extortion.
   Sullivan told committee members it had been his understanding
that the commission was aware that Eaves was on the Morehouse
payroll. The commissioners, however, were not aware. He had
understood that the commission had approved of Eaves' position at
Morehouse, he said.
   ``This was a serious error on our part in not assuring this had
been done,'' Sullivan said.
   He told members of the panel the school has taken steps to assure
that kind of problem would not occur again.
   Several members of the panel said they hoped the White House
would review its decision not to allow Sullivan to take a paid
sabbatical leave from Morehouse while he is at HHS.
   ``It's grossly unfair to him,'' said Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo.
   The White House initially approved Sullivan's request to take a
paid leave but then reversed itself and said the medical school's
sabbatical policies did not meet the government's standards because
they did not provide for the policy to be implemented uniformly
among those eligible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
