<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-23 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Florida has extended invitations to
city officials from Hollywood _ South Carolina, Alabama,
Mississippi, Maryland and more _ to discuss ways to stop the movies'
Hollywood from hogging their name.
   The two-day conference next week was organized after the movie
capital tried to trademark the name Hollywood and charge a royalty
for its use by other communities.
   Mayor Mara Giulianti of the Hollywood, Fla., and the Chamber of
Commerce are offering free air fare, meals and accommodations to
representatives of 10 other Hollywoods _ except the one with the
sign on the hill in Los Angeles.
   The other Hollywoods are in Louisiana, New Mexico, Texas,
Arkansas, Arizona and Georgia.
   ``We're just a quiet settlement in the Blue Ridge Mountains. We
don't want anyone to preclude our right to use our name,'' said Bill
Dover of Hollywood, Ga., which he said was settled by his
great-great-grandfather in 1812. It is unincorporated, but then even
the Hollywood of movie fame is just a section of Los Angeles.
   The use of the name became an issue for Hollywood, Fla.,
residents and business leaders earlier this month when they learned
the Chamber of Commerce of Hollywood, Calif., had tried to register
the name with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.
   Florida city officials temporarily blocked the proposal.
   ``We're not going to pay a royalty to promote our own town in New
York,'' said Chris Garrett of the Hollywood, Fla., Chamber of
Commerce. ``We're not going to pay a dime.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW CANTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Codd attends Sunday school
religiously.
   He can boast of 70 years of nearly perfect attendance and has 70
attendance pins to show for it.
   ``Sunday school is a spiritual (boost) for me,'' said Codd, who
turned 80 Sunday and also leads a weekly Bible study for a group of
seven elderly people.
   ``I just enjoy the fellowship,'' he said.
   Getting there hasn't always been easy.
   At age 11, when Codd was visiting his grandmother in Chesterton,
Ind., a storm dumped 3 feet of snow.
   His uncle hitched a horse to a sleigh and got him to church; no
one else made it, but a church janitor initialed a card noting that
Codd had tried to attend.
   Codd received his first perfect attendance pin in 1916 from Grace
United Bretheran Church in Chicago. Two years later, the flu kept
him from receiving a pin, but he attended for 50 years from 1919 to
1969.
   Since then, Codd has missed Sunday school only three weeks
because of an operation and job obligations, he said.
   When traveling, Codd stops at the first church he comes upon.
   ``It doesn't matter what denomination (the church) is,'' he said.
``It's a shame we have so many denominations because the Sunday
school lessons and the people are about the same anywhere.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
