<FIRST>u i AM-Reporter'sNotebook 1stLd-Writethru a0609 02-23 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reporter's Notebook, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0609,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>After 27 Hours, Bush's Fire Didn't Go Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Corrects spelling of Venkataraman in grafs 9,10,12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 24 hours after he'd left Washington,
President Bush's inner fires were still burning as brightly on
Thursday as the blaze in the fireplace of the U.S. Embassy, where he
ended his long day meeting separately with six world leaders.
   At the end of his first day in Japan, Bush spent three hours
speaking with two prime ministers, three presidents and a king _ one
after another.
   Sometimes, being president means doing the same thing, over and
over again.
   This was the procedure, and it did not deviate:
   Into an ornate, high-ceilinged room in the U.S. Embassy _ the
very room where a victorious Gen. Douglas McArthur first received
the vanquished Emperor Hirohito _ Bush received leader after leader,
such as Thailand's Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan.
   ``Nice cozy fire here,'' said Bush, leading the prime minister to
one blue chair, taking the other, while photographers snapped away.
They were, maybe, the most photographed chairs in Tokyo.
   ``You came in today?'' the president asked. ``How long a flight
was that?''
   ``About five hours,'' said Choonhavan. Bush nodded.
   The press was ushered out as the two leaders and a handful of
aides from both countries moved to a circle of not-too-comfortable
looking chairs elsewhere in the room for about 20 minutes of
diplomatic icebreaking. Choonhavan got 22 minutes. India's President
Ramaswamy Venkataraman got 28. Jordan's King Hussein got 20.
   Bush to Venkataraman: ``Did you come direct?''
   Bush to Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak: ``How are all the
problems of the world?'' And, with a wave toward the press corps:
``We can't discuss it until they leave.''
   ``For heaven's sake!'' exclaimed Venkataraman when he saw the
fire in the fireplace.
   It was remarkable. Smokeless. Well drafted. The flames shot
straight up. In between dignitaries, an aide moved in with fresh
logs, feeding the flames.
   But Bush's fire finally appeared to sputter a bit after his
27-hour day.
   At the end of his final chat, a clearly tired president waved at
reporters and said: ``See you guys. Sleep well.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest cheer Bush heard all day _ the only noisy spontaneous
outburst of approval _ came hours and thousands of miles earlier, at
Elmendorf Air Force Base in Alaska. What brought it on was Bush's
suggestion to an audience of airmen, infantrymen and their families
that he'd like to return to Alaska _ to go fishing.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   It was at Elmendorf that Hirohito landed on the start of a 14-day
visit to the United States in 1975. During that trip, according to a
biographical sketch put out by the U.S. government, he acquired his
favorite American souvenir: a Mickey Mouse wristwatch.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. biographical sketch of Bush issued in connection with
this trip diplomatically glosses over his wartime experiences. It
says he won four decorations as a bomber pilot in the Pacific
Theater, but says nothing about having been shot down by the
Japanese.
   And the U.S.-issued biography of Bush's Japanese counterpart,
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, covers the period from his birth to
his graduation from college in 1947, skipping Takeshita's wartime
experience. He was a pilot trainee when the Japanese sued for peace
in 1945 after the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
