<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OzoneDanger     02-23 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ozone Danger,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arctic Faces Potential Ozone Time Bomb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental time bomb is ticking away
miles above the North Pole as chemicals there threaten to damage the
Earth's protective ozone layer, Sen. Albert Gore Jr. said Thursday.
   ``Stated as simply as possible, this is one of the most serious
environmental threats our planet faces,'' Gore, D-Tenn., said at a
hearing during which a team of scientists reported on a
just-completed study of the arctic atmosphere.
   Dr. Adrian Tuck, of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, said that while no direct evidence of arctic ozone
damage was found, scientists were surprised at the extent to which
conditions in that area show the potential for such damage.
   These threatening changes in the arctic atmosphere ``present a
virtual time bomb,'' Gore commented at a hearing of the Senate
Commerce subcommittee on science, technology and space.
   The North Pole study was conducted in an effort to determine if
that portion of the world has an ``ozone hole'' similar to that
detected over the South Pole in recent winters.
   Scientists are concerned about the seasonal depletion of ozone in
the air eight to 10 miles above the Earth's surface because it is
that layer that protects the planet from harmful ultraviolet
radiation from the sun. A 1 percent depletion of ozone worldwide
could lead to a 2 percent increase in skin cancer among fair-skinned
people, said Dr. Robert T. Watson of the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration.
   In addition, increased ultraviolet radiation could damage plants
and other life forms, including the plankton, krill and other ocean
life so vital to feed larger fish and animals, he said.
   Determining the extent of damage will not be easy, since little
research has been done and the NOAA budget for such studies was cut
annually under the Reagan Administration, said Sen. John F. Kerry,
D-Mass.
   Watson said scientists turned their attention to the north
because most of the world's people live in the northern hemisphere
and an ozone loss in that area could have even more significant
effects than in the south.
   The Antarctic ozone loss has been measured at as much as 50
percent in the southern winter, although the ozone is renewed in
summer as more air flows into that region from other areas.
   Good ozone statistics are lacking for other areas, Watson said,
although he estimated that between 1970 and 1988 the layer has been
depleted as much as 5 percent to 7 percent between 40 degrees North
latitude and 65 degrees North. That would be roughly between the
middle of the United States and the northern end of Norway.
   As to the arctic region itself, no significant loss was found in
the new study, but the region seemed poised on the brink, Tuck said.
   Dr. Susan Solomon of NOAA said the arctic study found increased
levels of chlorine _ the chemical blamed for the loss _ as well as
polar stratospheric clouds which can increase the rate of chemical
reactions which damage ozone.
   Chlorine migrates to high altitudes from a variety of sources
including refrigerants and other industrial chemicals. Many nations
signed a protocol in Montreal to reduce the use of these chemicals,
known as chlorofluorocarbons, but Watson said that agreement doesn't
go far enough.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
