<FIRST>u i AM-Bush Bjt   02-23 0948</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, Bjt,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Imperial Funeral, Bush Pursues Mideast Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be topped with developments, expected after 8:00 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush used the occasion of an imperial
Japanese funeral to pursue a Middle East peace, while his secretary
of state challenged the Soviet Union on Thursday to pitch in with
deeds instead of ``simply rhetorical exercises.''
   On the eve of services for the late Emperor Hirohito, Bush
engaged in around of fast-paced diplomacy, meeting with a succession
of world leaders including Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Israeli
President Chaim Herzog and Jordan's King Hussein.
   After Bush's round of meetings, Secretary of State James A. Baker
III challenged the Soviets to contribute to the peace process in a
``concrete way'' by establishing full diplomatic relations with
Israel, using its influence in Syria and denouncing ``radical
countries'' such as Libya.
   Baker said a ``new dynamic'' for peace existed in the area and
that Bush hoped to nurture it. The president's sessions with Mideast
leaders provided a counterpoint to Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze's 10-day tour through the region, where he attempted to
advance Moscow's role.
   On Friday, Bush was to attend an elaborate state funeral for the
late Japanese emperor, joining about 10,000 other Japanese and
foreign leaders in two giant, open-sided tents for the solemn
ceremony at Tokyo's Shinjuku Imperial Gardens. The park in downtown
Tokyo once served as the garden for the imperial household.
   Hirohito, the last of the World War II era world leaders, died
Jan. 7 of cancer at age 87 after reigning for six decades.
   In a meeting with Japan's Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita on
Thursday, Bush ``began by expressing the condolences of the American
people'' upon Hirohito's death, White House press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   First lady Barbara Bush, meanwhile, donned a tailored black suit
and an elegant strand of pearls to pay a visit Naoko Takeshita, the
wife of the Japanese prime minister.
   The two women sipped tea at Takeshita's official residence, with
Mrs. Bush expressing sympathy over Hirohito's death and the Mrs.
Takeshita offering congratulations on Bush's election as president.
   Bush's focus on the Middle East during his first overseas trip _
a five-day visit to three Asian capitals _ appeared to be an effort
to steal some of the spotlight from Shevardnadze's journey to the
area.
   Baker, briefing reporters after Bush's full day of meetings with
world leaders, said Soviet overtures to participate in a Middle East
peace were ``healthy, quite frankly.''
   But, he added, ``I suppose we would want to know that there were
concrete contributions that they had in mind, rather than simply
rhetorical exercises.''
   He said he would have a better idea of what the Soviets intend
when he meets with Shevardnadze in March in Vienna.
   Baker said contributing to the new dynamics for peace were talks
between the United States and the Palestine Liberation Organization
and statements by PLO leader Yasser Arafat denouncing terrorism.
   He said the United States intended to be active in the peace
process.
   However, he said ultimately a settlement would have to flow from
``direct negotiations between the Palestinians and the Israelis.''
   ``We are concerned that if we act too precipitously we might
preempt promising possibilities that could surface if we adopted a
more reasoned and measured approach,'' Baker added.
   Earlier, Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, said the subject
of a Middle East peace settlement also came up in a lunch with
French President Francois Mitterrand.
   ``We think there are some opportunities to move the (peace)
process forward,'' Fitzwater said. ``We want to be methodical and
deliberate in our approach.''
   Bush's seven hours of meetings with foreign leaders began
immediately after he stepped off Air Force One following a 16-hour
flight here from Washington.
   By the time he ended a day that had begun at 5 a.m. EST on
Wednesday, a clearly tired Bush waved at reporters and said: ``See
you guys. Sleep well.''
   His meetings also included sessions with Prime Minister Mario
Soares of Portugal, Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan of Thailand
and President Ramaswamy Venkataraman of India in back-to-back
meetings at the U.S. Embassy, a block away from the Okura Hotel,
where Bush and his entourage are staying.
   He also paid a courtesy call on Takeshita. The Japanese leader
had been Bush's first foreign visitor to the White House earlier
this month.
   Yukio Okamato, a Japanese Foreign Ministry official, said Bush
and Takeshita called each other by their first names, ``George'' and
``Noboru.''
   During the session, Bush, a former combat pilot, did not mention
his experience of being shot in the Pacific during World War II by
the Japanese, Okamato said.
   ``The Japanese people are deeply touched by President Bush's
basic position, that he is concerned with the present, not the
future,'' Okamato said. In the meeting with Takeshita at the richly
decorated Akasaka Palace, Bush discussed a range of issues,
including trade, the environment, East-West relations and Cambodia,
Fitzwater said.
   On Cambodia, Bush voiced concern that the withdrawal of
Vietnamese there was proceeding ``at a slower pace than we would
like to see,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``President Bush also emphasized that we would like to see a
government in Cambodia that would involve Prince Sihanouk and would
not see a return to the power of the Khmer Rouge,'' the spokesman
said.
   After Friday's funeral, Bush was expected to participate in still
more face-to-face sessions with foreign leaders, including
Philippine President Corazon Aquino.
   U.S. officials had said a meeting with Aquino had been hard to
arrange because of scheduling difficulties.
   The president was to have an audience with Japan's new Emperor
Akihito on Saturday, before visiting Beijing, China, and Seoul,
South Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
