<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a ballot-stuffing attempt on behalf of
another candidate, NBC anchorwoman Connie Chung turned out to be the
people's choice in a newspaper poll on who should replace Diane
Sawyer on CBS' ``60 Minutes.''
   After Sawyer said earlier this month she was jumping to ABC, the
New York Post asked readers to vote on a list of 17 candidates,
including one fictional character.
   At first count, another Sawyer looked like the winner, until
suspicious pollsters traced most of ABC anchorman Forrest Sawyer's
ballots to his agent, Arthur Kaminksy. He said the ballot stuffing
was just a joke.
   ``Murphy Brown made me do it,'' he quipped, referring to the fact
the Post included on its ballot the sitcom newswoman played by
Candice Bergen.
   Forrest Sawyer denied any knowledge of the ballot stuffing.
   Chung was declared the winner with 49 out of the 302 votes
declared valid. Leslie Stahl of CBS came in second with 29 votes.
