<HEAD>Ex-Paraguayan Requests Visa To Visit United States</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to CORRECT that Stroessner wants visa, not asylum.
No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfredo Stroessner, the deposed
Paraguayan president living in exile in Brazil, has requested a visa
to enter the United States, a Foreign Ministry official said today.
   The high-ranking official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said in a telephone interview that Stroessner was waiting for a
response to his visa request to join his wife and daughter in
Florida.
   News reports have said Stroessner is afraid of a possible
assassination attempt, but it was not clear if that prompted him to
request the visa.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said,
``As far as we're aware, we have no application for a visa and we
don't expect one.''
   ``We don't expect one because he's been granted asylum in Brazil.
He has his own house there. He has good medical care,'' Redman said.
   Stroessner, 76, a military dictator for 34 years in Paraguay, was
overthrown in a bloody coup Feb. 3 by his second-in-command in the
army, Gen. Andres Rodriguez. Stroessner arrived in Brazil on Feb. 5
and was granted political asylum in this country a day later.
   Stroessner, who spent three weeks in a guest house owned by a
government-run electric company in Itumbiara, 800 miles northwest of
Rio, has said he wants to spend the rest of his life in Brazil. But
news reports said today he is living in fear of a possible
assassination attempt.
   The privately-owned Rio newspaper Jornal do Brasil reported that
Luiz Melzer, federal police commissioner in charge of Stroessner's
security, said the former dictator did not feel safe in his
beachfront mansion in the Atlantic coastal resort of Guaratuba,
where he recently moved.
   Paulo Marra, a spokesman for the federal police, told the AP
today more security guards had been posted around the mansion and
that roadblocks had been put up on access roads. He did not say if
security was tightened in response to fears of an assassination
attempt.
   News reports said Stroessner only takes walks through a back
garden at night, with the garden lights out.
</TEXT>
