<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-AIDS     02-23 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-AIDS,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents of AIDS-Infected Area Face Discrimination, Writer Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of an area where more than two dozen
children were infected with the deadly AIDS virus are being pelted
with stones and asked to move away by fearful neighbors, a newspaper
reported Thursday.
   Writing in the government newspaper Izvestia, poet David
Kugultinov urged legislation banning discrimination against people
suffering from the virus.
   ``The mass media has so vividly described the dirt, roaches, mice
in our medical institutions, the low profession level of doctors,
nurses and sanitarians that unwillingly the impression has been
created that in all this the AIDS virus grew all by itself,'' he
wrote.
   In late January, the official media reported that 27 babies and
children had been infected with the virus in Elitsa, a city near the
Caspian Sea, by nurses using dirty syringes. Several mothers of the
children also were found to have been infected.
   Now, Kugultinov said, residents of nearby areas have begun
throwing stones at cars with Kalimkii license plates, ``as if the
cars are spreading AIDS.''
   ``The relationship to students leaving Kalimkii to study in
neighboring republics has sharply changed, voices are calling out,
demanding to separate them from the dormitories,`` he said.
   The poet said that the Soviet Union should follow the example of
the United States in seeking to prohibit discrimination against AIDS
victims.
   After long denying the existence of the disease in the Soviet
Union, officials have acknowledged that Soviets have been infected
and started a campaign against it. New regulations require
foreigners who want to stay in the Soviet Union more than three
months to prove they are free of AIDS.
   Since August 1987 it has been a crime to infect anyone with the
disease, and the official media has reported at least two AIDS
deaths.
   But the country cannot produce enough hypodermic needles and
syringes to avoid reusing them.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
