<FIRST>r i AM-India-Carbide     02-23 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court to Hear Petition from Group Opposed to Bhopal Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday agreed to
hear a petition from a social service group asking Union Carbide
Corp. to pay $600 million as liability for the 1984 Bhopal gas
disaster.
   The case will come up for a hearing Friday, a court official said.
   Legal experts, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it was a
legal duty of the Supreme Court to agree to hear the petition filed
by the Association For Socio-Legal Literacy.
   ``The court has already given its judgment, and both the parties,
the (Indian) government and the Union Carbide, have agreed to abide
by the order,'' said a Supreme Court lawyer, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The Supreme Court on Feb. 14 ordered the Danbury, Conn.-based
Union Carbide to pay $470 million to settle the Bhopal case. It was
not clear if the group wants $600 million to be paid in addition to
the $470 million or if it wants the $600 million to include the
earlier judgment.
   Gas leaked from the Indian subsidiary of the company in the
central Indian city of Bhopal on Dec. 3, 1984 and killed more than
3,400 people.
   The federal minister for industries, J. Vengala Rao, told
Parliament on Thursday the highest figure offered by Union Carbide
for the disaster was $300 million.
   ``Therefore, the settlement of $470 million was much higher and
it meant immediate availability of finance,'' Rao said.
   Opposition members, shouting ``Shame! Shame!'' walked out of the
house protesting the government support of the judgment.
   Rao made no mention of the petition by the social service group,
which was filed Wednesday.
   The Association For Socio-Legal Literacy filed the petition under
an article of the constitution allowing any individual or group to
ask the Supreme Court to seek constitutional remedies to a previous
judgment.
   The petition said the Supreme Court should not have disposed of
such ``an important case by a one-page order without giving
reasons.''
   The petition said the people have the right to know ``as to what
was the material before the court and what were the circumstances
and reasons to reach a conclusion that $470 million would absolve
Union Carbide of its liabilities and also satisfy the gas victims.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
