<DOCNO> AP890223-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SuperCollider     02-23 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super Collider,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>India First Foreign Nation to Aid Super Collider</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India has agreed to provide $50 million toward
the super collider atom smasher, making it the first foreign nation
to commit funds to the $4.6 billion project, a Texas congressman
told his colleagues Thursday.
   Officials of Japan, Taiwan, Korea and several Western European
nations have held preliminary cost-sharing discussions with U.S.
officials, Rep. Joe Barton told the energy research and development
subcommittee of the House Science, Space and Technology Committee.
   Barton is a Republican whose district includes the planned
collider site.
   Last year, Italy signed an agreement to explore collaboration on
the project. India is the first country to make a commitment.
   President Bush has endorsed the super collider and recommended
spending $250 million in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 toward
initial construction.
   The Energy Department has chosen a site around Waxahachie, Texas,
for the 53-mile underground tunnel in which beams of protons would
smash into each other with 20 times the energy of today's most
powerful atomic accelerators.
   Faced with heavy demands for funds for science projects, Congress
last year agreed only to spend $100 million on the project in the
current fiscal year and decreed none of the money could be used for
construction.
   Robert O. Hunter Jr., director of the office of energy research
at the Energy Department, confirmed Barton's disclosure of the
Indian contribution and said ``several hundred million dollars'' is
a minimum estimate for foreign contributions of particle-collision
detectors to the project, but the exact sum won't be known for
another year or two.
   Though Hunter said foreign contributions could be substantial, he
did not repeat predictions of department officials about a year ago
that foreign countries could pay up to half the cost of the machine.
   Such large installations are used by scientists of all nations
and foreign contributions are usually made to speed a project along,
not in return for specific agreements for research time, said
department spokesman Jeff Sherwood.
   The agreement with India calls for a contribution of $50 million
``in kind'' _ that is, equipment or services _ contingent upon a
U.S. commitment to build the collider, Hunter said.
   The $4.6 billion cost is the lump-sum equivalent of all future
federal spending expressed in dollars of 1988 buying power. The
Office of Management and Budget has used a figure of $5.9 billion in
inflated dollars of future years, of which the Energy Department
expects $1.8 billion to come from non-federal sources.
   At least some of the $1 billion being contributed by the state of
Texas will be counted in that $1.8 billion, said Sherwood, but it is
not clear that all of that is for items in the department's collider
budget.
   The project still faces high hurdles in Congress, which must
provide substantial funds for construction this year if the collider
is to operate in 1996, as the department would like.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Balloonist     02-23 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloonist,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescued Balloonist Says He's Embarrassed but Will Try Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOKOHAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who tried to become the first person
to cross the Pacific alone in a balloon said Thursday he is
embarrassed he had to be rescued but is confident he'll succeed on
the next attempt.
   ``When I first recognized the Japanese flag on an aircraft flying
beside my gondola, I thought I was safe,'' Fumio Niwa told a news
conference after returning home. ``But I became a bit worried when
no one came to save me for some time after landing.''
   ``Half an hour or so later, I lost consciousness because of
severe seasickness and do not remember what happened,'' he said of
his rescue after more than 10 hours bobbing in the Pacific in the
18-foot plastic gondola.
   Uncooperative winds last week forced the 38-year-old balloonist
to abandon his Pacific crossing and drop into the sea Saturday. He
was less than halfway to his target in southern California.
   A coast guard rescue vessel returned him Thursday to Yokohama,
where he started his flight Feb. 15.
   Niwa, who quit his job with a computer firm to attempt the
crossing, landed in the water about 1,560 miles southwest of Tokyo.
He said he regained consciousness when his gondola hit something.
   ``I looked out the window and there were blinding lights outside,
and I realized there was a ship right next to my gondola,'' he said.
   He was picked up first by a Japanese fishing boat operating
nearby and transferred the next day to a patrol vessel of the
Maritime Safety Agency, Japan's coast guard.
   Niwa said he felt embarrassed by his failure.
   His flight encountered trouble from the start as high-speed winds
that usually blow toward California veered sharply to the north,
forcing him to stay at lower altitudes in slower winds.
   ``On the radio, I fought my navigators' and sponsors' idea to
quit the flight until the very last minute, but I had no choice when
I was told: `You know we are not going to make it now. So why don't
we quit bravely before troubling other people any further.'''
   Japanese officials said it cost about $560,000 to rescue Niwa.
   Asked if he would try the solo crossing again, Niwa said: ``Of
course. I miscalculated and underestimated the winds this time, but
I think I got a taste of it. After reviewing the failure this time,
I can confidently say I can make it next time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
