<FIRST>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral Bjt   02-23 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral, Bjt,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Write-In Candidacy Could Create Problems for Daley's Mayoral Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Alderman Ed Vrdolyak made life tough for
the father and now, by jumping into the mayor's race just days
before the primaries, he aims to do the same for the son.
   But Democratic front-runner Richard M. Daley, whose father ran
the city for 20 years, insisted Thursday that Vrdolyak's Republican
write-in candidacy would not siphon off enough votes to keep him
from defeating acting Mayor Eugene Sawyer in Tuesday's Democratic
primary.
   ``I'm going to win the primary and the general election,'' Daley,
the Cook County state's attorney, said at a campaign stop.
   Vrdolyak, 51, a Democrat-turned-Republican from a gritty, mostly
white working-class enclave, announced his write-in candidacy late
Wednesday.
   Daley immediately accused him of trying to be a spoiler without
any real expectation of victory. ``The people are smarter than
that,'' Daley said. ``He thinks he's going to fool the people. He's
not going to fool anyone.''
   Vrdolyak denied on Thursday that he was entering to spoil Daley's
chances. Voters would be foolish to think a Republican ``can go in
and upset a Democratic primary where the two candidates have spent
$8 million and, in five days, upset the campaign,'' he said.
   Most political observers believe too few white ethnic voters _
Daley's core constituency _ would cross over and vote for Vrdolyak
to hand Sawyer an upset victory. Both Vrdolyak and Daley are white;
Sawyer is black.
   The most recent polls published in the Chicago Sun-Times and
Chicago Tribune show Daley, 46, heading into the final weekend
before the primary with a lead of between eight and 12 percentage
points over Sawyer.
   Vrdolyak has beaten the political odds in the past.
   He survived a series of City Council run-ins early in his
aldermanic career with Daley's father, Richard J. Daley, and rose to
the top of the local Democratic heap before defecting to the GOP
late in 1987.
   But few political observers doubt Vrdolyak can muster enough
votes to overtake the Republican Party's endorsed candidate,
61-year-old urologist Dr. Herbert Sohn.
   That despite Sohn's brave prediction that he would end Vrdolyak's
political career and ``be the one that drives the spike through
Count Dracula's heart.''
   Eugene Kennedy, a Loyola University professor and author of
``Himself,'' a biography of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, said
Vrdolyak's impact on the younger Daley's candidacy would be limited
by a number of factors.
   Most important, Kennedy said, is that Sawyer, 54, does not
command the monolithic black support that installed the late Harold
Washington as the city's first black mayor in 1983 and re-elected
him four years later.
   ``The number of black voters is down significantly. On top of
that,'' Kennedy added, ``a handful of black leaders are working
against Sawyer and for (black third-party candidate) Tim Evans. And
that doesn't even begin to address how strong Daley's own political
organization is.''
   Vrdolyak, however, is not without an impressive organization of
his own.
   During a five-year stint as city and county Democratic Party
chairman and 18 years as alderman, Vrdolyak delivered votes for
himself and state and national Democrats with a consistency matched
by few political peers.
   Even after stepping outside the Democratic party to make a
third-party run at Washington in the 1987 mayoral election, his
personal popularity was such that Vrdolyak still captured 18,000
votes of the 25,000 votes in his ward.
</TEXT>
