<HEAD>Soviet Military Praised on Afghanistan Role</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet soldiers showed their best qualities in
Afghanistan and were a major factor in maintaining world peace, the
defense minister said Thursday.
   Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov praised the military in a special
``Order of the Day'' to mark the 71st anniversary of the nation's
army and navy.
   Moscow streets and buildings were bedecked with red national and
military flags for the anniversary.
   The anniversary came eight days after the last Soviet soldiers
withdrew from Afghanistan, putting an end to a nine-year engagement
that cost 15,000 lives and left about 35,000 wounded.
   ``Soviet soldiers showed again their best qualities when
fulfilling the internationalist duty in the republic of Afghanistan,
during the elimination of the consequences of the accident at the
Chernobyl nuclear power station and of the earthquakes in Armenia
and Tadzhikistan,'' Yazov said.
   Military troops were deployed following the April 1986 nuclear
plant disaster and sent to help victims of the earthquakes that hit
the republics in December and January.
   Yasov said the overall threat to peace has been rolled back.
``This is largely due to the new initiatives of the Soviet state
aimed at radical improvement of international relations, the
U.S.S.R.'s decision on unilateral reduction of its armed forces and
armaments.''
   He said the United States and NATO should take similar actions.
