<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     02-23 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three PLO Guerrillas Killed In Infiltration Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli-backed militiamen patrolling southern
Lebanon on Thursday shot and killed three guerrillas from a radical
PLO faction who were on their way to attack a target in Israel, an
army spokesman said.
   The Marxist guerrilla group, the Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, said in a statement that the three fighters
killed three Israeli soldiers and two Christian militiamen before
they were gunned down.
   The army official said on condition of anonymity that no
militiamen were hurt in the clash, and he made no mention of Israeli
troops being involved.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official, also speaking privately,
said the attempted infiltration was ``another example of the
inability of the PLO to fulfill its declared statement of stopping
terror.''
   In a related development, a top aide to Labor Party leader Shimon
Peres urged the Israeli government to reverse its stand and open
talks with the Palestine Liberation Organization if the group
abandons terror.
   Yossi Beilin, deputy finance minister, said the PLO has not yet
met the condition, but he told Israel television: ``If this happens,
we would be ready to talk with them.''
   In clashes in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, six
Palestinians were wounded by army gunfire, including a 16-year-old
girl shot in the stomach, Arab doctors said. The army confirmed five
wounded and said it was checking further.
   At least 385 Palestinians have died in the 14-month uprising,
along with 16 Israelis.
   In the West Bank village of Aqaba, 19-year-old shepherd Mohammed
Mahmoud Kassem was wounded in the face and hands when an explosive
device went off as he grazed his sheep, said doctors at Al Ittihad
Hospital in the nearby city of Nablus.
   Two Palestinians have been killed and a dozen wounded by
unidentified explosives in recent weeks, and the army has launched
an investigation.
   The three PLO guerrillas were killed about a mile north of the
Israeli border in Israel's self-declared security zone.
   A South Lebanon Army patrol spotted the squad about a mile north
of the village of Al Jibbayn and opened fire, the army official said.
   Documents found on the guerrillas' bodies showed they were
members of Naif Hawatmeh's Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, a radical faction of the PLO, the officialsaid.
   The guerrillas carried three Soviet-designed Kalashnikov rifles,
a rocket-propelled grenade launcher, large quantities of grenades,
food and wirecutters, the army said.
   ``They were on their way to attack a target in Israel,'' said the
official, adding that the equipment carried by the guerrillas showed
``they were not picnicking.''
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat renounced terrorism during the Palestine
National Council meeting in November, but the PLO feels this
definition does not apply to military confrontations or attacks on
military targets.
   Thursday's attempted infiltration was the second by a radical PLO
faction since Arafat launched a diplomatic initiative in December
and the United States renewed talks with the PLO.
   On Feb. 5, Israeli troops killed five guerrillas on the northern
border of security zone, and the army said the squad was en route to
attack a target in Israel. Three of the guerrillas belonged to the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a PLO faction.
</TEXT>
