<FIRST>u i AM-Korea-US     02-23 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Battle Police; Pyongyang Says Bush Visit Makes War More
Likely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students showered riot police
with rocks and firebombs Thursday despite stern government warnings
and burned an effigy of President Bush. North Korea said Bush's
visit next week will increase the danger of war.
   The students from Chungang University fought police for 40
minutes in front of the Seoul school. They also burned an effigy of
President Roh Tae-woo before dispersing.
   ``Punish Chun Doo-hwan and oust Roh Tae-woo!'' the students
shouted.
   Chun Doo-hwan, Roh's predecessor, stepped down last February and
is under acute criticism for corruption and misdeeds during his
seven-year administration.
   The United National Democratic Movement, an umbrella organization
for more than 200 dissident groups, said it is planning major
anti-American rallies on Monday, when Bush comes for a five-hour
visit.
   The North Korean government newspaper Minju Choson said that
during his visit Bush will be ``examining the preparations for a new
war on the spot and pushing ahead with the U.S. aggressive plan to
carry its Korea and Asia strategy into practice.''
   He also seeks to ``threaten the people who have risen in the
anti-U.S., anti-dictatorship struggle for reunification and defuse
the serious crisis of the colonial rule,'' said the paper's
commentary, broadcast in part by North Korea's official Korean
Central News Agency, monitored in Tokyo.
   ``Bush's visit to South Korea will only result in further
encouraging the South Korean puppets to fascism and confrontation,
increasing the danger of war and permanent division and laying
greater obstacles in the way of reunification,'' the statement said.
   Thursday's clash between students and police followed Roh's
warning that he will not tolerate further acts of violence.
   In a meeting with governing party officials, he reaffirmed a
government plan to clamp down on the protests beginning this weekend.
   Roh said radical groups are trying to overthrow the government
through revolutionary means. He said the government and society must
be prepared to fight the radicals.
</TEXT>
