<FIRST>r w AM-Weicker     02-23 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weicker,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weicker To Head New Group To Promote Medical Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr., R-Conn., a
leading advocate for medical research during his 18 years in the
Senate, will become head of a new non-profit organization to promote
such research and increase government funding.
   Weicker, who lost his bid for a fourth Senate term by less than 1
percentage point in November, will become president and chief
executive officer of ``Research! America,'' which will open its
doors in Alexandria, Va., this spring, said publicist Jane Miller.
   Weicker would not discuss details of the new organization,
pointing to a news conference in Washington on Monday.
   Terry Lierman, a Washington lobbyist who founded the group, said
the organization will not lobby Capitol Hill, but instead take its
message _ with Weicker as the point man _ around the country to
educate the public and rally citizens' support to put additional
pressure on Congress.
   Lierman, president of Capitol Associates Inc., a Washington
lobbying firm specializing in health-related issues, said the new
group plans to spend about $3 million a year on an education
campaign that will feature Weicker speaking around the country.
   Research! America will act as an umbrella group for a wide range
of academic, fund-raising, industry and research groups, including
the National Multiple Sclerosis Society, Cystic Fibrosis Foundation,
American Association of Universities, American Association of
Medical Colleges, and Upjohn Co.
</TEXT>
