<FIRST>u a AM-Andrus-Waste     02-23 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Andrus-Waste,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Idaho Governor Reopens Border To Colorado Nuke Waste</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Cecil Andrus on Thursday partially
lifted his four-month-old ban on shipments of nuclear waste bound
for temporary storage at the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory,
citing national security concerns.
   But shipments will be allowed only from the U.S. Department of
Energy's Rocky Flats weapons plant in Colorado, and only for the
next six months, he said.
   ``We have not thrown the borders open, and we will not,'' Andrus
said.
   The governor said he had agreed to allow the department to
transfer two railroad boxcars per month from the Rocky Flats site
near Denver.
   An average of four boxcars per month were shipped from the
Colorado plant to the laboratory before Andrus closed Idaho's
borders to waste shipments Oct. 19.
   Lifting the ban on shipments will allow Rocky Flats to remain
open and give the Energy Department time to clear up problems that
have delayed opening of its Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a permanent
waste storage site near Carlsbad, N.M.
   ``I do not relish the job of once again pulling their chestnuts
out of the fire,'' Andrus said. ``But it is obvious to me that DOE
has no alternative short of closing Rocky Flats and precipitating a
national security crisis.''
   Because there already are thousands of boxcar loads of waste at
the INEL, Andrus said, ``12 more really won't make that much
difference to us.''
   Nuclear waste is building up at Rocky Flats, and the plant could
be weeks away from reaching its limit of 1,600 cubic yards of
material, said Rich Marquez, an Energy Department spokesman in
Albuquerque, N.M.
   Colorado Gov. Roy Romer had threatened to shut down Rocky Flats
if waste storage reached capacity.
   ``Sooner or later we were going to bump into the ceiling,''
Marquez said. ``This gives us some breathing room.''
   The INEL is the only facility in the nation other than Rocky
Flats that can accept the waste right now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
