<FIRST>u w AM-ArmsDirector     02-23 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Director,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Negotiator in Line to Head Arms Control Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Defense Secretary Ronald F. Lehman, a
former U.S. negotiator, will be named director of the U.S. Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency and Margo Carlisle, another top
Pentagon official, will be his deputy, Bush administration and
congressional sources said Thursday.
   Lehman was in charge of strategic weapons reduction talks with
the Soviets in Geneva from 1985 to 1988 when he moved to the
Pentagon to take charge of international security policy in the
closing months of the Reagan administration.
   Ms. Carlisle, who is close to Senate conservatives, is the
Pentagon's chief liaison to Congress and like Lehman holds the title
of assistant secretary of defense. She is a former aide to Sen.
James A. McClure, R-Idaho, and was staff director of the Senate
Republican Conference.
   The sources, who declined to be identified, said the nominations
would be sent to the Senate for approval.
   The arms control agency, created by Congress in 1962, usually
cooperates closely with the State Department where it has most of
its offices. Lehman will head a staff of about 250 people and act as
a principal adviser on arms control issues to President Bush and
Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   However, Brent Scowcroft, the president's assistant for national
security affairs, is considered likely to play a more prominent role
in decisions on how to negotiate with the Soviet Union on reducing
nuclear, conventional and chemical weapns.
   Lehman, 43, has close ties to former Sen. John G. Tower, whose
nomination as defense secretary is facing opposition in the Senate
Armed Services Committee. Lehman worked for Tower when he was
chairman of the committee and later succeeded him as chief
negotiator with the Soviets in Geneva on strategic nuclear arms.
   He apparently won the endorsement of Baker while traveling with
him last week to the 15 countries that are U.S. allies in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization. Lehman had been making tentative plans
to return to private life in northern California.
   Baker, in testifying Tuesday before the House Foreign Affairs
Committee, said he expected the head of the agency to operate
primarily as a technical adviser to Bush rather than as an
independent voice in policy disputes.
   The agency has been headed since last April by William F. Burns,
a retired major general.
</TEXT>
