<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FarmExports     02-23 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Exports,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Up More Than Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both the value and tonnage of U.S. farm exports
are recovering at a faster pace than expected three months ago, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   ``Increased demand for U.S. grain has boosted the forecast for
U.S. agricultural exports in fiscal 1989 to $38 billion and 145
million (metric) tons,'' the report said.
   That would mean an 8 percent in export values from $35.3 billion
in the 1988 fiscal year that ended last Sept. 30 and the most since
1984 when they totaled $38 billion.
   However, the actual volume, forecast at 145 million tons, would
be down from 148.3 million tons last year.
   In November, USDA predicted exports at $36.5 billion and a
decline in volume to 136 million tons.
   The new figures represent ``a gain of $1.5 billion and 9 million
tons since the November forecast,'' the report said. ``Larger
prospective corn imports by the (Soviet Union) account for much of
the expansion. Also, competitor corn production and exports are
lower than forecast in November.''
</TEXT>
