<FIRST>u w AM-Sullivan 1stLd-Writethru a0685 02-23 0946</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Wins Easy Committee Approval; Abortion Issue Disappearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with additional senators' votes, Armstrong comment,
subbing 2nd graf and inserting 2 grafs after 14th graf pvs, ``Like President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis Sullivan, nominated as President
Bush's first black Cabinet secretary, won overwhelming support
Thursday from a Senate Finance Committee that showed no interest in
prolonging controversy over his abortion views.
   The panel voted 19-0 to recommend to the full Senate Sullivan's
confirmation to be secretary of health and human services. The vote,
on which Sen. William L. Armstrong, R-Colo., had himself recorded as
``present,'' came after a two-hour hearing in which both Republicans
and Democrats spent much less time on abortion than on sympathy over
Sullivan's apparent sacrifice of $300,000 to take the government job.
   Sullivan did address the subject of abortion, a main point of
controversy in recent weeks, in his opening testimony, reading a
series of sentences that echoed the position taken by Bush. He
apologized to committee member Bob Packwood, R-Ore., for having
``misspoken'' on the subject during a private meeting.
   He was not asked about it during subsequent questioning, in which
senators asked him about such major programs as Medicare and Social
Security that will come under his jurisdiction as head of the
114,000-employee department that administers fully a third of all
federal spending.
   Indeed, the only senator who brought abortion up directly was
Packwood, who said the issue had been blown out of proportion and
the HHS secretary really has little to do with substantive decisions
on abortion.
   ``I do not understand the disproportionate attention,'' said
Packwood, who disagrees with the position Sullivan stated in his
testimony.
   ``My side of this issue has lost ... on the floor of the
Congress,'' said Packwood, noting that, by congressional direction,
few abortions are financed with federal money.
   Saying that the HHS chief has no authority over private
abortions, Packwood told Sullivan, ``The questions that people ask
(of you) might appropriately be asked of the Department of Justice
where we apparently are going to litigate this matter for a number
of years.''
   That was a reference to Bush's assertion that he favors reversal
of the 1973 Supreme Court decision, in a case entitled Roe vs. Wade,
that legalized abortion.
   In his opening remarks, Sullivan had apologized to Packwood for
having ``misspoken'' his position on abortion in their meeting.
Packwood had indicated after that meeting that Sullivan had said he
did not want Roe vs. Wade overturned, a position similar to one
Sullivan had been quoted as taking in an earlier interview with the
Atlanta Journal Constitution.
   He told the committee on Thursday:
   ``I am opposed to abortion, except when the life of the mother is
threatened, or cases of rape or incest.
   ``I support a human life amendment, embracing the exceptions just
noted.
   ``Like President Bush, I would welcome a Supreme Court decision
overturning Roe vs. Wade.''
   As for Armstrong, the Colorado senator said he might vote for
Sullivan on the floor of the Senate but was voting ``present'' in
committee to express his displeasure that Sullivan would not state a
public position on research use of tissue from intentionally aborted
fetuses.
   Sullivan said he had not reviewed the recommendations of a
National Institutes of Health advisory committee convened to study
the fetal tissue issue and wanted to do that before deciding.
   Another controversy that had swirled around Sullivan's nomination
concerned an arrangement with Morehouse College in Atlanta, where he
founded the predominantly black institution's medical school. Under
the arrangement, he could have received about $300,000 in severance
benefits built up over his 32-year association with the school.
   Sullivan told the committee he decided to forfeit the money
because _ ``as the issue was presented in the press'' _ he was
concerned that it would raise ethical questions that might hamper
his effectiveness.
   ``I was also concerned about the image of Morehouse,'' he said.
   ``I know it's a tremendous privilege to work with us, but I don't
think you ought to have go through a toll booth where the charge is
$300,000,'' said Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I.
   ``It is grossly unfair to him and has nothing at all to do with
ethics,'' said Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo. ``You have forgone
benefits ... you have earned. ... It just doesn't seem right to me.''
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, the Texas Democrat who chairs the committee,
said he, too, was concerned about what appeared to be ``undue
sacrifice'' made by Sullivan, and he told the nominee just prior to
the panel's vote that he would ``probe'' the matter further.
   Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, the Senate Republican leader, was the
only member to mention Sullivan's race.
   ``There are a few cynics in this town, not all in the media, and
there are some who will say, `Well, we're greasing it for Dr.
Sullivan, the only black appointed by president, and therefore he'll
get through,'' Dole said.
   He invited Sullivan to comment.
   ``I believe and I hope I was asked to serve ... because of my
qualifications that I bring, both as a physician and because of my
life experiences,'' said Sullivan.
   ``I think the fact that I am black should be incidental. But I
also do represent an important constituency. I believe we have a
government that works best when we have representatives of all
segments of our society.''
   ``I am black and I am proud of that fact. But I am equally if not
more proud of what I have been able to accomplish and what I hope to
accomplish as secretary of health and human services,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
