<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan     02-23 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Resumes Aid; Prime Minister Says Army Threat Lifted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Red Cross on Thursday said it has
resumed shipping food and medicine to starving masses in the
southern Sudan after reaching agreements with government and rebel
forces in the region.
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi, meanwhile, indicated the military had
lifted or extended its ultimatum to the government. The army said
Wednesday it was giving the government one week to begin talks with
rebels and institute reforms.
   Bernard Juler, acting director of the International Committee of
the Red Cross, said the relief airlift resumed Wednesday and that
three aircraft already had reached Wau, capital of the southern Bahr
el-Ghazal region, 625 miles south of Khartoum.
   The Red Cross got approval from the government and the rebel
Sudan People's Liberation Army in December to airlift supplies to
government- and rebel-held areas in the south.
   Aid has been hampered because rebels have been shooting at
civilian and military flights there, claiming the army uses relief
planes to transport supplies.
   The Red Cross airlift was abruptly stopped two weeks ago.
   ``It was only technical questions and we have overcome that. We
have supplied both the government and the (rebels) with new (flight)
programs and schedules and we obtained the OK,'' Juler said.
   Juler said there would be two daily flights, each carrying about
17 tons of supplies.
   The flights to the government-held towns leave from Khartoum and
those for rebel-held areas depart airports in northeast Kenya.
   The southern rebels took up arms against the government in 1983,
demanding more autonomy and economic reforms.
   Information Minister Beshir Omar quoted Mahdi as saying Thursday
that the military has assured the prime minister that its Wednesday
ultimatum was not final. Mahdi then met with his Cabinet in an
emergency meeting.
   All of Khartoum's papers on Wednesday reported that the army
issued Mahdi a one-week ultimatum either to resign or to reform his
government and begin peace talks with rebels.
   A military spokesman, Mohamed Osman Malik, said the military made
``certain demands'' but he would not characterize it as a coup
threat.
   The warning came one day after Mahdi accepted the resignation of
Defense Minister Abdel-Magid Khalil, who stepped down to protest of
the government's refusal to accept a peace agreement negotiated by a
major political party.
   Communist Party Secretary-General Mohamed Ibrahim Nugud said
Mahdi told political leaders that there was ``no connection whatever
between the resignation of the Sudanese defense minister and the
memorandum submitted by the army.''
   The civil war costs the government an estimated $1 million daily.
Western relief workers believe that in 1988 alone, more than half a
million southerners died from starvation caused by the war or from
the fighting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
