<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Kemp-Conservatives     02-23 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kemp-Conservatives,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Conservatives</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kemp Asks Conservatives to Work with Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp defended his appeals to
liberals and civil rights activists before the Republican Party's
right wing Thursday and invited the conservatives to join in the
Bush administration.
   ``I want you to participate in this administration,'' the
secretary of housing and urban development told the Conservative
Political Action Conference.
   ``Ronald Reagan started the revolution,'' Kemp said. ``I'll bet
you right here and now, today, that George Bush, President Bush,
will consolidate it, strengthen it, broaden it, broaden its appeal.
I hope to bring it into the inner city.''
   The meeting is a gathering of more than 40 conservative groups,
led by the American Conservative Union and the Young Americans for
Freedom, a politically conservative organization for youth.
   Kemp, a conservative who had the backing of many in the audience
when he ran for the Republican presidential nomination last year,
was asked by one conservative supporter about his recent meetings
with civil rights leaders, who are also Democrats. The questioner
asked whether he was overlooking conservative blacks who have
supported Republicans in the past.
   ``I want to visit with all people,'' Kemp responded.
   ``Look, don't worry. Everybody is going to be heard,'' he added.
``It's what you do and who you follow and what kind of ideas you
express that we ought to judge our final results by.''
   Kemp met with several black leaders, including the widow and sons
of Martin Luther King Jr., during a tour of Atlanta neighborhoods
last week.
   After the meeting with conservatives, Kemp departed for his
second trip as secretary, touring shelters and programs for the
homeless in Baltimore and Philadelphia.
   Kemp also commented on the ethics statement he had signed to
accept the Cabinet position, saying: ``I promised on my ethics
statement that I would never, ever, ever make any money again in my
whole life. That's what it feels like, almost.''
   Kemp's wide-ranging remarks also brought him to the subject of
the Federal Reserve's monetary policy where the former congressman,
an avid advocate of tax cuts and supply-side economics, stopped
himself:
   ``I'm not going to get into Federal Reserve Board policy because
that's not my portfolio. I lust for that portfolio, but I don't have
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
