<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Irish-PeaceDay     02-23 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish-Peace Day,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Peace Day Rallies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Protestants and
Roman Catholics attended Peace Day rallies Thursday in Northern
Ireland and expressed hope for an end to violence in the British
province.
   Church bells rang in many towns to support the event, organized
by Belfast city council members from four political parties and a
group called Women Together To Bring Peace toNorthern Ireland.
   In a joint statement, the organizers pledged ``full solidarity''
for peace and an end to all terrorist activity in Northern Ireland.
   Sectarian violence between Roman Catholics and the Protestant
majority since August 1969 has taken 2,722 lives, 93 of them in 1988
and 11 so far this year.
   About 4,000 people gathered outside the Belfast City Hall, many
wearing white badges.
   Other rallies took place in Londonderry, Eniskillen, Lurgan,
Banbridge, Bangor, Greenisland and Whitehead, and a Peace Day
service was held in St. Anne's Church of Ireland Cathedral in
Belfast.
   ``White for peace is the theme of the day, and we urged everyone
to wear something white to show their support for the campaign,''
said Joanne Elliott, coordinator of Women Together.
   Political parties supporting the observance were the Official
Unionist Party, the largest Protestant party; Social Democratic and
Labor, the largest Catholic party, the centrist Alliance Party,
which draws support from both religious groups, and the Worker's
Party, an offshoot of the socialist Labor Party in Britain.
   In London, Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King told a luncheon of
the Association of American Correspondents there was growing
evidence the people of in the province want an end to violence.
   He said the importance of secret talks in West Germany last
October among politicians from both sides was ``that people right
across both communities, far from being shocked and appalled, were
encouraged and pleased and looked to see that process continue.''
   The talks centered on the possibilty of a power-sharing agreement
to run the province, which now is governed from London.
   King said it was too early to predict results, ``but it is
certainly progress.'' He said he had ``no high ambitions for speedy
progress'' and would not set targets ``which some might enjoy
defeating.''
</TEXT>
