<FIRST>r w AM-IndianInvestigation     02-23 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Investigation,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Suggest White House Name Staffer to Coordinate Indian Affairs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three senators investigating problems on Indian
reservations said Thursday there should be a White House staff
member designated to work primarily on issues affecting native
Americans.
   ``This designation would send a signal throughout the Indian
communities of your dedication to America's first inhabitants,''
Sens. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., John McCain, R-Ariz., and Thomas
Daschle, D-S.D., said in a letter to President Bush.
   The senators, members of the Senate Select Committee on Indian
Affairs, have been conducting special investigative hearings on a
wide range of problems on reservations and within government
agencies doing business with them.
   Saying they wanted to meet with whomever Bush designates soon
after the appointment, the senators predicted their hearings would
produce legislative proposals to correct longtime deficiencies in
government policies toward Indians.
   In the meantime, they said, a more formal, institutionalized
process for coordinating Indian affairs policies could begin at the
White House.
   There was no immediate response from the White House to the
letter. Bush was in Japan for the funeral of the late Emperor
Hirohito.
   The senators said testimony before their committee ``raises
significant concerns about whether the United States is adequately
fulfilling its fiduciary duties to protect the property rights of
American Indians' rights to land, water, forest, hunting, fishing
and mineral resources.
   ``As we are sure you will agree, legal representation is at the
very core of the federal government's trust responsibility to
American Indians. The inherent conflicts facing the federal trustee
arise not only in legal matters, but also in policy decisions.''
   They cited as one major shortcoming in U.S. policy President
Reagan never having appointed anyone to work on Indian affairs
despite establishing a policy of dealing with Indians on a
``government-to-government basis'' and promising to fulfill federal
responsibilities to them.
</TEXT>
