<FIRST>r w AM-DCDrugs-Guard     02-23 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC Drugs-Guard,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Guard Plans to Help Police Battle Drugs; Ministers Seek
Curfew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Guard of the District of Columbia
is planning to help city police in the fight against drugs in the
nation's capital, but guardsmen would not be used in street patrols,
Guard officials said Thursday.
   Meantime, more than 30 ministers from drug-plagued city
neighborhoods urged Mayor Marion Barry Jr. to put more police on
patrols, and sought a curfew that would prohibit teen-agers from
gathering between midnight and 6 a.m. on streets where drug sales
are most common.
   ``The feeling is, we've had enough,'' said H.R. Crawford, a City
Council member, who set up the ministers' meeting with the mayor.
``The talking is over _ we simply need to see some action. Too many
people are dying.'' Barry was not immediately available to comment
on the ministers' requests.
   City police officials have asked the Guard if it could help in
the battle against the drug trade. Police blame the trade for 60
percent of last year's record 372 killings in the city. So far this
year, 84 people have been slain in the district compared with 52 at
this time a year ago.
   Before the Guard can begin providing equipment or expertise, the
plan must be approved by the defense and justice departments, but
Guard officials said they expect approval and hope to start the
program in the next 60 days.
   Maj. Gen. Calvin Franklin of the D.C. National Guard said the
Pentagon has given preliminary approval to fund a $300,000 project.
   ``We have put together a detailed comprehensive drug operation
and support plan in concert with the district police department that
will help fight the drug problem,'' Franklin said. ``It could
involve the D.C. Guard using helicopters and night-vision devices to
assist in monitoring and detection of illegal drugs.''
   Guardsmen would not be involved in street patrols. ``We would be
concerned about having armed military personnel on the street to get
involved in arresting people,'' Franklin said. ``When you put a
soldier out there in uniform, he would make an ideal target for a
drug operator wanting to send out a signal _ he'd make a target.''
   The plan calls for the Guard to train city police in the use of
night-viewing devices, sophisticated radar systems and other
equipment the police do not have.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
