<DOCNO> AP890223-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0695 02-23 0980</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0695,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contra Leader Says Money He Gave North Wasn't for Personal Use</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Calero, Gesell comments, subbing 10 grafs for grafs
5-8 pvs, Calero one ... our problems,'' editing at end to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebel leader Adolfo Calero testified
Thursday in Oliver North's criminal trial that he hadn't expected
North to make personal use of any of the $90,000 Calero gave him to
help free American hostages in Lebanon.
   ``I had absolute trust in what Colonel North was doing so I was
not intent in demanding an accounting'' for the money, Calero said.
``He said that he had an accounting. We talked about getting it, but
I guess I never got around to it.''
   Prosecutor John Keker asked Calero if he expected North, who is
charged with embezzling $4,300 of the money, to spend any of it on
himself.
   No, said Calero.
   Later, North's attorney asked whether Calero complained to the
government that North ``misappropriated any of the traveler's checks
you gave him?''
   ``Not at all, to anyone,'' said Calero. ``To this day I believe
he acted properly.''
   Calero also said he wasn't disturbed that North gave $1,000 of
the traveler's checks as a wedding gift to Robert W. Owen, a former
aide to North who served as North's courier in Contra dealings. Owen
is to be the next witness Friday.
   In a light moment during a long day of testimony. Calero said he
never took notes at his many meetings with North, adding that ``I
never dreamed I would be here.'' Said U.S. District Judge Gerhard A.
Gesell: ``We can all say that!''
   Calero also brought laughter to the courtroom when he said he
felt so close to the late CIA Director William Casey that he
referred to him ``very dearly as `Uncle Bill.'''
   Calero, one of the top leaders of the Nicaraguan rebels, known as
Contras, testified that he gave North money in traveler's checks
after the White House aide ``mentioned the need to help rescue
Americans held hostage.''
   The money came from a Miami bank account that had received $32
million in deposits in eight months after Calero gave North the
account number, he testified.
   The money began flowing in, he said, in June 1984, soon after
official United States financial support for the Nicaraguan
guerrillas was barred by Congress.
   ``I informed Colonel North of everything I did,'' Calero said.
``He was the one who listened to all our laments, to all our
problems.''
   The defense tried to show that North's dealings with Calero were
well known in Washington. The Contra leader said: ``Whenever I talk
to agency (CIA) people, if I went beyond what they were permitted to
hear or talk to me about, they would say `see Ollie about that.'''
   Calero spoke highly of North, saying at one point, ``For us he
became sort of a savior.'' At another point, he declared, ``They are
going to erect a monument to him once we free Nicaragua.''
   North lawyer Brendan Sullivan, who has been trying to persuade
the jury that North was merely following orders from President
Reagan and other top administration officials, distributed to jurors
loose-leaf binders of pictures taken of Calero and other Contra
leaders with Reagan at the White House.
   ``The president of the United States had been very outspoken; he
had clearly stated a number of times that we had the support of the
country,'' the Contra leader said. Those sentiments, he pointed out,
were expressed after official U.S. aid was suspended.
   Calero, who was president of the Nicaraguan Democratic Force _
FDN _ was the second prosecution witness at North's trial. As he
waited to take the witness stand, Calero did not look at the
defendant, who was staring at him intently.
   The leadoff witness, Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., testified he had
not known at the time about Reagan administration solicitations of
help for the Contras from other countries in return for increased
U.S. military and economic aid.
   Hamilton said he didn't know then that Secretary of State George
P. Shultz asked an Asian country to provide communications equipment
to the Contras because the rebels' devices were antiquated.
   He also said he wasn't told that Shultz and then-National
Security Adviser John M. Poindexter knew of a plan by a Central
American nation to provide aircraft to help train Contra fighter
pilots.
   And he didn't recall being told that Poindexter's predecessor as
national security adviser, Robert McFarlane, authorized North to
contact ``a senior military official of an Asian country'' to
arrange ``the sale of missiles to the resistance.''
   He said, too, that he was not told that Gen. John W. Vessey Jr.,
then chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, also met with the Asian
official to arrange the sale.
   None of the countries involved was identified.
   Hamilton, answering questions from Sullivan, said he was not told
of these and other efforts on behalf of the Contras in the 1984-1986
period when direct U.S. military assistance was forbidden by law.
   The defense is trying to show the Reagan administration didn't
tell lawmakers about its efforts to help the rebels by soliciting
foreign donations after the ban on aid. North, who was a Marine
lieutenant colonel attached to the National Security Council, is
charged with lying to Congress about his role.
   ``Sometime in 1985, there was a crisis in Lebanon where American
hostages were taken,'' he said. ``Colonel North talked about that.
He mentioned the need to help reduce the Americans held hostage. I
said I would gladly contribute money I had control of to free those
hostages. ... I gave him money for that purpose.''
   Calero also testified he bought $11 million worth of weapons from
retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord, whom he met through
North, between January 1984 and early 1985.
</TEXT>
