<FIRST>u i AM-Austria-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0715 02-23 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Austria-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austrian Cabinet Minister, 10 Others Killed in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with all aboard confirmed killed,
new quotes. CORRECTS that submarine was West German, not Austrian. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane crashed into Lake
Constance near the Swiss-Austrian border on Thursday, and all 11
people aboard were killed, including Austrian Social Affairs
Minister Alfred Dallinger, officials said.
   Dozens of helicopters, boats and a West German submarine took
part in international search efforts. Around 6 p.m., seven hours
after the crash, the wreck of the Gulfstream Aerocommander AC-90
aircraft was found about 260 feet below surface, about half a mile
from the shore.
   Waldemar Marquart, a Swiss investigating judge, said in an
interview on Austrian TV that the submarine crew made a video film
of the sunken plane to help salvage teams in their efforts to raise
the aircraft on Friday.
   ``On the basis of the (video) pictures it is quite clear that
none of the people on board is still alive,'' Marquart said.
   Ernst Sperl, a spokesman for the civil aviation authority, told
The Associated Press earlier no hope of survivors existed.
   It was not known why the plane crashed as it was preparing to
land at Altenrhein, just over the border in Switzerland.
   In Vienna, a previously unknown group calling itself the Austrian
People's Army claimed responsibility for the crash in a telephone
call to the West German news agency DPA. The Austria Press Agency
said police were investigating.
   Dallinger, 62, who took over the social affairs portfolio in 1980
and was the longest serving Austrian minister, was among the nine
passengers.
   The two crew members were identified by Renate Moser, a
spokeswoman of the private Austrian airline Rhinethalflug, as pilot
Brigitte Seewald, the wife of the airline's owner, and her co-pilot,
Hans Reiner.
   Lake Constance, also known as Bodensee, lies in Austria,
Switzerland and West Germany.
   The plane was originally scheduled to land at Hohenems in
Vorarlberg, Austria's westernmost province, but was prevented from
doing so by thick fog, Austrian radio reported. The plane had taken
off from Vienna.
   The radio quoted an unidentified control tower official at
Altenrhein as saying the plane had passed over the airport in
preparation for landing and then looped back out over the lake to
fly in on the designated runway.
   He said the crew gave no indication of any problems on board, the
radio said.
   A second Aerocommander belonging to Rheinthalflug reportedly had
to make an emergency landing at Vienna's Schwechat airport in
January 1988, after both engines failed, the Austria Press Agency
reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
