<DOCNO> AP890223-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     02-23 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Seeks Power to Fire Plant Managers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Mieczyslaw Rakowski said Thursday
he will ask Parliament for the power to fire plant managers who pay
workers too much.
   Lech Walesa, founder of Solidarity, said he will urge a boycott
of forthcoming parliamentary elections unless the outlawed
independent union is returned to legal status by then.
   Supporters of a free-speech group did a brisk business in
underground newspapers outside the official PAP news agency before
police arrived and briefly detained three of them.
   Rakowski told foreign journalists attending a
government-sponsored seminar he needs more authority over state
enterprises to make sure economic reforms proceed and managers do
not give excessive pay raises.
   ``Today for example, as prime minister, I am unable to fire a
manager,'' he said. ``I think the chief of a concern has such a
right, and I don't.''
   He said some members of the opposition are against the government
having the power to fire a manager who ``drastically abuses
principles of the wage and prices policy.''
   ``The opposition stated that it was a return to the hard hand and
even Stalinism,'' Rakowski said.
   ``Soon I'll be hearing Stalin was my father,'' he declared. But
he said he will seek the power from Parliament ``because I am
against the weakening of the authorities in Poland. ... I
experienced it a few years ago, when our legs were hobbled like a
horse's and then there was a whip trying to hurry us up.''
   Keeping wages from rising faster than prices is one of the
government's major goals, both to fight inflation and to maintain
adequate supplies.
   Former Premier Zbigniew Messner's government gave in last year to
pressure for wage increases when inflation reached more than 60
percent. Economists blame the raises for a buying sprees that made
shortages worse.
   Walesa told a news conference in Gdansk, where he works as a
shipyard electrician: ``If elections are held before we become a
union, if there is no decision about the relegalization of
Solidarity, everything becomes invalid. There will be a boycott and
Lech Walesa will not vote.''
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban was asked for comment during a
student rally at Gdansk Polytechnic and replied: ``All will be
settled before the elections.''
   Reform of the electoral system is a central topic in talks on
political and economic reform between authorities and the
opposition, which have entered their third week.
   Officials say the government wants its opponents to be in
Parliament so they will share responsibility for unpopular decisions
and so conflicts can be dealt with politically rather than through
protests or strikes.
   Solidarity was born in the labor turmoil of 1980, the first free
union in the Soviet bloc, then suppressed and outlawed after the
declaration of martial law in December 1981. Since the talks began,
the government has indicated a willingness to make the union legal
again.
   About two dozen people who said they were from the newly formed
Movement for Free Speech assembled outside the PAP offices across
the street from Communist Party headquarters and a library featuring
books and periodicals from communist countries.
   They held up banners saying ``Free Access to Radio and
Television,'' ``We Demand Lifting of Censorship,'' ``Stop
Repressions Against Independent Publishing Houses'' and ``We Demand
a Change of the Press Law.''
   About a dozen sold banned underground weeklies, including
Tygodnik Mazowsze, the Solidarity weekly of the Warsaw region, were
sold to passers-by.
   Police watched for half an hour, then confiscated the banners and
detained three young men for about 10 minutes.
</TEXT>
