<FIRST>u i AM-Mideast-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0681 02-23 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mideast-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0681,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Says Israel Must Talk to PLO Before Soviet Ties Restored</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 4 grafs after 16th graf pvs, ``Actually, it...' UPDATING
with Kollek comment, TV ban. Picks up 17th pvs, `Shevardnadze complained...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
said Thursday that Israel must agree to talk with the PLO and accept
an international peace conference as the price of renewing
diplomatic relations.
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat said the Soviets are providing him an
indirect channel to the Israelis through increased contacts set up
this week in Cairo.
   Shevardnadze met separately with Arafat and Israeli Foreign
Minister Moshe Arens in Cairo on Wednesday. He flew to Baghdad on
Thursday.
   On arrival in the Iraqi capital, he told reporters: ``The
prospects of a solution to the Middle East look good and more
realistic ... because of the PLO's peace overtures.''
   Shevardnadze planned to visit Iran after Iraq and then head home,
and Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency reported that Shevardnadze
will be granted a rare audience with Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
during the visit. The report was monitored in Cyprus.
   In a speech to politicians in Cairo, Shevardnadze said: ``We
would like the government of Israel to know that once it opts for
the conference and agrees to a dialogue with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, our two countries could take yet another
step toward re-establishing full diplomatic relations.
   ``The beginning of the conference would be a starting point for
resumed relations,'' he said. Relations were severed after the 1967
Middle East war.
   Israel opposes a U.N.-organized conference but has said it would
go to one under the auspices of the United States and the Soviet
Union. Israel, however, has said it will not talk with the PLO,
which it considers a terrorist organization.
   Under the plan proposed by Moscow, the Soviet Union, the United
States and the other three permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council would attend such a conference, along with Israel, the PLO
and other regional parties.
   ``Israel should not be afraid of the conference,'' Shevardnadze
said. ``Our view is that (it) would indeed give a chance for a
historic compromise between the Arabs and the Israelis.''
   During their meeting, Arens rejected the idea. However, he said
afterward the Soviets have a role to play in Middle East peacemaking
even without diplomatic ties with Israel.
   In Jerusalem, Israel's Hadashot newspaper said Arens and
Shevardnadze agreed to advance ties by making the consular offices
in each country permanent.
   In Cairo, Arafat told a news conference that his organization is
pleased with the Soviet stand on relations with Israel.
   Arafat also appeared pleased at the new Soviet-Israeli dialogue,
which is to begin within days with meetings of Middle East experts
from the two countries. Shevardnadze and Arens are to meet again,
although no date or place have been announced.
   Asked about the results of Shevardnadze's meetings, the PLO
leader noted:
   ``Actually, it was indirect negotiations. ... He informed me
about what was mentioned by the Israeli delegation, and no doubt he
will inform the Israelis what I have mentioned.''
   Mayor Teddy Kollek of Jerusalem indicated at a news conference
there on Thursday that he would support formation of an independent
Palestinian state in the occupied West Bank, but would never agree
to any part of Jerusalem serving as its capital, as the Arabs demand.
   ``Not everything the Arabs want they can get,'' Kollek said.
   The head of Israel's state-run television banned broadcast of an
interview with Arafat conducted by the station's reporter for Arab
affairs, the Israel Broadcast Authority said in Jerusalem on
Thursday.
   Uri Porath, the authority's director general, said in a statement
Israeli law bars contacts between Israeli citizens and ``terrorist
organizations.''
   Shevardnadze complained to reporters after the speech about
President Bush's comments relegating the Kremlin to a ``limited
role'' in the Middle East.
   ``The U.S. president said he was not concerned about the Soviet
minister's tour of the region. That is basically quite right,''
Shevardnadze said.
   ``But in the end he made a qualification that I didn't like. He
said the role of the Soviet Union should be limited. That is very
sad because it injects an element of rivalry that is unnecessary.''
   He added with a smile: ``This is my first critical remark about
the president of the United States.''
</TEXT>
