<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-23 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Air And Snow Drive Into South, Noreaster Develops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures fell to record lows across the Plains and central
Mississippi Valley early Thursday, and the cold air pushed snow
flurries to the Gulf of Mexico coast.
   Snow was reported across parts of Alabama and northern Florida,
including Apalachicola and Jacksonville. Albany and Elberton, Ga.,
reported 4 inches of snow by afternoon.
   The snow also spread across western and central parts of the
Carolinas while rain was reported along the eastern Carolinas. Up to
3 inches of snow was reported across parts of the north midland of
North Carolina and Nantahala in Macon County reported 5 inches of
new snow.
   Record lows reported by the weather service were 11 at
Batesville, Ark.; 4 below zero at Grand Rapids, Mich.; 7 at
Harrison, Ark.; 13 at Hot Springs, Ark.; 13 at Jonesboro, Ark.; 2 at
Kansas City, Mo.; 16 below at Lincoln, Neb.; 14 at Little Rock,
Ark.; 17 at Memphis, Tenn.; 13 at Mena, Ark.; 3 below at Muskegon,
Mich.; 13 below at Norfolk, Neb.; 7 below at Ottumwa, Iowa; 13 at
Ozark, Ark.; 17 at Pine Bluff, Ark.; and 10 below at Traverse City,
Mich.
   The cold air over the Southeast helped generate a low pressure
zone over the North Carolina coast that was expected to develop into
the type of snowstorm called a ``nor'easter.'' Depending on how
closely it follows the coast, it was expected to produce northeast
winds along the Atlantic Coast and snow over the mid Atlantic region
and New England.
   Winter storm watches were posted from much of eastern Virginia
through Maryland and Delaware into New York City and the southern
New England coast into Friday, with 4 inches of snow expected.
   Lake effect snow fed by the moisture of the Great Lakes fell
along the shores of Lake Ontario. Rochester, N.Y., received an inch
of snow during the morning and Niagara Falls, N.Y., reported 2
inches. Lake effect snow also fell around Chicago and northwestern
Indiana.
   Showers were scattered along the northern Pacific Coast.
Quillayute, Wash., received 0.63 of an inch of rain in 24 hours.
   Gusty wind developed across higher elevations of Wyoming and over
eastern South Dakota. Gusts measured at 60 to 75 mph near Cheyenne,
Wyo., and blowing snow forced closure of Interstate 80.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 10
degrees at Grand Forks, N.D., Brookings, S.D., and Bloomington,
Ill., to 89 at Santee, Calif., outside San Diego. Thursday's low for
the Lower 48 states was 24 below zero at Hibbing, Minn.
   For Friday, snow was forecast across the middle and northern
Atlantic Coast region. Scattered snowshowers were forecast from the
central Appalachians into the eastern Great Lakes. Showers were
forecast along the northern Pacific Coast. Scattered showers were
forecast from northern California into the northern Plateau,
possibly mixed with snow in Montana west of the Continental Divide.
   Highs only in the 20s were predicted from the upper Great Lakes
into the lower Ohio Valley and central Appalachians into the
northern half of the Atlantic Coast; only be in the 50s across
southern Florida; in the 50s and 60s from the central Pacific Coast
through the Great Basin into the central high Plains, the southern
Plains and the Texas Gulf Coast; in the 70s from southern California
to the Rio Grande Valley of Texas; in the low to mid 80s across the
desert Southwest; and in the 30s or 40s across much of the rest of
the nation.
</TEXT>
