<FIRST>u a AM-SouthernCold 2ndLd-Writethru a0721 02-23 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southern Cold, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0721,0856</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Shivers With Blast Of Snow And Cold</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf, `Snowflakes reached ..., to UPDATE
with S.C. closings, one death; INSERTS 1 graf after 13th pvs, ``The kids
..., to add sled sales; and INSERTS 3 grafs after 18th graf pvs, ``In Florida
..., with detail on crop threats.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The coldest air of the winter surged across the Deep South on
Thursday, icing highways and threatening the citrus harvest while
delighting youngsters with rare snow and closed schools.
   Snowflakes reached the beaches on the Gulf of Mexico, and
temperatures dropped below freezing in northern Florida.
Meteorologists said traditional methods of keeping fruit crops from
freezing might not help against the wind-driven cold that pushed
wind chill factors below zero across most of Alabama.
   Businesses closed early in South Carolina, where Gov. Carroll
Campbell also sent most state workers home in the middle of the
afternoon. One traffic death in Georgia was blamed on icy roads.
   Elsewhere, up to a foot of snow fell around the Chicago area and
northwestern Indiana.
   The core of the cold wave dropped temperatures to record lows
across the Midwest and as far south as Tennessee and Arkansas.
Records included 17 at Memphis, Tenn.; 2 at Kansas City, Mo.; 13
below zero at Norfolk, Neb.; 13 below zero at Spencer, Iowa, and 10
below zero at Traverse City, Mich.
   The combination of the cold and gusty wind produced wind chill
readings of 11 degrees below zero at Memphis Naval Air Station in
Tennessee, 14 below at Harrison, Ark., 22 below at Springfield, Mo.,
and zero at Jackson, Miss.
   Lows early Friday were predicted in the upper 20s in central
Florida and the high teens in the Florida Panhandle.
   ``This is the coldest it's going to be since (January) 1986,''
said National Weather Service forecaster Noel Risnychok in Coral
Gables, Fla.
   The cold snap comes on the heels of record highs just last week
that saw Birmingham, Ala., hit 78 twice.
   Flurries were reported in Alabama as far south as Mobile and
Baldwin counties on the Gulf coast. Snow accumulated in northern
Alabama, and sections of two interstate highways near Trussville and
Leeds were closed.
   Slippery roads closed schools in Georgia, South Carolina and
Tennessee.
   Snow fell across northern Florida from Panhandle beaches to
Jacksonville but melted as soon as it hit the ground. Four inches of
snow fell at Athens, Ga. Up to 3 inches of snow fell in parts of
Tennessee. Atlanta got its first snow of the year.
   In Valdosta, Ga., Nancy Robinson, a police desk clerk, said the
last snowfall police could recall in the area was six years ago.
   ``The kids were very excited because they're not used to this,''
she said.
   In Cobb County, Ga., one hardware store store sold all of its
three dozen sleds by the time the first snowflakes appeared. ``It's
amazing. It's just the anticipation of snow,'' said Ken Lindsey,
owner of Acworth True Value Hardware.
   While highways iced up, grocery stores in Georgia reported that
customers were stocking up, and some liquor stores also reported an
increase in sales.
   ``It has been a little busier today,'' said Carol Thompson, an
assistant at a store in Roswell, an Atlanta suburb. ``People are
afraid they are going to be snowed in without anything to drink.
That could be tragic, you know.''
   The men's division of the Atlanta Union Mission operated above
its 300-bed capacity Wednesday night. The Rev. Bernard Weaver said
more than 40 men slept on pads on the floor.
   Forecasters in Alabama predicted crop-saving efforts such as
using helicopters to blow warmer air down to the ground and setting
fires would be of little benefit because of the wind and the
duration of the freezing cold.
   In Florida, enough oranges to fill 65 million 90-pound boxes were
awaiting harvest and could face some damage, along with half the
projected grapefruit harvest of 54 million 85-pound boxes, said
Ernie Neff, spokesman for Citrus Mutual, a growers organization.
   Central Florida growers and farmers braced for the cold as frost
threatened as far south as the northern Everglades.
   ``We're all going to do a lot of praying,'' said Roy Parkes, a
Hillsborough County strawberry farmer. ``It looks like we're going
to be at the mercy of the wind and cold.''
   Georgia Agriculture Commissioner Tommy Irvin said the cold
threatened wheat, peach and Vidalia onion crops. ``I think we're in
for some hard times,'' said Rick Hartley, Toombs County extension
service director.
   Kentucky was still coming to grips with flooding caused by heavy
rain last week. The state had documented more than $18 million in
uninsured damage in 18 counties, and Gov. Wallace Wilkinson said the
damage total was certain to grow.
   In McLean County, the towns of Calhoun, Rumsey and Livermore were
inundated Wednesday when the Green River crested earlier than
expected, marooning some 275 dwellings. About a third of the county
was under water, officials said.
</TEXT>
