<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     02-23 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Indian Troops Will Stay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it will
not ask Indian troops to leave Sri Lanka until radical violence that
has killed thousands of people is finally crushed.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne said it would be ``foolish'' to
ask Indian forces to withdraw before a provincial administration and
police force were established in the violence-plagued north and east.
   ``We don't want to act foolishly just to satisfy the whims of
both Sinhalese and Tamil extremists,'' said Wijeratne, who also is
Sri Lanka's deputy defense minister.
   ``When law and order is established the president will ask the
Indian troops to leave,'' Wijeratne said.
   In July 1987, India and Sri Lanka signed an agreement aimed at
ending the Tamil insurgency that began in 1983 and has claimed at
least 8,500 lives.
   The mostly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 per cent of the island's 16
million people. They say they are discriminated against by the
nation's predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese majority, who comprise 75
percent of the population.
   Militant Tamils have waged a guerrilla war for an independent
nation in the north and east of Sri Lanka, where they are a majority.
   India prevailed on militant Tamils to accept limited autonomy in
exchange for giving up the struggle and sent in troops to monitor a
cease-fire. But the most hard-line guerrillas rejected the accord
and began battling the Indians.
   Sinhalese extremists, claiming the government had made too many
concessions to the Tamil minority, also began demanding the Indians
withdraw and started assassinating Sinhalese officials.
   Neighboring India became involved in the situation because of the
sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils.
   India says about 40,000 of its soldiers are posted in northern
and eastern Sri Lanka. Four battalions of Indian soldiers, about
7,000 men, withdrew from the island soon after Ranasinghe Premadasa
in the Dec. 19 presidential election.
   Elsewhere in the island, police and military officials said at
least six Sinhalese rice paddy farmers were shot and stabbed by
suspected Tamil militants.
   At least 10 others were injured in the attack late Wednesday in
the Sinhapura village, 160 miles northeast of Colombo. The militants
attacked the villagers and set six huts on fire, officials said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Two Indian soldiers were killed Wednesday in confrontation with
Tamil militants in northern Jaffna town, 186 miles north of Colombo,
said a spokeswoman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
