<DOCNO> AP890223-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FBIPersonnel     02-23 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI Personnel,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glover Honored by Marshals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John D. Glover, the FBI's highest-ranking black
official, was honored Thursday by the U.S. Marshals Service as the
FBI announced he will retire next month.
   John J. Twomey, deputy director of the service, gave Glover the
service's Frederick Douglass Award at the U.S. Courthouse in San
Francisco during a Marshals Black History Month ceremony to honor
``his outstanding career and leadership in federal law
enforcement,'' the service said.
   Glover, 50, executive assistant director of the FBI in charge of
administration, is a 22-year veteran who was the first black to
become a special agent in charge of an FBI office when he was
appointed to head the Atlanta office in 1981.
   His rank is just below that of FBI Director William Sessions.
There are two other executive assistant directors.
   The FBI announced Glover will retire March 31 to become a vice
president with the Bristol-Myers Co. in New York.
   Glover will be replaced by Floyd I. Clarke, a 25-year FBI veteran
who has been assistant director in charge of criminal investigations
since 1985, the agency announced. Clarke's successor was not
announced.
   Clarke, a George Washington University graduate, will be
responsible for the FBI budget, personnel administration, resource
allocation, long-range planning and FBI policy development, the FBI
said.
</TEXT>
