<FIRST>r w AM-D.C.-NationalGuard     02-23 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-D.C.-National Guard,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Guard to Aid D.C. Police in Battle Against Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Guard will soon join the war on
drugs in the nation's capital, Guard officials said Thursday, while
Mayor Marion Barry agreed to send additional police officers to city
neighborhoods where the drug problem is the worst.
   District of Columbia National Guard Maj. Gen. Calvin Franklin
said the Pentagon has given preliminary approval to a $300,000
project that will allow guardsmen to aid city officials in breaking
up more than 80 open-air drug markets that flourish in the district.
   ``We have put together a detailed comprehensive drug operation
and support plan in concert with the district police department that
will help fight the drug problem,'' said Franklin.
   ``It could involve the guard using helicopters and night vision
devices to assist in monitoring and detection of illegal drugs.''
   However, no guardsmen will patrol the streets despite the wishes
of some city council members and community activists to have them do
so.
   ``We would be concerned about having armed military personnel on
the street to get involved in arresting people,'' Franklin said.
``When you put a soldier out there in uniform, he would make an
ideal target for a drug operator wanting to send out a signal.''
   Under the plan, the Guard will train city police to use infared
night-viewing equipment, sophisticated radar systems, and other
devices the police do not have.
   The partnership began in November, after city police officials
asked the Guard to help fight the city's growing drug trade. Police
say 60 percent of last year's record 372 killings were drug-related.
Eighty-four people have been killed in the district so far this
year, compared to 52 at the same time last year.
   The plan must be approved by the Departments of Defense and
Justice before the Guard can start providing equipment or expertise,
but Guard officials say they expect approval and hope to start the
program in the next 60 days.
   Meanwhile, Barry agreed to demands from a group of ministers that
he assign 50 extra police officers to neighborhoods where the drug
problem is worst.
   ``I've been delighted that these ministers came here in
partnership with some real concerns,'' Barry said. ``We want these
killings, these shootings, stopped.''
   The ministers also gained a commitment from the city council that
it would draft a bill giving the mayor authority to declare a curfew
in specific areas to prevent teen-age drug dealers from plying their
trade on neighborhood street corners. Such legislation would allow
Barry to flood the areas with police officers.
   But the ministers did not receive a pledge from Barry to declare
a state of emergency in any of the city's neighborhoods.
   ``I'm perfectly willing to take a wait-and-see attitude,'' said
councilmember H.R. Crawford, who helped organize the meeting.
Crawford said he was satisfied with today's actions.
   ``I consider this real action _ a real step forward,'' Crawford
said.
   The city is also proceeding with plans to hire an additional 150
officers, police sources confirmed. However, police union officials
cautioned that these officers will only replace others who are
retiring, and will not increase the number of police officers on the
streets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
