<FIRST>r a AM-GunsArrest     02-23 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guns Arrest,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Wanted On Murder Charge Arrested After X-Rays Detects Weapons
In Baggage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new X-ray security system at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport spotted a weapons cache hours after it was
introduced and nabbed a murder suspect in the process.
   A Mexican national was ordered off a Delta Air Lines jet Tuesday
after airline employees discovered 24 guns and 215 rounds of
ammunition in his luggage bound for Acapulco, U.S. Customs officials
said.
   ``We had just begun using the X-ray equipment that same day,''
said Delta spokesman Jackie Pate. ``This guy apparently picked the
wrong day to fly.''
   Customs agents said Anai Portillo-Castro, 28, would be charged
with violating federal export laws, which ban the shipment of
firearms to any foreign country without federal licensing.
   At the time of his arrest, Portillo-Castro was carrying 3.8 grams
of cocaine and $2,554 in cash, agents said. Officials said he was
held in lieu of a $45,000 bond and that drug possession charges also
would be filed.
   He told Customs investigators that the guns and ammunition were
being shipped to a Mexican Federal Judicial Police commandante
there, Customs officials said.
   Portillo-Castro, who lives near Acapulco, was wanted for
investigation of murder in the Dec. 21, 1984, shooting of Juan
Flores Jaimez. A Dallas County grand jury indicted him on a murder
charge in January 1985.
