<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Spies     02-23 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Spies,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says KGB Man Betrayed By Love For Pasta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A KGB agent's love for pasta helped tip off
investigators who smashed a spy ring seeking military information
from Italy, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   Corriere della Sera said Valery Popov, based in Yugoslavia and
unhappy without good pasta, asked a Yugoslav electronics engineer
working in Italy to get large amounts of the Italian staple along
with microfilm of military secrets.
   Authorities last week announced they arrested the Yugoslav,
42-year-old Giorgio Stancich, who worked in Trieste, a city on the
border with Yugoslavia. News reports said magistrates have also
issued warrants for Popov and another Soviet, both apparently at
large.
   The Milan newspaper said Italian counterespionage agents who had
Stancich under surveillance had their suspicions raised by the
engineer's frequent stops in Trieste grocery stores.
   Tapping his telephone, they heard him talking to a Russian who
lamented he couldn't find the proper ingredients in Yugoslavia to
make the Roman speciality ``bucatini all'amatriciana,'' a dish of
thick spaghetti with pork, the paper said.
   Corriere della Sera, which did not cite its sources, said the
Russian developed his taste for the dish during a previous stint in
Rome, first as a Tass correspondent then as a trade office
spokesman. The Soviet Embassy in Rome has said it never heard of the
people allegedly charged in the case.
