<FIRST>r a AM-LibraryPresident     02-23 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Library President,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgetown President to Head New York Public Library</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Timothy Healy, president of Georgetown
University, was named president of the New York Public Library on
Thursday.
   Healy, a native New Yorker who has served as an administrator at
Fordham University and the City University of New York, will replace
Vartan Gregorian, who is leaving the post to become president of
Brown University.
   Healy, 65, will take the post sometime this summer, said library
spokeswoman Lauren Moye. The library's board of trustees elected
Healy during a special meeting Thursday morning, she said.
   Gregorian became president of the library in 1981 after serving
as provost of the University of Pennsylvania. He was credited with
improving the library's finances through a number of innovative
fund-raising techniques, including parties that attracted members of
high society.
   Healy became president of Georgetown in 1976 and oversaw vast
changes at the Washington, D.C., school. In his 13 years, its
endowment rose from $38 million to $225 million.
   Each year, 1.3 million people visit the New York Public Library's
four research and 81 branch libraries. It has an annual operating
budget of $128 million and a staff of 2,274.
   Healy, who started his teaching career at Fordham Prep School,
was director of alumni relations at Fordham University from 1955-62;
executive vice president of Fordham University from 1965-69; and
vice chancellor for academic affairs at CUNY from 1969-76.
   In 1974, he took a leave from CUNY to become special assistant to
the chancellor of the State University of New York for planning the
State Prison College.
   Healy attended Regis High School in Manhattan, then received a
bachelor's degree in English and master's degree in philosophy from
Woodstock College in Maryland. He was ordained as a Jesuit priest at
the Facultes Saint Albert in Louvain, Belgium, in 1953.
   He earned a master's degree in English literature from Fordham,
and in 1965, his doctorate from Oxford University.
</TEXT>
