<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDSNotice     02-23 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Notice,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Exposed To AIDS To Receive Antiviral Drug, Officials Announce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Institutes of Health workers who are
accidently exposed to the AIDS virus will immediately be started on
doses of zidovudine, the only drug now approved for treatment of the
viral disease.
   In a notice posted late Thursday to NIH employees, an AIDS
advisory group announced that NIH director James B. Wyngaarden had
approved the emergency use of zidovudine, also known as AZT, for
research and clinical workers exposed to the AIDS virus in
laboratory or hospital settings.
   The AIDS virus, known as human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, is
being studied at a number of laboratories at the NIH, and there also
are patients treated at the NIH clinics. Elaborate laboratory
procedures are in effect to contain and control the virus, but there
have been a number of health care workers exposed through needle
sticks or other accidents. At least one medical worker in the U.S.
has developed AIDS after such an accident.
   ``Although definitive evidence for the efficacy of AZT
prophylaxis (preventative) in HIV exposures has yet to be
established, the advisory group concluded that the available data
suggest possible value in this setting,'' the announcement said.
   AZT, the announcement said, will be provided ``where it is judged
that the individual may have sustained a significant exposure.''
   HIV can be transmitted through an exchange of body fluids. The
disease usually is spread through sexual contact, the sharing of
needles among drug addicts, from birthing mother to child, or from
the medical transfusion of blood or blood products.
   But experts say that health care workers can also be at risk if
spilled blood, body fluids or laboratory specimens are absorbed
through small cuts or abrasions, or from the accidental stick of a
syringe needle, a fairly common accident in hospitals.
   The announcement said that the NIH advisory group on AIDS
recommended that medical workers experiencing an exposure accident
should start AZT medication ``as soon as possible, preferably within
hours following the exposure.''
   AZT, once called azidothymidine, is marketed by the Burroughs
Wellcome Co. under the brand name Retrovir. It was approved for the
treatement of AIDS in 1987 after studies showed that the drug could
suppress the HIV infection in many patients. Though the drug can
control progress of AIDS in many cases, it is not considered a cure
for the disease.
   Recent studies have also suggested that the drug is able to
prevent persons exposed to the HIV virus becoming infected if the
drug is started shortly after exposure. These studies have not been
completed.
   The AIDS virus attacks and eventually kills vital
disease-fighting cells in the blood. This leaves the body
defenseless to attack by other diseases and cancers. Most AIDS
victims die from opportunistic infections, such as rare types of
pneumonia, that their body is not able to fight.
   As of Feb. 13, 1989, AIDS had been diagnosed in 86,157 Americans,
of whom more than half, or 43,390, have died since June 1, 1981,
according to the Centers for Disease Control. No one is known to
have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
