<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     02-23 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Arrives In Province On Fourth Day Of Strike By Albanians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TITOVA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raif Dizdarevic
arrived Thursday in troubled Kosovo province, where thousands of
ethnic Albanian workers struck for the fourth straight day despite
government warnings.
   The official Tanjug news agency said Dizdarevic was accompanied
by Petar Gracanin, president of the Yugoslavia's Serbian republic,
which administers the province. It was an apparent attempt to head
off possible clashes between the Albanian majority and the Serbian
minority.
   Tanjug said ``hostile pamphlets written by Albanian nationalists
and separatists'' calling for ``an uprising and bloodshed by ethnic
Albanians'' have appeared in the provincial capital of Pristina and
other Kosovo towns.
   The pamphlets allegedly denounced the provincial and national
communist leadership.
   About 1,200 workers at the Trepca lead and zinc mines continued
occupying their pits and protesting alleged discrimination by
authorities in Serbia.
   About 2,000 ethnic Albanian students from the province's capital,
Pristina, protested through the night in a sports hall to show
solidarity with the miners. About 10,000 other people were involved
in protest strikes throughout the economically depressed province.
   ``We are determined to stay in the pits until we die if our
demands are not met,'' Azim Suljemani, a digger, told The Associated
Press in an interview conducted about a half mile underground.
   The miners are on all 12 levels of the mine, which was founded in
1925 by a British company. They were sitting on wooden crates in
ankle-deep mud.
   They read reporters a written statement addressed to the United
Nations Committee For Human Rights denouncing ``discrimination of
ethnic Albanians by the Serbian government.''
   Serbian leaders say the republic should have more judicial and
police control in Kosovo to protect the Serbian minority. Serbs say
they are persecuted by the ethnic Albanians, who make up about 85
percent of the province's 2 million population.
   The nine-man national presidency, meeting in an emergency session
urged the workers to immediately end their strikes and said it would
take all constitutional and legal measures to prevent the crisis
from growing.
   Among other demands, the strikers were calling for the
resignation of the province's Communist Party chief, Rahman Morina.
   At least 17 Trepca miners were hospitalized for exhaustion after
spending three days in the pits, Kosovo's information bureau said.
   Eleven ethnic Albanians were sentenced in Pristina on Thursday to
jail terms of between four months and eight years, Tanjug said.
   The were sentenced for ``illegal, hostile'' activities allegedly
carried out as members of a group which calls itself ``The
Marxists-Leninists of Kosovo,'' Tanjug said.
</TEXT>
