<FIRST>u i AM-Bush-Tower 2ndLd-Writethru a0799 02-23 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Tower, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0799,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Stands Behind Tower, Spokesman Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with committee vote against Tower.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will stick with embattled Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower even though a Senate committee voted
to reject his nomination, a White House spokesman said Friday.
   In advance of the Senate Armed Services Committee's 11 to 9 vote
against favorably recommending Tower's nomination to the full
Senate, press secretary Marlin Fitzwater also told reporters that
Bush has not had any discussions of dropping Tower and finding
another candidate for the Pentagon job.
   Fitzwater said that Bush had a telephone conversation Friday
morning with Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, and that
White House chief of staff John Sununu had made calls to the Hill
during the night. Tokyo is 14 hours ahead of Washington time.
   ``We have not heard anyone say he would not make a good secretary
of defense,'' Fitzwater said. ``We have not heard anyone say he is
not qualified for the job ... We hear vague talk about concern about
his personal habits and we think this debate ought to be on a
slightly higher level than that.''
   Fitzwater briefed reporters just after Bush's motorcade left for
the funeral of Emperor Hirohito, at Shinjuku Park, just a short ride
from the hotel.
   The press secretary reiterated the White House view that the
much-awaited FBI report, which was submitted last Monday,
``refutes'' allegations of excessive drinking by Tower.
   Asked pointblank whether Bush and Sununu had discussed finding
another candidate for the top Pentagon job, Fitzwater said there had
been no such talk whatsover.
   ``I can flatly say that. I do flatly say that,'' he said. ``I've
talked to the president about that several times, including just 10
minutes ago. There's no consideration of alternative candidates.
There's no alternate list _ bar none.''
   Fitzwater, however, said there had been no discussions with Sen.
Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee.
   ``We think he's been fair,'' the spokesman said. ``He's tried to
have open consideration here. He's been critical but the committee
has every right to look into these matters.''
   `` ... And we simply say that if the (committee) vote is not as
positive ... as we would like, the next step is to consider it on
the floor, and that's what we will do,'' the press secretary said.
   Asked whether Tower should offer to withdraw his name from
further consideration, he said that was not an option ``because we
think he's a good candidate and we presume the secretary wants the
best secretary of defense they can get.''
   ``We now go to the (Senate) floor,'' Fitzwater said. ``There's a
lot of time left in this process. ... the FBI report, we feel, deals
in great detail with the drinking problem and should put the matter
to rest.''
   Fitzwater said that ``you may be assured'' that the president
``has been kept abreast of this of this all the way.''
   In the ensuing days, the spokesman said, Bush will be making
``any number of contacts'' on the Tower matter, but said ``we don't
have a specific schedule of meetings or anything like that.''
   Asked if Tower had been too damaged by the confirmation process
to succeed in the Cabinet, the spokesman said, ``No, we don't
believe so. ... Believe he will come out of this a strengthened
secretary of defense.''
   Fitzwater also said that Bush does not see the Tower confirmation
battle as a sign of any refusal by congressional Democrats to seek
bipartisanship consensus on the various issues.
   ``The president believes ... the candidate deserves to have a
hearing before the full Senate,'' he said. ``Let's hear what it is
that they're basing their judgment on.''
   ``We've been lobbying through the day the nomination went up. We
believe he will be confirmed and we will certainly work toward that
end,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``We don't believe this speaks to any larger question of
bipartisanship,'' he added, saying that ``I would think the members
of the Senate and House would tell you the same thing. ... This is
quite a separate matter that has to be considered in that context.''
   Fitzwater said the White House had ``been in the game since the
day the nomination went up'' and said administration officials see
the Tower situation as ``an important nomination that we will
pursue.''
</TEXT>
