<FIRST>u w AM-CabinetRejection-History 1stLd-Writethru a0662 02-23
0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cabinet Rejection-History, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS pvs 6th graf with 2 grafs to update with Tower vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Committee Last Rejected Cabinet Nominee 44 Years Ago, Senate 30 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It has been 30 years since the Senate rejected
a president's choice for his Cabinet and 44 years since such action
was taken by a Senate committee.
   All in all, eight Cabinet nominations have been turned down by
the full Senate, according to the Senate Library.
   The most recent was President Eisenhower's nomination of Lewis B.
Strauss to be secretary of commerce, which was rejected by a 49-46
vote on Jan. 19, 1959. Strauss had been serving in the post by an
interim appointment since the previous November.
   The Senate Commerce Committee, controlled by Democrats, had
recommended Strauss' confirmation by a vote of 9-8, with three
Democrats joining six Republicans in support of him.
   Strauss had previously been chairman of the Atomic Energy
Commission. Opponents said that in that position he withheld
information from Congress or gave misleading information.
   Before the Senate Armed Services Committee voted Thursday to
reject the nominiation of John Tower as secretary of defense, the
last time a Senate committee rejected a Cabinet nominee was on Jan.
26, 1945.
   The Commerce Committee then turned down President Roosevelt's
nomination of Henry A. Wallace to be secretary of commerce by a vote
of 14-5. Wallace, who had been secretary of agriculture and then
vice president, was nevertheless confirmed by the full Senate by a
vote of 56-32 on March 1.
   The first president to have a Cabinet choice rejected by the
Senate was Andrew Jackson, whose nomination of Roger B. Taney to be
secretary of the treasury was turned down on June 23, 1834. Taney,
who was already serving in the post by a recess appointment, was
later named chief justice by Jackson and confirmed for that post by
the Senate.
   President John Tyler had the worst luck of any president when it
came to his Cabinet nominations. He had four of them turned down,
one of them three times.
   The Senate rejected Tyler's nomination of Caleb Cushing to be
secretary of the treasury by three separate votes on March 3, 1843.
It also rejected his choice of James S. Green for the treasury post
on June 15, 1844, James Madison Porter for secretary of war on June
30, 1844, and David Henshaw for secretary of the Navy on Jan. 15,
1844.
   Also rejected by the Senate was President Andrew Johnson's
selection of Henry Stanberry to be attorney general in 1868.
   President Calvin Coolidge's nomination of Charles B. Warren as
attorney general was rejected twice, on March 10 and again on March
16, 1925.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Politics     02-23 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Politics,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Socialist Party Elects New Leadership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Socialist Party, Japan's No. 3
opposition party, elected a new chairman Thursday to replace a man
who stepped down because of a stock-profiteering scandal that has
shaken the government.
   Eiichi Nagasue, 71, was elected chairman as a regular party
convention. He succeeds Saburo Tsukamoto, 61, who announced Feb. 8
he would not seek re-election as chairman.
   ``If my resignation can bring gains for the party, I decided it
is better for me to withdraw now,'' he said then.
   A party official quoted Nagasue as telling the convention he
wants to form a coalition with the nation's largest labor union,
Rengo, and bring down the Liberal Democratic Party government of
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   The union confederation claims 5.5 million members.
   On the stock scandal, Nagasue said, ``In order not to bring to
naught former chairman Tsukamoto's courageous decision (to step
down), we will try our best to find out the truth of the Recruit
affair and bring it before the people,'' the official reported on
condition of anonymity.
   He said about 1,500 party members attended the two-day annual
convention in downtown Tokyo.
   Tsukamoto's secretary bought 10,000 unlisted shares in
Recruit-Cosmos Co., a real estate subsidiary of the information
conglomerate Recruit Co., and made about $77,000 by selling them
after public trading in the shares began in 1986 and prices soared.
   Tsukamoto has denied any direct involvement in the scandal.
   Most of the politicians linked to the case were from Takeshita's
party, and three Cabinet ministers have resigned in connection with
the affair.
</TEXT>
