<FIRST>u i AM-Balian-Profile     02-23 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balian-Profile,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Captain Was Vietnam War Hero</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cannibal Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy Capt. Alexander G. Balian, convicted
Friday of abandoning Vietnamese refugees at sea who later turned to
cannibalism to survive, is a decorated hero of the war that created
the ``boat people.''
   The career naval officer in 1966 won the Silver Star, the United
States' third highest military award for valor, for saving members
of his crew after their river patrol boat was caught in a Viet Cong
night ambush.
   His tours of duty since then have included command of the
ammunition supply ships USS Kilauea and USS Kiska, and the
amphibious assault ship USS Peleliu.
   He took command of the USS Dubuque, a 16,500-ton amphibious
transport dock ship based at Sasebo, Japan, in May 1987. The Dubuque
carried 400 Marines as a ready reaction force and also served as
mother ship for U.S. minesweepers in the Persian Gulf.
   Balian was convicted of failing to render adequate assistance to
more than 80 Vietnamese refugees when the Dubuque, en route to the
gulf, encountered the boat people in the South China Sea last June 9.
   He was acquitted of two other charges. The court-martial panel
has yet to hand down a sentence, but he could be jailed for three
months and fined two-thirds of his pay for three months.
   United Nations and Navy officials say 31 of the Vietnamese died
from the time they encountered the Dubuque to when they were rescued
by Filipino fishermen on June 27. Survivors said they ate five of
the dead, including two who were killed.
   Balian was court-martialed at Subic Bay Naval Base in the
Philippines. Balian, 48, is a somewhat gregarious man, a cigar
smoker who once described himself as a trouble-shooter specializing
in putting ships back in shape. He is married and has two daughters.
   He was born in Southgate, Calif., a Los Angeles suburb where his
family is in the grocery business.
   At the time of his 1966 heroism, he was a young lieutenant
commanding a group of Navy ``swift'' boats operating on rivers and
canals southeast of Saigon, now called Ho Chi Minh City.
   His helmsman was killed and the other three men on board,
including Balian, were wounded when Viet Cong gunners attacked the
boat from shore with rocket-propelled grenades and automatic weapons.
   As the fragile boat sank, the survivors put the helmsman's body
on a makeshift raft and floated downstream to safety, past enemy
positions.
   As Balian recounted the episode recently, they slipped past the
Viet Cong outposts only to encounter poisonous jellyfish, the type
known as Portuguese man-of-war. The men suffered painful stings over
their entire bodies.
   Balian, awarded the Silver Star and the Purple Heart in that
episode, later did a second tour in Vietnam aboard a destroyer in
1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
