<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Editorials     02-23 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Editorials,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Newspapers Reflect On Hirohito's Reign On Funeral Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hirohito Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following are excerpts from newspaper editorials
Friday, the day of Emperor Hirohito's funeral.
   The liberal daily Asahi Shimbun wrote:
   ``At the time Hirohito ascended the throne six decades ago, Japan
was regarded with suspicion by the world as an emerging military
power. ... We must never forget the tragic sacrifices that many
people were forced to make, in Japan as well as abroad, along
Japan's path of change.
   ``We must not turn our eyes away from this somber history. It is
most important to renew our awareness of the responsibilities Japan
has to the world today.
   ``For today's state funeral ceremonies, the government never
really drew a clear line between the secular and the religious.
Moreover, the Japanese public at large tends to bow to orders from
above as a matter of course; a perfect case in point is the
Education Ministry's order to all public schools that they should
teach their children the importance of mourning for the late emperor.
   Another nationally circulated Japanese daily, Mainichi Shimbun,
said:
   ``Although the government has asked people to conduct a
nationwide meditation at noon, the decision of whether to express
mourning should be left up to each individual.
   ``Unlike the days of previous deified emperors ... this funeral
is the first one under the new constitution. It should be a concise
ceremony suitable for the symbolic emperor.
   ``Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's remarks that whether World
War II was a result of Japanese aggression was a matter that future
historians should determine have received severe criticism from
countries ... damaged by the Japanese.
   ``Such overseas reactions may puzzle those of the younger
generation without knowledge of war. ... But we cannot erase the
fact that Japan caused great damage among other Asian nations, which
has not healed even today.''
</TEXT>
