<FIRST>r a AM-XGR-Duke     02-23 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-XGR-Duke,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Rep. Duke Gets His Committee Assignments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly elected Rep. David Duke got the
House committee appointments he wanted Thursday, including one that
oversees welfare legislation, and the former Ku Klux Klan leader
said he was pleased.
   Duke, who was seated Wednesday in the House amid controversy over
his residency in the New Orleans suburb of Metairie, also received a
seat on House Judiciary Committee in addition to a spot on the
Health and Welfare Committee.
   ``I'm very happy with them,'' Duke said. ``That's what I wanted
... I want health and welfare because obviously welfare reform is
one of the most important parts of my program. Judiciary, I'm
concerned about our courts and law enforcement.''
   Rep. Alphonse Jackson the chairman of the health and welfare
panel and a member of the black legislative caucus, said, ``Glad to
have him. We can keep an eye on him.''
   Duke said he planned to pursue legislation encouraging welfare
recepients to obtain job training and employment and to cut down on
the illegitimate birth rate _ two planks of his campaign platform.
   The new lawmaker said he favored a system of incentives for
``those who show responsibility'' such as preferential housing
areas, job training and education programs.
   Although Duke said the panel probably would not meet until the
regular legislative session, he said he planned to present
amendments to Gov. Buddy Roemer's tax revision proposal once it
reached the House floor.
   Earlier Thursday, Roemer said he had no plans to meet with Duke,
but added that the door to his office was open to Duke _ under
specific circumstances.
   ``If he wants to come see me in terms of his district or our
state, I'm willing,'' he said. ``But if it's in terms of his
political philosophy, not now, not ever.''
   Duke, whose platform also called for no tax increases and
opposition to affirmative action programs, said he intended to
represent his district, which is 99.6 percent white.
   ``He is the governor of our state and I have respect for him in
that position and I'm sorry that the man doesn't understand what my
philosophy is,'' Duke said. ``He's operating on what he perceives my
philosophy was 10 years ago or 15 years ago. I wish he would have a
little bit more of an open mind.''
</TEXT>
