<FIRST>u a AM-PlantExplosion 2ndLd-Writethru a0758 02-23 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plant Explosion, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0758,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion at Industrial Plant Injures Five</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `A fire ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with employee
statement on cause of fire; SUBS grafs 7-8, `Four people . .., with 3 grafs
to to UPDATE with number of employees who fled, injured people treated
and discharged, CORRECT hospital name to Huguely, sted Hugely; ^By KELLEY
SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALVARADO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of explosions blew the roof off a
building in an explosives plant complex Thursday, rocking homes more
than a mile away and injuring at least five people, authorities said.
   Fire raced through the building at Jet Research Center Inc., a
manufacturer of explosives for oil production, triggering the
explosions around 2 p.m., said police in this community of 3,000.
   An employee, Corine Hines, said The fire began when a mixture of
chemical powders she was mixing in a jar ignited. ``It just blew up
in my face,'' Ms. Hines told WFAA-TV. ``I couldn't run because I
couldn't see.''
   Two other Jet Research buildings containing explosives were
untouched by fire and appeared to be safe several hours after the
blaze, said Johnson County Sheriff Eddy Boggs.
   Firefighters ran out of water about a half-hour after they began
battling the fire and decided to let it burn itself out.
   Police asked news helicopters to stay away, dispatcher Billye
Lane said about an hour after the blast. ``They're expecting it to
blow again,'' Lane said.
   ``The explosion shook my house,'' said Jack Hillis, who lives 1\
miles from the plant.
   Boggs said he did not know how many people were in the building,
but about 50 Jet Research employees fled the complex, witnesses said.
   Four people were taken by ambulance to Huguley Memorial Hospital
in Fort Worth, about 25 miles away. All were treated for minor
injuries, including burns and bruises, and discharged, said hospital
spokeswoman Mary Whitehead.
   Boggs said five people were injured. Ms. Whitehead said one
person at the scene declined treatment.
   John Weber, a farmer who lives three miles from the plant, felt
several explosions. ``I was just feeding the rabbits in the barn at
the time,'' Weber said. ``All of sudden the whole building just
shook.''
   Investigators from the Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms bureau and
the Occupational Safety and Health Administration were on the scene
late Thursday.
   Jet Research is a subsidiary of Dallas-based Halliburton Co.,
which acquired the company when it purchased Fort Worth-based
Gearhart Industries in September 1988.
   The plant is used in manufacturing ``shaped charges'' to
perforate oil wells, said Guy Marcus, a Halliburton vice president.
</TEXT>
