<SECOND>AM-Lukens Indicted, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0786,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ohio Congressman Indicted In Sex Case With Teen-Age Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to RECAST, addition comment from Lukens;
picks up 7th graf: `Lukens, who ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CO3,CS3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEITH ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Donald Lukens was indicted Thursday on
a misdemeanor charge that he had sex with a teen-age girl, but the
58-year-old congressman declared he was innocent.
   The charge stems from a meeting, secretly videotaped by a TV
station, between Lukens and the girl's mother, who contended Lukens
paid for sex with her daughter four years ago when the girl was 13
and again last November.
   The four-term conservative Republican, who is divorced, was
charged with contributing to the unruliness and delinquency of a
child. The offense carries up to six months in jail and a $1,000
fine.
   A state grand jury accused him of having sex with the girl on
Nov. 6, when she was 16, in his Columbus apartment. The girl is now
17.
   In a statement issued in Washington, Lukens said: ``I do
categorically deny that I contributed to the delinquency and
unruliness of a minor at any time, and I further categorically deny
the accuracy of the alleged facts upon which the charge was
apparently based. I am innocent of the charge brought forth today.''
   Lukens said his attorney had advised him against commenting on
the allegations. ``But I do feel an explanation is owed to my
friends and constituents in southwestern Ohio,'' he said.
   Lukens, who is from Middletown, about 30 miles north of
Cincinnati, and represents a rural district, said he was ``pleased
that the grand jury found no evidence for the basis of serious
charges.''
   The House Ethics Committee, which has jurisdiction over
allegations of wrongdoing by lawmakers, typically waits for the
outcome before taking any action in cases where members have been
charged in court.
   A criminal conviction does not automatically bar a legislator
from sitting in Congress.
   Franklin County Prosecutor Michael Miller said he had recommended
a different charge than the one returned, but he would not elaborate.
   Miller also said he recommended an additional charge against
Lukens for an alleged incident in 1985, when the girl was 13. Jurors
determined there was insufficient evidence because of conflicting
testimony from the girl, he said.
   No date for a court appearance was set for Lukens.
   Columbus TV station WSYX on Feb. 1 broadcast a videotape that
showed Lukens apparently offering a government job to Anna Coffman
after she asked why he was ``messin' around'' with her daughter. The
station videotaped the Nov. 11 meeting at a fast-food restaurant in
Columbus after Ms. Coffman contacted the station.
   Lukens told Ms. Coffman he thought her daughter was an adult,
according to the videotape. ``Well, first of all, I didn't really
know she was a teen-ager. I didn't know that, no. I do now, of
course,'' Lukens said.
   The FBI and prosecutors reviewed the tape and but said they found
no evidence of bribery.
   Ms. Coffman, interviewed by WDTN-TV of Dayton after the
indictment, said she had hoped for a more serious charge.
   ``I expected more because this is a very serious matter,'' Ms.
Coffman said. ``What kind of impression does it have on our
children, our future?''
   Mrs. Coffman's daughter said she thinks Lukens should be sent to
jail and stripped of his congressional seat.
   ``It's like a hurt right underneath my heart,'' the daughter
said. ``Donald Lukens, he ruins my life.''
   WDTN also interviewed Michelle Foster, 20, of Columbus, who said
she was Lukens' girlfriend. She said the girl's allegations are not
true.
   Lukens was first elected to Congress in 1966 and served two
terms. He lost a bid for governor in the 1970 GOP primary. He
returned to Congress in 1986 and was re-elected in November.
   After the 1970 race, he was barred from seeking office for five
years for not filing campaign reports on time. However, the law was
changed, and he was appointed to the state Senate in 1971 to fill an
unexpired term.
   In 1974, while in the state Senate, he fought allegations he
accepted $1,000 in campaign contributions from Korean businessman
Tongsun Park during his stint on Capitol Hill.
   He presented results of a voluntary lie detector test that
indicated he was not lying when he said he had not received a
contribution from Park.
</TEXT>
