<FIRST>u a AM-KempVisit 2ndLd-Writethru a0827 02-23 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kemp Visit, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0827,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Touring Homeless Shelters in Philadephia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Kemp quotes from Philadelphia
tour; picks up 2nd graf pvs: ``We want ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp visited a
Baltimore soup kitchen and a shelter Thursday, then came here to
continue his first-hand look at what he has called ``a national
tragedy of appalling proportions'' _ homelessness.
   In Philadelphia, Kemp visited a home for impoverished women and a
shelter for homeless men, ending the nighttime tour at a federally
subsidized apartment house for senior citizens where he was spending
the night.
   He said he came to the nation's fifth-largest city ``to talk with
folks and to listen, to learn about the problems, to see what
they've done and what I can do to be a catalyst, to make an impact,
make a difference in this problem.''
   ``It's a very human, real problem that exists and it's a national
tragedy, and (President) George Bush wants me to not only inventory
the problem but inventory some of the answers,'' he said.
   ``We want to make some changes,'' Kemp told an audience earlier
Thursday at the Viva House shelter in Baltimore, saying he came as
an advocate for their needs, not as an adversary.
   Viva House Director Brendan Walsh told Kemp that programs for the
homeless suffered during the Reagan administration. ``So much money
has gone to the military that the federal housing budget has been
cut from $31 billion to $7 billion,'' Walsh said.
   ``That's why I'm here,'' Kemp answered. ``I want to find some
answers to the problem of homelessness.''
   Kemp's Philadelphia tour began Thursday night at Women of Hope, a
permanent shelter for impoverished women. He was accompanied by
Pennsylvania's U.S. senators, Republicans John Heinz and Arlen
Specter.
   Kemp heard 16 victims of poverty complain about the lack of
affordable housing and jobs for unskilled workers.
   ``While we sit here in this room tonight, many of our sisters and
brothers are out in the freezing cold,'' said Sister Mary Scullion,
who runs the center.
   ``We expect you, as our representative, to begin to solve this
problem.''
   ``We wanted Kemp to see human faces,'' said Robert M. Hayes, an
attorney for the Coalition for the Homeless. ``Ten minutes on a
steam grate is worth 50 white papers.''
   In addition, Hayes said, the tour will help link Kemp to the
issue.
   ``I hope this touches his heart, but in any event, his political
future will be linked with his success in battling homelessness,''
Hayes said. ``We want to teach him, but we want to link him, and
he's jumping in head first.''
   Officials estimate 10,000 women, children and men are homeless in
the city.
   Kemp, who served nine terms as a conservative Republican
congressman from upstate New York, has called the plight of the
homeless ``a national tragedy of appalling proportions.''
   After his tour of various shelters, Kemp was to spend the night
at the Opportunity Towers, a federally supported apartment complex
for senior citizens in impoverished North Philadelphia.
   Henry Taylor, the building manager, said Kemp would have his own
apartment at the towers, which he described as being ``right in the
heart'' of the one of the city's low-income neighborhoods.
   The homeless issue went to the forefront in Philadelphia in
mid-December, when city workers demolished a ``cardboard city''
erected in a subway concourse by about 75 street people seeking
shelter from freezing temperatures.
   The workers returned the following night to clean out more
makeshift homes.
   Some of the homeless then left the concourse and erected
cardboard shelters outside the U.S. Courthouse, where they and
members of a Philadelphia coalition for the homeless maintained a
12-day vigil.
   In the morning, Kemp is to visit Dignity Housing, a North
Philadelphia shelter for homeless women and their children.
   Hayes, who is acting as a tour guide, called Kemp's visit ``a
non-ideological, novice's composite tour'' with as little time as
possible spent in offices with politicians.
   Kemp spent two days in Atlanta last week, visiting housing
projects, renewal programs, interim housing for the homeless, and
privately financed developments aimed at low- and moderate-income
families.
</TEXT>
