<SECOND>AM-City Council Scuffle,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Fight In Council Chamber</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wednesday's City Council meeting had a bit more
punch than usual when a councilman, who later explained he was tired
of being called a coward, scuffled with a lawyer.
   A stunned Mayor Annette Strauss and other council members watched
as colleague Al Gonzalez marched into the gallery and confronted
lawyer Domingo Garcia.
   Garcia said he had come to the council to speak on a zoning issue
when Gonzalez surprised him by coming up to his seat.
   Police officers quickly separated the two after Gonzalez, a
former professional boxer, began pummeling Garcia on his chest and
shoulders, observers said.
   A Gonzalez staff member was unable to say where the councilman
could be reached for comment by The Associated Press. But earlier,
Gonzalez told a Dallas radio station he does not remember throwing
the first punch.
   Garcia said he clearly was assaulted and later was asked by
police if he desired to press charges. Garcia declined.
   Both men agreed that the incident was politically provoked.
   ``Mr. Garcia had been making some personal remarks about me,''
Gonzalez told WBAP. ``He said something about me being a coward and
something about not having the courage, or what have you.
   ``I needed to defend my honor, and certainly I needed to defend
my name.''
   Garcia criticized Gonzalez about a month ago when the council
member said he would not endorse any Hispanics for the next council
elections. The 30-year-old Garcia and other Hispanic community
leaders have said that Gonzalez, who is not running again, is not
supporting their effort to replace him with another Hispanic.
