<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0834EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv23   02-23 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 23,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs., Feb. 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Economics I' The Hard Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you sometimes wonder why Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan is so worried about inflation, which might
not even reach 5 percent this year, think back to the 1970s.
   That was the decade in which the nation's economic powers lost
control of inflation and then, in a belated effort to restrain it,
forced interest rates to the highest levels in most Americans'
memory.
   The 1970s were not a long time ago, but the pace of economic
activity is so swift now that those days seem buried in history, and
gone with them _ somehow forgotten _ are the financial tragedies
that destroyed ordinary people.
   The setting for the disaster was in the previous decade, that of
the 1960s, when inflation was insignificant. From 1958 through 1965
the consumer price index, measured from one December to the next,
never even reached 2 percent.
   Stability of that sort made planning easy. You saved your money
at a certain rate of interest and, low as that rate was, you could
project your financial assets far into the future. You knew where
you stood.
   In the latter half of the 1960s things began to change, in part
because the United States under President Lyndon Johnson sought to
pursue a guns and butter economy. That is, Johnson said, both an
Asian war and a Great Society were possible.
   It wasn't true, as history demonstrated. Inflation began creeping
into the economy as budget deficits appeared. By 1969 it exceeded 6
percent. It slowed a bit over the next three years, then it struck a
devastating blow.
   From 1967 to the end of 1983 the consumer price index tripled. In
the 1970s alone it doubled. Three times between 1974 and 1980 the
rise in the price index exceeded 10 percent, reaching an incredible
13.3 percent in 1979.
   At 13.3 percent, the value of a dollar is cut in half in less
than 5{ years. While that was the extreme, and lasted for only a
year, the average annual inflation rate in the 1970s exceeded 7
percent.
   At 7 percent a year, the value of savings accounts, insurance
policies, savings bonds and the like is cut in half in 10 years.
True, savings accounts and savings bonds did earn interest, but at
much less than the inflation rate.
   Many savings accounts, for example, were fixed by law at 5.25
percent.
   Those people who believed in old virtues such as saving for a
rainy day, virtues nurtured in the steady decade of the 1960s, found
themselves robbed.
   Meanwhile, those who borrowed to speculate on inflation became
rich. In spite of rising interest rates, investors borrowed heavily
and bought real assets, such as houses. Housing prices soared _
faster even than the CPI.
   So what if interest rates were high? You wrote them off on your
taxes. And you repaid the mortgage in cheaper dollars. And you also
wrote off depreciation on the house while it doubled in market value.
   All this was possible because other people had saved money in the
good old American tradition, and were robbed. It was the heist of
the century, as if a big truck had been backed up to the banks of
America.
   Some of those people, mainly older ones, never recovered. And, of
course, the inflation that robbed them, and the efforts to overcome
it, pitched them into still another disaster, the terrible recession
that followed the '70s.
   This sad tale was just one of the consequences of the great
inflation of the 1970s. While the economy is different today, the
consequences are no less _ and probably much greater.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs., Feb. 23.</NOTE>
</DOC>
