<DOCNO> AP890223-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0833EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Babar Adv27   02-23 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Babar, Adv 27,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Feb 27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>All Hail the Elephant King</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian animators turning the Babar stories into
a television series and feature film are well aware of the long
memories their viewers may have of the elephant king.
   ``You have generations of people who have heard of Babar,''
director Laura Shepherd said. ``You don't want to contradict that.''
   The Babar stories date back to 1931 in France, first by Jean de
Brunhoff and then his son Laurent.
   After Toronto-based Nelvana productions won the rights to produce
a Babar series, the team that would be working on the project
immersed itself in the books to find out what was so special about
the them.
   The result _ churned out at the company's headquarters in a
fashionably renovated munitions factory _ already has started
showing on the Canadian Broadcasting Corp. in a weekly, evening slot
and will start this spring on Home Box Office in the United States.
The programs can be expected in other countries as well.
   Marvelous as the books might be, the animators found more visual
strength and character in them than 30-minute plot lines for
animation.
   ``The story lines had to be significantly changed, (but) the
bottom line for us is that the spirit's still there,'' Shepherd said,
   Indeed, it's hard not to smile through much of the first shows,
possibly because of the animated characters of Babar, Celeste, the
Old Lady and all the rest or perhaps just from the lingering
goodwill of old memories.
   The company is hoping to attract parents as well as children.
   ``We had to show networks it could work for the whole family,''
said producer Michael Hirsch, one of the company's three founders.
   The solution was to concentrate on stories about Babar as a young
king. Each episode is framed with a ``bookend'' featuring the more
familiar, older Babar and his family, flashing back to problems that
he had as a boy king and how he solved them.
   In one, for example, one of Babar's sons tries to please everyone
at his birthday party by entertaining too many special guests. Babar
then recalls how he once had a date with Celeste and a gorilla
princess at the same time.
   ``We made the theme of the series growing up,'' Hirsch said. ``We
think it makes it easier for older children and adults.''
   That makes Babar significantly different from one of Nelvana's
earlier success stories since the company's start in 1972, the Care
Bears projects, which were aimed for children from 2 to 6.
   Hirsch and fellow producer Patrick Loubert, two of the company's
three founders, don't worry about the sometimes mixed reviews the
simpler projects have had. ``The Care Bears are frankly for younger
kids. They work on a young kid level,'' Loubert said.
   ``Care Bears have very high parental approval,'' Hirsch said.
``Children love it, parents love it, but reviewers have the toughest
time of it.''
   The first Babar episode drew mixed reviews in Toronto, where the
Toronto Star said Nelvana succeeded in ``a painstaking balance of
styles'' while the Globe and Mail said fans would be better advised
to stick to the books.
   The first episode includes the scene in which his mother is
killed by a hunter, recalling the tragic episode in the animated
Disney movie, ``Bambi.''
   Asked if it was difficult to include such a scene in a children's
series, Loubert replied: ``It's a classic property. I believe the
death of the mother was part of the story. ... We agonized over it,
let me tell you. There was a lot of talk.''
   The producers are hoping for a long run with the series and Babar
animated films, the first due this summer.
   The company, which among earlier animation projects handled Star
Wars characters and the Strawberry Shortcake fad, also is taking a
direct role in licensing for the first time. The producers talk
about Babar being as durable as a Disney character, so the elephant
can be expected on everything from sheets to toys.
   ``Not everything lasts,'' Loubert said. ``We would hope that this
property would last for years.''
   ``We want Babar to be a perennial,'' Hirsch said.
   Nelvana is among the more visible companies in the growing
Toronto film and TV production industry. It claims to be among the
world's top 10 animation companies.
   The arrangement with Laurent de Brunhoff was made by Clifford
Ross, who formed a company to work with classic children's stories
and then brought Babar to Nelvana.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Feb 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
