<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv26   02-23 0966</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv26,1002</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Last Year's Drought Still a Vivid Memory for Many Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Given normal precipitation as winter fades
away, farmers will take to the fields this spring hoping for bumper
crops, good prices and smiles at the bank just in case of hail or a
summer dry spell.
   Just about everywhere, though, lurks the memory of last year's
heat and drought that caused billions of dollars in losses to crops
and livestock.
   ``Many farmers who had successfully survived the farm financial
turbulence of the mid-1980s faced a new challenge (in 1988) as their
crops withered in the fields,'' says an Agriculture Department
report. ``Some farmers were fortunate enough to have large crop
inventories from the previous season and could sell them at
drought-induced higher prices.''
   Others made extensive use of irrigation and harvested good crops
at substantially higher prices.
   But there were others who had no stored grain, no irrigation and
not much chance of convincing lenders that the 1988 drought was just
a glitch and that times were bound to get better in 1989 or 1990.
   The staff report by the department's Economic Research Service
estimated that without drought relief, some 20,000 to 30,000 of the
nation's 550,000 commercial farmers _ those with annual sales of
$40,000 or more _ suffered losses that put their long-term survival
at risk.
   As it was, Congress passed the $3.9 billion Disaster Assistance
Act to help hard-hit farmers. That law and its relief programs will
``likely reduce the core problem group'' by half and leave 10,000 to
20,000 shaky farms, the report said.
   Most of the farms hurt most by drought losses are in the northern
Great Plains, Corn Belt and Great Lakes areas.
   Higher prices for the big grain inventories kept the cash income
of farmers nationally at a near-record level in 1988, despite
drought and lower yields.
   ``Cash income in 1989 is expected to fall somewhat because
farmers likely will replenish inventories, will receive fewer
government payuments because of higher commodity prices, and,
consistent with increased planting, will incur somewhat larger
expenses,'' the report said.
   ``Nonetheless,'' it added, ``the farm sector will be in a
stronger financial position in 1989 and possibly 1990 because the
drought lowered burdensome stockpiles, especially corn, while
strengthening commodity prices.''
   The drought of 1988 was a major event for agriculture, with crop
and livestock losses at around $13 billion in dollars of 1982 buying
power. Those losses amounted to only about 0.3 percent of the
nation's real Gross National Product, or the total value of all
goods and services produced last year, the report said.
   In specific areas, however, the effects of the 1988 drought were
much more disheartening.
   The report included findings on five severely hit areas of
Montana, North Dakota, Wisconsin, Illinois and Ohio. Here are
descriptions of these areas and capsule summaries of the drought
impacts.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>MONTANA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An eight-county area in the northeast, including large-scale
wheat farms and cattle ranches. The average farm is more than 3,500
acres, compared with the U.S. average of 440 acres.
   The direct farm loss from the drought was estimated at $152.5
million, most of it from reduced wheat production. An estimated
federal drought assistance payment of $68 million reduced the loss
to around $85 million.
   The drought's impact on the overall economy ``could be
substantial'' as well, with a potential drop in total business
activity of nearly 10 percent, even after federal aid.
   The counties covered were Daniels, Dawson, Garfield, McCone,
Roosevelt, Richland, Sheridan and Valley.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>NORTH DAKOTA</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-county area in the north-central part of the state. It is
also the most farm-dependent area of those examined. Farm production
accounted for 32 percent of percent of all jobs in 1985 and
agribusiness accounted for another 3 percent. The farms produce
mainly wheat and barley.
   Sales in the livestock sector are mostly beef cattle but include
some swine and dairy cattle.
   Drought losses to agriculture were estimated at $114.6 million,
with federal assistance offsetting about $35 million of the total
losses.
   The counties covered were Benson, Bottineau, McHenry, Pierce and
Rolette.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>WISCONSIN</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A seven-county area in the southwest involves mostly medium-sized
dairy farms. Twenty-six percent of all employment is in farm
production, with another 5 percent in agribusiness. More than half
of all farm sales are dairy products.
   Direct loss to farmers was estimated at $134.2 million, largely
because of higher feed costs. Federal drought aid was estimated at
$29.4 million.
   The counties covered were Crawford, Grant, Iowa, Lafayette,
Richland, Sauk and Vernon.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>ILLINOIS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven counties in east-central Illinois, representing ``one of
the most productive farming areas in the United States,'' deep in
the heart of the Corn Belt. The farm sector is dominated by medium
and large farms that produce corn and soybeans.
   But while farming is important, the area's economic base is ``not
very dependent'' on agriculture. Most local jobs are in industry or
government, with farm production accounting for about 7 percent and
agribusiness about 5 percent.
   Drought losses to farmers were estimated at $326 million, of
which $108 million was offset by federal payments.
   The counties covered were Champaign, Ford, Iroquois, Livingston,
Kankakee, Piatt and Vermillion.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>OHIO</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven counties in the northwest, dominated by manufacturing and
other non-farm economic activities. Farming accounts for only 4
percent of total employment, with agribusiness adding 3 percent.
Corn and soybeans account for more than half of total farm sales.
   Corn and soybean losses were estimated to be 40 percent and 25
percent, respectively. Total direct losses from drought were
estimated at $164.8 million, with drought payments offsetting about
$31 million.
   The counties include Allen, Defiance, Fulton, Henry, Lucas,
Hancock, Paulding, Putnam, Van Wert, Williams and Wood.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
