<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-23 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0896</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices shot up 0.6 percent last month,
their fastest rise in two years, the government said in a report
that analysts cited as fresh evidence of entrenched and accelerating
inflation.
   Propelled by higher costs for food, energy and a variety of other
goods and services, the seasonally adjusted increase in the Consumer
Price Index doubled the moderate 0.3 percent gains of November and
December, the Labor Department said Wednesday.
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, meanwhile, stepped up
his warnings about higher inflation, pointedly noting the disturbing
increase in consumer prices and raising the prospects of a recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration sent its 333-page
savings and loan bailout bill to Congress, where lawmakers from both
parties immediately started picking away at its key provisions.
   Members of the Senate Banking Committee on Wednesday attacked
provisions to raise S&amp;Ls' capital requirements, finance the
government portion of the bailout off the federal budget _ at an
extra cost of $4.6 billion to taxpayers _ and give the Treasury
Department greater control over the institutions.
   Meanwhile, in their rush to catch up to thrift industry fraud and
mismanagement, federal regulators may have unknowingly hired some of
the culprits responsible for the savings and loan debacle, The
Associated Press has learned.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House budget director Richard Darman,
attacked by Democrats for playing games when the deficit must be
cut, refused to reveal President Bush's policies on a wide swath of
domestic programs.
   Darman repeatedly declined Wednesday to say what spending levels
Bush wanted next year for programs such as care for poor pregnant
women, veterans' education, mass transit or the Job Training
Partnership Act.
   Also on Wednesday, the government reported that it posted a $2.8
billion surplus in January due to a surge in revenue caused by
quarterly tax payments from individuals.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's largest airline announced a $3.15
billion order for 20 Boeing 747-400s and said negotiations are under
way for up to 20 Boeing 767s.
   The sale announced Wednesday of 747-400s to All Nippon Airways
for delivery beginning in 1992 came despite Boeing's inability to
meet delivery deadlines for the sophisticated jumbo jets to other
airlines.
   The order, added to six 747-400s ordered by All Nippon in
October, makes the airline the biggest purchaser of the new model.
Japan Air Lines ordered 20 of the same model in July 1987. British
Airways PLC ordered 19 in August 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines pilots said they would cross
Machinist union picket lines if there's a strike next month,
provided the troubled carrier's owner grants them concessions in
their own contract.
   Wednesday's statement from Eastern's pilots union came after it
had threatened to join the machinists in a possible March 4 walkout,
and was seen as an overture to Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank
Lorenzo, who controls Eastern.
   In Washington, meanwhile, a federal mediator began meeting with
representatives of Eastern and the Machinists in an effort to reach
a settlement before a 30-day cooling-off period expires.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penny stock scams and non-Wall Street insider
trading will be the main targets of a new coast-to-coast federal
battle against securities fraud, investigators say.
   Disclosure of offenses to be prosecuted, made in telephone
interviews this week, marked the first mention of specific
objectives for new task forces in six cities formed by Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh last month.
   The Justice Department is spending $2 million to hire prosecutors
for the fraud patrols, the first permanent structured assault on
financial corruption in a decade of highly publicized Wall Street
crimes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A continued drought this year would push crop
prices to record highs, trigger a new round of food price increases
and magnify loan losses for farm lenders, a government economist
warned.
   Mark Drabenstott, assistant vice president and economist at the
Federal Reserve Bank in Kansas City, Mo., on Wednesday forecast a
bleak outlook for agriculture if dry weather again plagues the
nation's Farm Belt as it did last year.
   The Agriculture Department's chief meteorologist, Norton
Strommen, has said a recurrence of last year's severe drought is
unlikely. Drabenstott agreed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s plans to streamline its
advertising budget is raising concerns among newspapers that count
the nation's biggest retailer as a major source of revenue, industry
leaders said.
   Publishers expressed uncertainty Wednesday about the financial
impact of the proposed changes by Sears, the nation's largest
newspaper advertiser.
   But some newspaper executives who are negotiating with Sears say
they believe the talks will produce agreements beneficial to both
sides.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Fear of inflation and higher interest rates produced the stock
market's worst day in three months Wednesday. The Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials fell 42.50 points to 2,283.93.
   The dollar fell against most major foreign currencies. Gold
prices gained, driven higher by the government's inflation report.
   Bond prices tumbled, weakened by the inflation data.
   Copper futures prices rose sharply; precious metals and energy
futures advanced; grains and soybeans were mostly higher; and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
