<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WorkerHousing Bjt   02-23 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Worker Housing, Bjt,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Hotel Union Contract Could Spark Change In Federal Labor Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at Boston's hotels are eager to improve
their living conditions through a unique union contract provision,
but their use of the union's new housing fund is on hold because it
apparently violates federal law.
   Business and labor leaders alike hailed the affordable housing
trust fund adopted in December by Boston's hotel management and the
AFL-CIO's local hotel and restaurant workers union as part of the
workers' contract.
   Labor advocates say substandard housing conditions are as
unacceptable as inadequate health care and that union aid is long
overdue, especially in expensive housing markets such as Boston's.
   The plan also has been touted as a potential boon for
hard-to-staff businesses based in pricey resort areas like
Massachusetts' Martha's Vineyard or Aspen, Colo.
   But the ground-breaking fund has sparked concern that it violates
federal labor law.
   Lawmakers in Washington are considering whether to legalize the
housing fund under the labor restrictions contained in the
Labor-Management Relations Act of 1947.
   The legislation, known as the Taft-Hartley Act, was initiated
chiefly to prevent union kickbacks by specifying exactly what kinds
of joint union-management funds may be established.
   ``The law has to catch up to the times,'' said Bruce Marx, the
local union's housing director. ``We have to pick up the slack for
the reduction in the federal government's involvement in housing,
and yet the law makes it illegal for unions and management to
cooperate.''
   Boston union leaders last year proposed the fund to help workers
afford the city's housing. The leaders envisioned building housing
with the fund, or subsidizing mortgages, down payments and rental
deposits.
   In a recent survey, 98 percent of the city's hotel workers
reported they could not afford to buy a medium-priced home, while 78
percent said the couldn't rent an average apartment, Marx said.
   Recent figures show the median cost of a home in Boston is about
$177,200 while the average hotel worker's annual salary is $16,000.
   Resolved to bridge the housing affordability gap, labor leaders
negotiated up to a December strike deadline before securing the
unprecedented housing fund.
   The three-year agreement requires hotels to funnel $1 million
into the housing trust, which will be combined with $12 million in
union pension funds earmarked for upgrading workers' accommodations.
   Hotel managers initially were reluctant to adopt the fund but
reconsidered when it became apparent that housing was a top priority
for most of the 3,000 union workers, said Peter Van Kleek, president
and chief executive officer for Saunders Hotel Co. Inc., which
operates three large Boston hotels.
   ``Our reaction in the final analysis was that we want to respond
to those issues which the workers feel are important,'' he said.
   Nevertheless, Van Kleek predicted the fund could run into trouble
on Capitol Hill.
   ``There have been any number of efforts over the years to reopen
Taft-Hartley and there is, I'm sure, a whole shopping list of items
people would like to see included,'' he said. ``I suspect there
might be some controversy.''
   But Richard Ferlauto, a director at the American Affordable
Housing Institute, said housing has become a critical concern
nationwide. The housing fund is thus likely to gain bipartisan
support in Congress, where lawmakers are expected to set the labor
policy agenda in coming weeks, he said.
   ``We happen to think that housing benefits will be the new
collective bargaining benefit of the 1990s, much like day care was
the cutting edge issue in the 1980s,'' said Ferlauto, whose New
Brunswick, N.J.-based institute is affiliated with Rutgers
University.
   Labor activists are pushing for an amendment to current federal
law before June 1990, at which time the money being set aside for
housing will revert to the union's health and welfare fund if no
such legislation has been passed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 0828EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Unisys Bjt   02-23 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unisys, Bjt,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Lays Off 1,700 Workers As Part Of Major Restructuring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp., which last week promised to
trim its work force by 3 percent in 1989, has effectively met its
goal by laying off 1,700 employees at 60 U.S. locations in a major
restructuring.
   In addition to the U.S. layoffs, the company said Wednesday from
its headquarters in suburban Blue Bell that it will close a
component assembly plant in Nogales, Mexico, at a cost of 400 jobs.
   ``Obviously this is a major restructuring ... that has brought us
essentially into the range where we told people we wanted to be for
1989,'' said J. Peter Hynes, a Unisys spokesman.
   The move comes on the heels of last week's announcement by Unisys
Chairman W. Michael Blumenthal that the computer giant planned to
reduce its work force of 93,000 by 3 percent this year, or about
2,800 people, and cut more than $500 million from its inventories by
mid-year.
   About 190 employees at the company's headquarters were laid off
Wednesday, and about 400 more will lose their jobs at the end of
July, when the company consolidates a computer-design group at the
headquarters with a larger division in Roseville, Minn., Unisys said.
   The action this week was just the latest move in Unisys' employee
cutbacks.
   Since Burroughs Corp.'s $4.8 billion takeover of Sperry created
Unisys in 1986, the company has pared 18,000 from its payroll
through sales of operations and 12,000 more through early
retirements and layoffs, not counting the layoffs announced
Wednesday.
   Hynes said only ``a small number'' of the affected employees
would be transferred or rehired.
   Hynes said all employees released this week will receive six
weeks' pay in addition to a severance package. All also are eligible
for job counseling, he said.
   Hynes said earlier that about 900 of Unisys' 68,000 U.S.
employees have been offered early retirement so far this year.
   On Tuesday, Unisys introduced a long-awaited line of mainframe
computers designed by the engineering group in Blue Bell. The new
2200 series will replace the company's 1100 line. The product's
release was delayed by several months, hurting sales as customers
postponed purchases until the new line was available.
   Blumenthal acknowledged last week that it had been ``a tougher
year'' than anticipated and that he expected a weakness in sales to
continue in the first half of 1989.
   Sales in 1988 increased 2 percent from 1987, to $9.9 billion.
Although Unisys' profits rose about 18 percent in 1988, most of the
increase was attributable to lower tax rates, not bigger profit
margins. The company's operating profits slumped by nearly
one-quarter in the final quarter of 1988.
   At a recent meeting with Wall Street analysts, senior executives
said they expected results from the first three months of 1989 to be
``poor,'' with no revenue growth, largely because of the bottoming
of the 1100 product cycle.
   The second quarter will improve as the new computer line starts
kicking in revenue, while the third and fourth quarters will be
``exceptional,'' they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
