<TEXT>
   The stock market lost more ground today in a
carryover of selling from Wednesday's sharp drop.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .18 to 2,283.75
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outumbered gainers by about 5 to 2 in the early tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 267 up, 691 down and 510
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 22.69 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said the markets were still struggling to recover from
the jolt of the report Wednesday that the consumer price index
jumped 0.6 percent in January.
   The news sent bond prices lower and stepped up expectations that
the Federal Reserve might feel compelled to tighten credit further
and faster than it had previously planned.
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, described the report as
``disturbing.''
   With all that, however, brokers said blue chips began to recover
today, benefiting from buying by money managers who had been looking
for a pullback in prices to move some of their large cash reserves
into stocks.
   Among the blue chips, International Business Machines dropped ]
to 123; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was unchanged at 30{, and
General Electric rose [ to 45}.
   Japanese issues were strong after the Tokyo market set a new
high. Honda Motor rose 2~ to 159 and Matsushita gained 2| to 188.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .13 to 163.42. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .62 at 321.45.
   On Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 42.50 points
to 2,283.93, for its biggest decline in three months.
   Declining issues outnumbered gainers by nearly 4 to 1 in
nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 332 up, 1,197 down
and 446 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 163.14 million
shares, up from 141.95 million in the previous session.
