<HEAD>West Point-Pepperell To Announce Auction Results</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile giant West Point-Pepperell Inc.,
target of a $1.53 billion hostile takeover from rival Farley Inc.,
convened its board of directors today to decide who would acquire
the company.
   The West Point, Ga.-based company was put on the auction block
Feb. 3 as the board sought to thwart the $52-per-share offer by
Chicago-based Farley.
   The company said its board was meeting but didn't specify when an
announcement would be made.
   Farley, which owns underwear-manufacturer Fruit of the Loom Inc.
and Acme Boot Co. Inc., has informed the Securities and Exchange
Commission it has made a bid for the company separate from the
tender offer. The terms of that offer have not been disclosed.
   The Wall Street Journal reported earlier this week that Merrill
Lynch &amp; Co., or its separate leveraged buyout unit Merrill Lynch
Capital Partners, had put in a bid for the company, which has about
a quarter of the nation's home fashion textile market through such
brands as Lady Pepperell, Martex and Utica.
   Other companies reportedly showing interest in Pepperell include
Dominion Textile Inc. of Montreal and Milliken &amp; Co. of Spartanburg,
S.C.
   Pepperell, founded in 1886, became the nation's largest publicly
traded textile company last year through the acquisition of most of
J.P. Stevens &amp; Co. Inc.
   It has 41,000 employees and 22,000 stockholders. The company
earned $10.8 million on revenues of $683.13 million in the last
quarter of 1988. For the fiscal year ended Sept. 24, the company had
revenue of $2.15 billion and earnings of $84.36 million.
</TEXT>
