<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Retreat Amid Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mostly lower in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade as speculators
took profits after three days of rising prices.
   The early sell-off followed indications that the Soviet Union
purchased 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices
overnight. The wheat market had rallied Wednesday in anticipation of
such a purchase, and today's opening losses reflected traders'
tendency to ``buy the rumor, sell the fact.''
   Soybean and corn futures also opened slightly lower. Some
analysts said the soybean market was overbought and due for a
correction after the solid gains of the three previous sessions.
   This week's higher prices also prompted a pick-up in farmer sales
of corn and soybeans. The increased availability was reflected in
this morning's lower futures prices.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.24} a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 1\ cents lower with March at $2.72 a bushel; oats were { cent to
1\ cents lower with March at $2.12\ a bushel; soybeans were { cent
to 2{ cents lower with March at $7.53{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were moderately higher in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .47 cent higher with April at 78.17
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .43 cent higher with
March at 84.37 cents a pound; live hogs were .38 cent to .78 cent
higher with April at 43.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.32 cent to .55 cent higher with March at 39.27 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
