<FIRST>u f BC-ChryslerPlant     02-23 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chrysler Plant,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler: New Dodge Sport Utility Vehicle To Be Made In Detroit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Dodge sport-utility vehicle and
another Jeep vehicle will be built in early 1992 at a new Chrysler
Corp. plant in Detroit, the company said Thursday.
   The vehicle, code named the ``ZJ,'' will be the first
sport-utility vehicle marketed by Dodge dealers, the company said in
a statement. It will be the only vehicle made at Chrysler's planned
Jefferson North plant.
   The ``ZJ'' will be larger than the Jeep Cherokee, now made at a
Chrysler plant in Toledo, Ohio, the statement added. Details of the
vehicle will be available when production starts.
   The Dodge and Jeep versions would be different, but Chrysler
spokesman Doug Nicholl declined to say how.
   The $1 billion Jefferson North factory will replace Chrysler's
current Jefferson Avenue plant. Chrysler said it expects to begin
construction at the Jefferson North complex in two months and that
production would start in January 1992.
   The new plant, with two shifts operating, will have a production
capacity of about 200,000 vehicles a year by 1993, Nicholl said.
   Chrysler now makes the Plymouth Horizon and the Dodge Omni at the
Jefferson Avenue plant. A production decision involving those two
cars beyond 1992 has not been made.
   The No. 3 automaker said it is putting the new sport-utility
vehicle at the Jefferson North plant because of growing demand in
that segment of the light truck market and because the Toledo plant
was at full production levels.
</TEXT>
