<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices sagged today in a carryover of
selling from Wednesday's sharp drop.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 42.50 points
Wednesday for its largest loss in three months, dropped 5.36 to
2,278.57 by noontime today on Wall Street.
   Losers outumbered gainers by about 8 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 467 up, 767 down and
560 unchanged.
   Analysts said the markets were still struggling to recover from
the jolt of the report Wednesday that the consumer price index
jumped 0.6 percent in January.
   The news sent bond prices lower and stepped up expectations that
the Federal Reserve might feel compelled to tighten credit further
and faster than it had previously planned.
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, described the report as
``disturbing.''
   With all that, however, brokers said blue chips attracted some
support today from buying by money managers who had been looking for
a pullback in prices to move some of their large cash reserves into
stocks.
   One group that benefited from the new flareup of inflation
worries was the gold mining stocks. Battle Mountain Gold gained ~ to
15{; Homestake Mining { to 14{ and Placer Dome | to 14].
   Aristech Chemical jumped 5 to 36{. The company said Wednesday
that Jon Huntsman, chief executive of Huntsman Chemical, apparently
wants to buy at least $15 million of Aristech stock.
   Japanese issues were strong after the Tokyo market set a new
high. Honda Motor rose 3 to 159[ and Matsushita gained 2| to 188.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .27 to 163.28. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .36 at 321.71.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 75.41 million shares at noontime,
down from 81.75 million at the same point Wednesday.
