<FIRST>u f PM-UtilityBankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru   02-23 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Utility Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Suggests Auctioning Off Debt-Ridden Utility</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with new grafs 8-10; subs grafs 8 and 12 pvs to conform</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. bankruptcy judge overseeing the
future of Public Service Company of New Hampshire proposed
auctioning off the insolvent utility, still swamped in debt from the
stalled Seabrook nuclear power plant.
   Judge James Yacos made the surprising suggestion Wednesday during
the first day of a hearing on the direction of the utility's
complex, 13-month-old bankruptcy case.
   ``I realize this is coming out of left field,'' Yacos said after
raising the auction idea with Steven Davis, president of a
bondholders group that is a major player in the reorganization, the
biggest by an investor-owned utility since the Depression.
   Yacos asked Davis, who was the first witness at the hearing,
whether it would be feasible to establish a set of terms and
conditions that all bidders would have to meet.
   Davis replied that Yacos' idea could work _ but only if there
first is agreement on what electricity rates the reorganized or
bought-out Public Service will be allowed to charge.
   ``The auction procedure you have outlined could be very valuable
and useful, provided rate levels are set beforehand,'' Davis told
the judge.
   Differences among the state, the utility and its creditors on
appropriate rates already have turned the reorganization into a
bitter and potentially lengthy ordeal.
   In testimony today, an executive of a utility hoping to buy
Public Service's non-Seabrook assets warned against being too
specific in setting terms for bids to settle the bankruptcy.
   ``I'm very concerned that if we overly structure the process,
we'll end up undervaluing the outcome,'' said Robert Busch, senior
vice president for finance of Connecticut-based Northeast Utilities.
   Busch said bids submitted without a formal structure could be
compared with one another adequately, though that wouldn't be easy.
   In debt from its 36 percent share of Seabrook and barred by state
law from charging ratepayers for the reactor before it operates
commercially, Public Service sought bankruptcy protection on Jan.
28, 1988.
   Settlement talks among New Hampshire officials, the utility and
its creditors broke off in December, and Public Service filed a
reorganization proposal on Dec. 27 under which it would seek federal
regulation and gain higher rate increases than the state is willing
to offer.
   State officials have offered rate increases totaling 22 percent
over five years, and say the rates Public Service seeks would drive
away customers and prove counterproductive. Public Service wants the
equivalent of a one-time increase of about 30 percent.
   The utility, which serves 75 percent of New Hampshire's 1 million
residents, is trying to get an extension of the ``exclusivity
period'' during which it has the exclusive right to make
restructuring proposals.
   However, state officials, creditors and Northeast Utilities _ New
England's largest power company _ oppose the extension, charging
that Public Service is stalling.
   To reach a decision, Yacos said, ``This court has to know whether
there are real negotiations going on and whether they are going
anywhere.''
   Northeast Utilities already has announced a bid for Public
Service, which says about a dozen other companies also have
expressed interest. New England Electric System of Massachusetts is
the only one to have said so far that it plans to bid too.
   Davis, president of Consolidated Utilities &amp; Communications Inc.,
was called to the witness stand by Public Service's chief bankruptcy
lawyer, Richard Levin. With banking giant Citicorp, Consolidated
owns key Public Service third-mortgage bonds.
   Davis testified for four hours on whether the judge should let
creditors and other parties start filing reorganization proposals _
buyouts or otherwise _ to compete with the proposal Public Service
filed Dec. 27.
   Since filing its restructuring plan, Public Service has said it
was continuing negotiations with Consolidated and other creditors.
But state officials refused to join the talks, saying the company
and its creditors were not being realistic in their demands.
   Davis disclosed Wednesday that talks with the company on rates
broke off during the first week of February.
   ``That particular effort is not going forward,'' Davis told
Levin. He said another meeting was held Thursday on other matters,
but he declined to elaborate, saying the participants have agreed to
confidentiality. Davis said no further talks are scheduled.
</TEXT>
