<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     02-23 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Car, Truck Sales Off 0.4 Percent In Mid-February</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales by the nation's Big
Three automakers dropped 0.4 percent in mid-February compared wiith
a year earlier, the companies said Thursday.
   The Big Three said gains in truck sales were offset by losses in
automobile sales.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. reported
they sold cars and trucks at an average daily rate of 34,580 during
the Feb. 11-20 period, compared with a rate of 34,718 during the
same 1988 period.
   Car sales by the Big Three dropped 3.2 percent, to an average of
21,507 a day from a 22,209 daily average in mid-February last year.
   Truck sales, meanwhile, jumped 4.5 percent to an average of
13,072 a day, compared with a 12,509 a year ago.
   Car sales during January and February 1988 were strong due to
incentives. After a big surge in late December last year, sales have
been running below last year's pace, but Thursday's figures showed a
narrowing of that gap.
   So far in 1989, the Big Three have sold cars and trucks at a pace
4.9 percent slower than a year ago. Car sales showed a big downturn,
dropping 8.4 percent, and truck sales have shown a modest upturn,
rising 1.5 percent.
   Chrysler showed a big dip, falling 18.5 percent during the period
this year. The nation's No. 3 automaker said its average daily sales
rate for cars fell to 2,960, compared with 3,630 last year. Car
sales for 1989 at Chrysler were 15.1 percent below the rate through
mid-February last year.
   Chrysler's truck sales rose 7.1 percent, going to a daily rate of
3,105 compared with a 2,899 daily rate a year ago.
   GM's car sales fell 1.2 percent, dropping to a daily rate of
11,714 from 11,852. For the year, GM's car sales are off 11.8
percent this year.
   GM reported a 3.3 percent gain in truck sales, rising to a daily
rate of 5,169 from a rate of 5,006.
   Ford said its car sales rose 1.6 percent in mid-February, going
to a daily rate of 6,833 compared with 6,727. Ford's annual car
sales are running 0.4 percent ahead of last year, rising to a daily
average of 6,441 from 6,415.
   Ford said it sold an average of 4,798 trucks during the period,
up 4.2 percent from 4,604 in the 1988 period.
</TEXT>
