<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Bally     02-23 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bally,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bally Calls Off Spinoff Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bally Manufacturing Corp. has canceled a proposed
restructuring because of opposition by New Jersey gaming officials
to a spinoff of its casino-hotel operations.
   Bally had announced in October a plan to make its four casinos _
two in Atlantic City, N.J., and two in Nevada _ a separate, publicly
owned company. Bally had proposed to retain a 15 percent stake in
the new firm.
   But in a preliminary opinion issued Wednesday, the gaming
enforcement division of the New Jersey attorney general's office
objected to the plan. It did not disclose its reasons.
   ``We're not going ahead with the plan because of New Jersey's
opposition,'' Bally spokesman William Peltier said.
   Anthony Parrillo, director of New Jersey's gaming enforcement
division, said the opinion would not be made public unless Bally
pursued the matter before the state Casino Control Commission.
   Parrillo did say his office believed the spinoff would leave
Bally's Atlantic City casino-hotels ``financially weakened.''
   The Chicago Tribune quoted an unidentified source saying the
division's principle objection was that the casino-hotels would have
to take on more debt as part of the spinoff plan.
   The spinoff would have left Bally with a health-club chain; the
Aladdin's Castle video-arcade chain; and three companies that
manufacture fitness, lottery and gaming equipment. Bally sold its
pinball and video-game manufacturing operations last year.
</TEXT>
