<HEAD>London Stocks Off 17.1 Points</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to delete AMs note</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed lower Thursday as the market
succumbed again to fears about rising world interest rates and the
recent weak trend on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 17.1
points, or 0.8 percent, lower at 2,016.6, having traded as much as
18.4 points lower soon after the opening. The index hit a session
high of 2,030.4, off 3.3 points, at midday.
   Volume was a moderate 551.7 million, compared with 551.6 million
shares Wednesday.
   After proving remarkably resilient in the morning to Wall
Street's steep fall Wednesday, stocks moved sharply lower in the
face of another drop in New York and more weakness in the U.S. bond
market.
   More signs of weakness in the pound also contributed to the
equity market's worries, dashing hopes of a cut in British interest
rates.
   With most players uncertain about the immediate outlook in the
currency markets, large institutional investors preferred to remain
on the sidelines, dealers said.
