<DOCNO> AP890223-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1417EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     02-23 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Lower In Europe, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged lower in choppy European trading
Thursday as the market remained vaguely bearish but still unsure
about the dollar's outlook. Gold rose.
   Dealers said the dollar was driven lower by skepticism over the
likelihood of higher U.S. interest rates, and by the West German
mark's strength. The mark, in turn, was helped by continuing
speculation that a hike in official West German interest rates would
materialize soon.
   The market is losing its faith that U.S. interest rates are
moving higher, something that would give the dollar strength. A
discount rate hike hasn't materialized despite comments from U.S.
officials such as Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan that
inflationary pressures must be resisted.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
1.7595 dollars to buy one pound, more expensive than 1.7465 dollars
late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
1.8215 West German marks, down from 1.8380; 1.5535 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5667; 6.2125 French francs, down from 6.2625; 2.0590
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0725; 1,344.50 Italian lire, down from
1,350.50; 1.1958 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1965.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.33 Japanese yen to a closing 126.29 yen. Later, in
London, it fell further to 126.15 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $391.50 a troy ounce,
compared with $386.30 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, gold rose to close at a bid $391.75 compared with
$386.25 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.99 to close at a bid $389.50.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.04 a troy ounce, compared with
Wednesday's $5.97.
