<HEAD>Gold Mining Group's Profit Falls 18 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Gold Fields PLC, the British mining
conglomerate that is the target of a hostile takeover bid from
Minorco SA, reported Thursday that its half-year profit sank 18
percent from a year ago.
   Consolidated Gold Fields said income for the six months ended
Dec. 31 totaled $178 million, or 83 cents a share, compared with
$217 million, or $1.02 a share, the same period a year ago.
   Sales rose 16.6 percent to $1.3 billion from $1.08 billion.
   The 1987 data included a $147 million gain from the sale of
operations, while the 1988 earnings were affected by a $30 million
charge to cover defense costs against Minorco's hostile bid launched
last September.
   Minorco on Monday renewed its attempt to gain control of
Consolidated Gold Fields by offering a sweetened $5.6 billion
cash-and-stock deal.
   The renewed offer came after the South African-controlled Minorco
was cleared earlier this month by the British Monopolies and Mergers
Commission to bid again. Minorco's original bid lapsed when the
matter was referred to the commission last October.
   The company didn't break out quarterly results. It isn't required
to under British law.
