<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OilFines     02-23 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Fines,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Seeks $1 Million For Corn Oil Adulteration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a 22-month investigation, the state
Thursday fined six cooking oil wholesalers more than $1 million for
allegedly diluting and mislabeling corn oil.
   Richard McGuire, commissioner of the state Agriculture and
Markets Department, said the companies mixed cheaper soy oil with
corn oil and then labeled the products pure corn oil.
   He said the state assessed $1,021,997 in penalties from the
firms, four of which are based in New York and two in New Jersey.
   The case of a seventh firm, Procter &amp; Gamble Co., is being
handled by state Attorney General Robert Abrams, McGuire said.
   A state officials said the oil appeared on grocery store shelves
under brand names and store brands, but he didn't specify which ones.
   State investigators conducted the oil probe by collecting samples
from grocery stores and warehouses. The state also subpoenaed
records and officials of oil manufacturers and distributors, McGuire
said.
   An analysis revealed ``widespread economic adulteration of corn
oil,'' he said.
   ``Soy oil is a fine, healthy food product,'' McGuire said. ``The
incentive for this fraud was purely economic. At the time, soy oil
was considerably less expensive than corn oil.''
   The largest penalty, $669,007, was assessed to CBS Food Products
Corp. of Brooklyn. Manager Bob Green said the company will challenge
the penalty.
   The other firms and penalties were Oasis Trading Co., Hillside,
N.J., $216,740; Supreme Oil Co., Englewood, N.J., $130,260; Garden
Chef Foods Inc., $4,680; and K. Kalustyan Orient Expert Trading
Corp., Yonkers, $1,200.
   The penalties were based on rates of $10 per gallon of corn oil
found to be diluted between 10 percent and 50 percent with soy oil,
and $20 per gallon for those diluted in excess of 50 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Indiana-Takeovers     02-23 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indiana-Takeovers,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indiana Governor Signs Anti-Takeover Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Bayh, signing his first bill into
law, approved a measure Thursday that will give Indiana-based
companies a new defense against hostile takeover attempts.
   Bayh signed Senate Bill 255 during a brief ceremony attended by
legislative leaders.
   The measure backed by many of Indiana's largest companies swept
through the General Assembly in less than one month, winning its
first committee approval on Jan. 31, clearing the Senate on a 47-2
vote and being approved by the House on a 93-5 vote.
   S.B. 255, which is effective retroactively to the end of January,
expands on a section of Indiana's historic 1986 anti-takeover law.
   The measure states that boards of directors, when considering
buyout bids, can weigh factors other than getting the top-dollar
price for shareholders. The new law says that directors can also
weigh the interests of constituents such as employees, suppliers,
customers and the communities in which the companies are located.
   ``I think it's appropriate that the boards of directors take into
account the interests of the people of Indiana and not just the Wall
Street brokers,'' said Bayh, a Democrat who took office Jan. 9.
   Indiana's 1986 anti-takeover law has been copied by other states
since its adoption and a 1987 U.S. Supreme Court decision upholding
the law and a state's attempt to protect its own companies.
   However, Indiana-based companies decided the 1986 statute needed
strengthening after courts in Delaware, which has a similar law,
ruled last year that shareholders' interest in getting the best
return on their investments should be a board's primary standard in
evaluating takeover bids.
   The measure had the support of both Cummins Engine Co. and Arvin
Industries, two Columbus-based corporations. A British company
currently owns almost 10 percent of Cummins stock and an Indonesian
company announced recently it has purchased 5.6 percent of Arvin's
stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
