<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-PanAm     02-23 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Pan Am,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Narrows Loss to $51.7 Million in Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. said Thursday it lost $51.7 million
in the fourth quarter of 1988, a narrowing the airline said was
aided in part by lower labor costs and an improved marketing
strategy.
   The nation's eighth-largest airline reported that losses fell
from $245.5 million in the same 1987 quarter. Fourth-quarter revenue
rose 11.4 percent to $839.9 million from $753.9 million a year
earlier.
   ``While we are not satisfied with our financial results, we do
believe that significant progress has been made in 1988 toward the
stabilization and improvement of our principal subsidiary, Pan
American World Airways,'' Pan Am Chairman Thomas G. Plaskett said in
a statement.
   He said the airline is now realizing benefits of lower labor
costs, had a year-end cash position of around $290 million, has
instituted an effective marketing plan and has enhanced its service
product.
   But Plaskett said the first quarter of 1989 will show a loss
greater than the 1988 first quarter. Pan Am lost $83.3 million in
that period.
   ``The increased loss results from a combination of higher
expenses...as well as lower revenue resulting principally from a
traffic shortfall in our Atlantic division,'' he said.
   Earlier this month, Plaskett said in a speech that Pan Am needs
to merge with another airline to ensure its survival. The statement
sent the company's stock soaring on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Pan Am recently put up for sale its profitable World Services
subsidiary, which markets security, maintenance and other services
to government agencies and other airlines. Financial analysts
estimate the unit's potential sale value at around $200 million.
   For all of 1988, Pan Am narrowed its net loss to $72.7 million
from $265.3 million in 1987. Revenue for 1988 jumped 16.8 percent to
$3.57 billion from $3.05 billion the year before.
   The 1988 results include a gain of $89.1 million from the sale of
options on 16 Airbus A320s to Braniff Inc.
</TEXT>
