<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-ChannelOne Adv26   02-23 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Channel One, Adv 26,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Whittle Nears Test Launch of High School News Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Personal File-Whittle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A half-dozen schools are each getting $50,000 in
television equipment in exchange for their participation in Whittle
Communications LP's test next month of Channel One, a commercial
news program for teen-agers.
   The project represents the Knoxville, Tenn.-based media company's
first venture in satellite-delivered television and it has raised
concerns among some educators about the propriety of allowing paid
advertising into classrooms.
   But if the test proves successful, Whittle chairman Christopher
Whittle hopes to take the project into 8,000 or more schools in the
fall of 1990 at a cost in hardware alone of more than $100 million.
   He said the project was designed to enable schools to obtain a
sophisticated television system they may not otherwise be able to
afford while giving students a useful embellishment to their daily
education.
   Whittle said he hopes to sign advertisers to long-term
commitments to the news program in exchange for getting product
exclusivity on the network and the ability to reach a teenage
audience that has often proven elusive.
   The program will be produced each weekday in Los Angeles and
beamed via satellite to the participating schools in time for the
principal to review it. Schools are expected to run the program once
each schoolday although school officials have the right not to air
it if they find something objectionable.
   Whittle plans to assemble a news staff of about 100 if the
project is taken national, and he has already sent a crew to the
Soviet Union to do a series on a day in the life of a Soviet
teen-ager.
   A pilot of the 12-minute program, which includes four 30-second
commercial spots, ran like this:
   _News headlines in which an announcer reads several brief stories
accompanied by purchased film footage to illustrate it.
   _A focus piece produced by the Channel One staff on someone
interesting to teens, such as an interview with the daughter of an
American hostage in Lebanon.
   _Following a one-minute commercial break, another Channel
One-produced segment of a weekly five-part series on topics such as
environmental pollution.
   _A pop quiz poses a question and, following another commercial
break, provides the answer.
   _A Channel One-produced feature story which in the pilot mixes a
music video with historical scenes from the life of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr.
   The six schools participating in the test starting March 6 are
Eisenhower Middle School in Kansas City; Mumford High School in
Detroit; Central High School in Knoxville; Billerica Memorial High
School in Billerica, Mass.; Withrow High School in Cincinnati; and
Gahr High School in Cerritos, Calif.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Feb. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
