<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-Soviet-Grain     02-23 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet-Grain,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy 400,000 Metric Tons of U.S. Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   The wheat was part of a Jan. 25 authorization of more than 2
million tons under the Export Enhancement Program, or EEP, said
Christopher E. Goldthwait, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service.
   He said the wheat is for shipment for March. Counting some left
over from a previous EEP arrangement and the Jan. 25 authorization,
the Soviets have more than 1.01 million tons still available under
the program.
   With the latest sale, the Soviet Union has bought about 3 million
tons of wheat for delivery in the sixth year of a long-term supply
agreement, which was extended last fall to run through Dec. 31, 1990.
   A metric tons is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. The 400,000 tons are equal to about 14.7 million bushels
worth around $60 million at recent U.S. farm prices of $4.08 per
bushel.
   The EEP arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced
prices in order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then
collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as
bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sales for delivery in the sixth year of the agreement also
included about 10.2 million tons of corn, along with 450,000 tons of
soybeans, 1.4 million tons of soybean meal, and 507,400 tons of
grain sorghums.
   Goldthwait said 300,000 tons of wheat were sold by Louis Dreyfus
Corp. and 100,000 tons by Cargill Inc.
   The companies will get subsidies of $22.06 per ton, or about 60
cents per bushel, under the EEP arrangement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Venezuela-Debt     02-23 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Debt,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuela Suspends Repayment of Private Sector's Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela has suspended capital
payments on about $5 billion in private-sector debt owed to creditor
banks, mainly in the United States, according to a published report
Thursday.
   The decision, which affects $472 million in principal due this
year, was called ``unprecedented'' by the independent newspaper El
Nacional.
   There was no immediate official confirmation of the decision and
the newspaper did not provide a source for the information.
   Bankers and businessmen had mixed reactions to the report but
said it did not come as a surprise.
   Private-sector debt was being paid off in an eight-year period
dating from 1986, at preferential rates granted by the Venezuelan
government, one businessman said.
   ``I don't think anyone expected the debt to be recognized at
preferential rates over the whole eight-year period,'' said the
businessman, owner of an electric parts plant, who did not want his
name used.
   ``But it will hurt some people who have not paid off the debt in
full,'' he added.
   The decision would add to the suspension in January of capital
repayments totaling more than $20.4 billion owed by the public
sector to foreign banks.
   Venezuela's total foreign debt of $33 billion is Latin America's
fourth largest after Brazil, Mexico and Argentina. Venezuela
recently began talks with its creditors to define new repayment
terms.
   Suspension of principal payments on both the private and public
sectors' foreign debts affects a total of $2 billion due this year,
the newspaper reported.
   A representative for an international bank said the decision
would ``create real problems'' for international bankers.
   ``The initial decision was a signed and sealed agreement. We'll
have to start all over now,'' said the banker, who asked not to be
named.
   He said he expected a new refinancing of the private sector debt
to include some sort of subsidy, otherwise many companies would be
forced into bankruptcy.
   As of January 1987, the private sector's debt totaled $4.97
billion. Capital payments for 1989 represented 9.5 percent of that
total, the newspaper said.
   Venezuela's private-sector foreign debt had been paid off
regularly over the past few years and the suspension ordered by the
Social Democratic government implies a ``radical change'' in the
nation's strategy with its creditors, according to El Nacional.
   ``Besides suspending amortization on the private sector's debt,
the government will demand this debt be granted the same treatment
to be accorded for the public sector's debt,'' the report said.
   That would represent a repayment period of 20 years, up from
eight begining in 1987, six to seven years of grace, and
rescheduling of interest payments.
   A greater problem, according to many business leaders, is what to
do about some $6.8 billion in letters of credit owed to financial
institutions.
   ``The government says the IMF is only willing to grant fresh
money if the letters of credit are paid off at free market rates.
But we see it as a violation of the rules we were operating under.
We never asked for those rules,'' said a business representative.
   The letters of credit were granted to businesses at preferential
rates, but negotiations between Venezuela and the International
Monetary Fund are trying to determine which of those letters of
credit must be paid back at free market rates, as part of the IMF's
austerity program.
   A team of Venezuelan negotiators are scheduled to travel to the
United States on Sunday, including central bank president Pedro
Tinoco, planning minister Miguel Rodriguez, and finance minister
Eglee Iturbe, to sign a letter of intent with the IMF for fresh
loans, said press accounts.
   Contingent on the signing with the IMF will be additional funds
forthcoming from the central bank of Spain and the U.S. Federal
Reserve worth some $1.1 billion to prop up Venezuela's reserves,
depleted to just 1.5 billion dollars in operative money, said El
Nacional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     02-23 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $3.25 Billion in Latest Week to Another Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 445 money market mutual
funds rose $3.25 billion in the latest week to hit a new all-time
high of $292.39 billion, the Investment Company Institute said
Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday shattered the
previous record of $289.14 billion set a week earlier from a $1.58
billion increase, the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said.
   The biggest weekly rise in the funds' assets _ $9.64 billion in
the week ended Oct. 21, 1987 _ came during the stock market collapse
as investors sought safe havens for their money.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 224 general purpose funds rose $496.5 million to $92.8
billion, assets of 93 broker-dealer funds increased $1.88 billion to
$125.20 billion, and assets of 138 institutional funds rose $879.7
million to $74.39 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.52 percent from 8.44 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 8.43 percent from 8.39 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 31
days, unchanged from the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts rose to 6.36 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.37 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was to 5.14 percent, unchanged.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.57
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.48 the
previous week. Yields were 8.80 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.74
percent; 8.85 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.78 percent; and 8.90
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.86 percent.
