<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Boeing-Wiring     02-23 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-Wiring,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Wiring Problems Reported As Boeing Announces Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wiring problems in two more jetliners have been
reported by a Boeing Co. customer, and the plane manufacturer says
it is studying possible changes in its assembly line to address the
matter.
   Air Canada discovered the latest wiring mixups on two of its
Boeing 767 passenger jets. Boeing passed the reports on to the
Federal Aviation Administration last week.
   Boeing confirmed on Wednesday that the repeated wiring mishaps
have prompted the company to start an engineering study in an effort
to prevent crossed wires and pipes in all Boeing models.
   ``There would be changes in the plugs and sockets so that, for
example, an individual wire can only go into a particular socket,''
Boeing spokesman Craig Martin said.
   Martin said the study to modify plugs and sockets was also in
response, in part, to the fire-suppression wiring problems detected
on Boeing 757s, as well as problems noted on other Boeing aircraft.
   He said company executives were supervising studies by three
engineering teams, but it was not known when changes might be made
or what the costs might be.
   Boeing hopes to find an ``across-the-board solution'' that will
make assembly of the units consistent and foolproof ``as much as
possible,'' Martin said.
   Some Boeing aircraft fire safety systems are color-coded or keyed
to prevent wrong hookups, but others have identical fittings for
different parts of the systems, he said.
   The Air Canada reports followed a flap between Boeing and the FAA
over apparent delays in reporting similar wiring problems in at
least seven other Boeing aircraft since last August.
   Some of the mishaps were not reported by Boeing until last month.
   Boeing officials called the delays a ``misunderstanding'' but
changed the company's reporting procedures this week to ensure
``timely reporting,'' said Philip Condit, Boeing's executive vice
president.
</TEXT>
