<FIRST>u f AM-Allegheny-DLJ     02-23 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny-DLJ,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankrupt Appliance Maker Agrees To Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc., the financially
troubled small appliance maker, agreed Thursday to be acquired and
kept intact for more than $800 million by a New York securities firm
it snubbed last month.
   Investors led by Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp.
are ready to pay $60 million for a 62 percent stake in the
Pittsburgh company currently reorganizing under federal bankruptcy
laws.
   The deal also would provide $747 million, including $541 million
in cash and $184 million in securities, to settle debts.
   The plan, subject to the approval of a bankruptcy court judge and
creditors, replaces management's plan to sell the valued
Oster-Sunbeam appliances division and have Allegheny International
stand alone.
   Banks whose claims are secured by company assets and other
institutions with unsecured debt would be paid the full value of
their claims. Certain senior unsecured debt would be paid at a rate
of 95 cents on the dollar.
   The takeover would be financed with Allegheny International's
cash, bank loans, bonds and other securities, along with DLJ's
investment. Preferred and common shareholders would be left with 38
percent of the company.
   ``The proposed new merger with DLJ provides us with the most
viable route for emergence from Chapter 11 protection,'' said
Allegheny International Chairman Oliver S. Travers. ``It enables us
to keep our customer products business intact, which always had been
our hope.''
   Management proposed the asset sale after accusing DLJ of cutting
a backroom deal with a rival bidder, the New York merchant bank firm
Joseph, Littlejohn &amp; Levy. The bankers were to purchase Allegheny
International's gas grill and lawn furniture businesses.
   Allegheny International in January withdrew its approval of the
first DLJ takeover plan.
</TEXT>
