<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1736EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CFTCProbe     02-23 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CFTC Probe,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Official Says Sanctions Don't Necessarily Indicate Degree of
Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Accounting Office official said
Thursday that the number of disciplinary actions taken against
commodities traders in recent years does not necessarily indicate
the degree of abuse at the nation's biggest futures markets.
   Richard Fogel, assistant comptroller general at the GAO, which is
Congress' auditing arm, also said results of an ongoing FBI
investigation of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and Chicago Board
of Trade may give a better idea of possible abuses in the
commodities pits.
   The federal government has subpoenaed more than 100 traders and
brokers in connection with a sweeping undercover investigation of
trading abuses alleged to have defrauded exchange customers of
millions of dollars.
   The GAO stated the number of contracts traded at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange grew from 40 million in 1984 to 80 million in
1988, and at the Chicago Board of Trade from 80 million to 140
million during the same period.
   The number of traders sanctioned for violations on the floor of
the Merc rose from 13 in 1984 to 105 in 1988, while sanctions at the
Board of Trade went from a low of eight in 1985 to a high of 32 in
1986. In 1988, the Board of Trade sanctioned 13 floor participants.
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., called the number of sanctions taken
against traders ``pitiful'' given the volume of trading.
   Fogel said the numbers could reflect an oversight system that is
working well or one that needs improvement because it is not
detecting abuses or punishing offenders severely enough.
   Fogel's testimony came at the first Senate oversight hearing this
year on the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which oversees the
commodities markets and is up for congressional reauthorization this
year.
   The CFTC's policing of commodities markets has come under fire
from a number of critics since the federal probe was disclosed
earlier this year.
   Separately, Wendy Lee Gramm, chairwoman of the CFTC, said the
agency has not yet responded to a request that it delay approving
new types of futures contracts until completion of the FBI probe and
a review of the commodities markets by the House Agriculture
Committee.
   Gramm made her comments in response to questions from reporters
following a speech in New York. Earlier this week, members of the
Agriculture Committee asked the agency to hold off considering
proposals it has pending.
   At the hearing, Fogel said Mercantile Exchange fines for trade
practice abuses totaled $3.6 million from 1984 to 1988. For the same
period, comparable Board of Trade fines were $811,000.
   The number of members expelled on both exchanges averaged about
two a year, Fogel said. He said exchange officials consider
permanent expulsion or lengthy suspensions as more severe than fines
because they deprive members of their livelihood.
   Fogel said CFTC officials told the GAO they could not comment on
their involvement in identifying or investigating alleged abuses
until after any indictments stemming from the FBI probe are issued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0288 </DOCNO>
