<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-23 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Closes Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped lower Thursday as pessimism
about the U.S. budget and trade deficits weighed on the foreign
exchange markets.
   Gold prices moved higher. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a late bid of $390.70 for a troy ounce of gold, up from
$386.40 late Wednesday.
   Analysts said the dollar declined as traders became convinced the
Bush administration had no firm plan to deal with the budget and
trade gaps.
   Interest rates have continued to edge higher, which should
support the dollar, ``but we still have twin deficits and no
resolution on that,'' said Dan Holland, an analyst at Discount Corp.
   Holland said traders also were concerned that the Federal Reserve
might be cautious in raising interest rates so as not to burden the
struggling savings and loan industry.
   Traders see Washington as placing a relatively low priority on
supporting the dollar, said Holland, who predicted the U.S. currency
could return to the levels where it traded before the November
election.
   Overseas dealers said the dollar was driven lower by skepticism
that U.S. interest rates will rise, and by the West German mark's
strength. The mark, in turn, was helped by continuing speculation
that a hike in official West German interest rates would materialize
soon.
   After the close of trading in New York, two major banks announced
they were raising their prime lending rate half a percentage point
to 11.5 percent, the second increase in two weeks. However, prime
rate hikes tend to follow, and not portend, increases in other
interest rates.
   The dollar began its day in Tokyo, falling 0.33 Japanese yen to a
closing 126.29 yen. Later, in London, it fell further to 126.15 yen,
and in New York, it slipped to 126.175 yen from late Wednesday's
126.525.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7595 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7465 late
Wednesday. In later New York trading, the pound rose to $1.7605 from
late Wedneday's $1.7470.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.82175 West German marks, down from
1.83425; 1.5505 Swiss francs, down from 1.56575; 6.2160 French
francs, down from 6.2555; 1,342.50 Italian lire, down from 1,349.75;
and 1.19485 Canadian dollars, down from 1.19985.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.8215 West German marks, down from 1.8380; 1.5535
Swiss francs, down from 1.5667; 6.2125 French francs, down from
6.2625; 2.0590 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0725; 1,344.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,350.50; 1.1958 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1965.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold closed at $391 a troy
ounce, up from $386.90 late Wednesday.
   Gold rose earlier in London to a late bid price of $391.50 a troy
ounce, compared with $386.30 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich, gold
rose to close at a bid $391.75, compared with $386.25 bid late
Wednesday.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $1.99 to close at a bid $389.50.
   Silver bullion prices were mixed. On the Commodity Exchange,
silver closed at $5.931, down slightly from late Wednesday's $5.935.
In London, the metal traded at a late bid price of $6.04 a troy
ounce, compared with Wednesday's $5.97.
</TEXT>
