<FIRST>u f AM-Chrysler-Plant 2ndLd-Writethru f0181 02-23 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler-Plant, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0181,f0202,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planned Chrysler Plant To Make New Sport-Utility Vehicle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to add time element; INSERTS graf after 3rd graf pvs
with Toledo plans; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, ``The ZJ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said Thursday it plans to replace
an aging Detroit assembly plant with a new $1 billion factory that
will make a new sport-utility vehicle beginning in 1992, betting
that demand for such vehicles will continue growing into the next
decade.
   The vehicle, code-named the ``ZJ,'' will be available in Jeep and
Dodge dealers and will be the first sport-utility vehicle carrying
the Dodge nameplate.
   Details about the ZJ _ which will be available in two models _
will not be given until production begins in January 1992. But
Chrysler spokesman Doug Nicoll said it would be larger than the Jeep
Cherokee now being made at a Toledo, Ohio plant.
   Chrysler said it will continue manufacturing Jeep Cherokees in
Toledo after 1992, when its current five-year contract with the
United Auto Workers union expires.
   ``The `ZJ' is basically a vehicle that is for another segment of
the market,'' Nicoll said. ``It is not a replacement for the
Cherokee. It is targeted at an upscale market.''
   The current base price for a two-wheel-drive Jeep Cherokee is
about $12,374. Four-wheel-drive and options can push the cost much
higher.
   The ZJ is the second new sport-utility vehicle for the 1990s that
Chrysler has announced this month.
   Chairman Lee Iacocca said Feb. 2 that Chrysler and the French
automaker Renault would collaborate on a ``mini-sport-utility
vehicle'' code-named the ``JJ.'' It will be assembled at one factory
in the United States and another either in Spain or Portugal
beginning in mid-1992.
   The base price for the JJ would be less than $10,000, Iacocca
said.
   The ZJ will be the only vehicle produced at Chrysler's new
Jefferson North plant, which will replace the company's aging
Jefferson Avenue assembly plant. Full production is expected to be
about 200,000 vehicles a year.
   Sales of utility vehicles of all sizes, from compacts like the
Suzuki Samurai to large ones like the Ford Bronco, have risen from
6.3 percent of the truck market in 1980 to 16.3 percent last year.
   It was too early to tell how many of the new vehicles would be
allocated to Dodge and how many would go to Jeep, Nicoll said. Final
names for the vehicles won't be determined for two to three years,
he said.
   The Jefferson Avenue plant, which has been producing cars since
1925, now makes the Dodge Omni and Plymouth Horizon cars. Nicoll
said the company was unsure whether the Onmi or Horizon nameplates
would continue after the plant is shut down.
   Construction of the Jefferson North plant on Detroit's east side
is to begin in April, Nicoll said.
   Chrysler indicated it was optimistic that problems regarding
chemical deposits on the plant site and acquisition of the land by
the city of Detroit would be cleared up by the time construction is
to start.
   Any delays in land acquisition or environmental cleanup in turn
could delay the startup, and significant delays could jeopardize the
project, Nicoll said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
