<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-23 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures turned in a mixed performance
Thursday with crude prices nearly flat in lackluster trading on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The April contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, closed the day down 1 cent at $17.83 a
barrel. Contracts for later delivery were unchanged to 4 cents lower.
   Among refined products, March heating oil rose 0.44 cent to 50.59
cents a gallon after jumping 1.23 cents on Wednesday in response to
an industry report showing an unexpected decline in inventories.
   Unleaded gasoline for March settled at 49.74 cents a gallon, up
0.67 cent. Analysts said there was no fresh news to move the market
although beginning investor concern about a seasonal decline in
demand for crude oil might have influenced prices somewhat.
   Activity in the gasoline pits reflected some concern about the
possibility of higher retail gasoline prices this summer. Analysts
said buyers were trying to lock in lower prices for summer
deliveries. Gasoline prices scheduled for delivery between June and
November were up 1.03 cents to 1.30 cents a gallon.
   The concern stems from the possibility that some Northeastern
states will impose new regulations requiring motorists to use higher
octane gasoline. The states are awaiting Environmental Protection
Agency approval.
   Refining capacity already is tight and the new gasoline would
require refiners to use more oil to produce a smaller amount of
motor fuel.
</TEXT>
