<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   02-23 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mid-February Sales Rise 1.7 Percent on Strong Truck Performance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mid-February sales of U.S.-based companies' cars
and light trucks rose 1.7 percent from year-earlier levels as the
effects of sales incentives available in early 1988 began to wear
off, the automakers said Thursday.
   The eight automakers said they sold cars and light trucks at an
average daily rate of 36,769 during the Feb. 11-20 period this year,
compared with a daily rate of 35,158 during the same time last year.
   There were eight selling days during the period this year and
nine last year, so percentage changes in sales are based on a daily
selling rate rather than on total sales.
   The overall sales rate during the period was bolstered by a 5.4
percent increase in truck sales, which offset a 0.3 percent decline
in car sales.
   Sales during the first six weeks of last year were heavily
influenced by buyer incentives offered by the automakers. Incentives
including cash rebates and low financing deals were offered this
year for a narrower range of cars and trucks.
   For the year to date, car and truck sales by domestic producers
fell 3.2 percent to an average daily rate of 32,334, compared with
33,412 last year. There were 42 selling days between Jan. 1 and Feb.
20 this year, one fewer than during the same time last year.
   The daily sales rate for cars was down 6.3 percent during the
period, while truck sales were up 1.5 percent.
   Chrysler Corp. mid-February car sales fell 18.5 percent from the
same period last year. The nation's No. 3 automaker said its average
daily sales rate for cars fell to 2,960 during mid-February from
3,630 a year earlier.
   For the year to date, Chrysler's car sales were down 15.1 percent
from a year earlier.
   Chrysler's truck sales were up 7.1 percent during the
mid-February period, to a daily rate of 3,105 from 2,899 last year.
   Joseph Phillippi, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton in New
York, agreed with Chrysler executives who recently predicted that a
short supply of cars due to model changeover might depress sales
numbers during early 1989.
   General Motors Corp. car sales fell 1.2 percent during
mid-February, dropping to a daily rate of 11,714 this year from
11,852 during the period last year. For the year to date, GM's car
sales are down 11.8 percent.
   GM truck sales were up 3.3 percent during the mid-February
period, rising to a daily rate of 5,169 from 5,006 a year earlier.
   Ford Motor Co. said its car sales rose 1.6 percent in
mid-February this year over last year, going to a daily rate of
6,833 from 6,727 last year. Ford's car sales are running 0.4 percent
ahead of car sales to date last year, rising to a daily average of
6,441 from 6,415.
   Ford said it sold an average of 4,798 trucks a day during the
period this year, up 4.2 percent from 4,604 last year.
</TEXT>
