<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     02-23 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three key measures of the nation's money
supply fell in the week ended Feb. 13, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell to a
seasonally adjusted $784.0 million from $787.2 million the previous
week, the Fed said.
   The broader measure known as M2 fell to a seasonally adjusted
$3,066.9 billion from $3,067.5 billion.
   An even broader measure, M3, decreased to a seasonally adjusted
$3,921.6 billion from $3,923.1 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   In congressional testimony on Tuesday, Fed Chairman Alan
Greenspan reaffirmed a target for 1989 of 3 percent to 7 percent
growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent growth in M3. The Fed
set the targets on a provisional basis last year. The central bank
has not set a target for M1 growth since early 1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M1 averaged $787.8 million, a 1.8
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13
weeks. M2 averaged $3,068.7 billion, up 3.9 percent, while M3 rose
5.1 percent to an average of $3,917.7 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks fell $75 million,
compared with a gain of $2.1 billion a week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window averaged $534 million, up from
$197 million.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $287.1 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, down from
$287.4 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 1813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GESettlements     02-23 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GE Settlements,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Electric Settles Five Lawsuits For $3.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. has agreed to pay the
government $3.5 million to settle five civil lawsuits for claims
including defense contract fraud, lawyers said Thursday.
   Four of the suits were filed under the False Claims Act of 1863,
which allows citizens to sue a defense contractor to try and recover
money for the federal government.
   James Helmer Jr., a lawyer for the plaintiffs, said the
government has agreed to give the four ``whistleblower'' plaintiffs
$770,000, or 22 percent, of the $3.5 million settlement.
   ``This is the largest amount of money ever recovered by the
United States in one of these actions,'' Helmer said. ``This was a
tremendous recovery for the United States' taxpayers.''
   The lawsuits, filed around the country, were consolidated in
Cincinnati for handling by U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin.
   John M. Gravitt, a former machinists' foreman at GE's suburban
Evendale jet engine-producing plant, alleged in a 1984 suit that GE
altered about 9,000 daily labor vouchers for defense contract work
done for the government.
   Stamford, Conn.-based GE denied the allegations and proposed a
$234,000 settlement federal prosecutors recommended in 1985. But the
judge rejected the settlement as inadequate. The case was to go to
trial Monday.
   GE spokesman Richard Kennedy said: ``There never was any
deliberate attempt by GE to defraud the government.''
   The company had denied the claims in the lawsuits, which charged
GE with various wrongdoings and falsifications of records. One suit
charged that a GE supplier allegedly paid bribes to a GE buyer.
   In the fifth case, which was not filed under the False Claims
Act, a California company alleged that GE refused its business
because its owner was Hispanic. GE denied the claim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
