<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;L-Texas     02-23 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L-Texas,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gramm Says FDIC To Dispose of Fail Thrift Assets In `Orderly Fashion'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. plans to
sell repossessed real estate from failed savings and loans in Texas
``at a good price'' after Congress approves a multibillion dollar
bailout package, Sen. Phil Gramm said Thursday.
   Gramm said FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman plans to establish
``an orderly process'' for disposing of billions of dollars in
assets from failed savings and loans in Texas so the state's
economic recovery is not disrupted.
   Those assets _ including office buildings, hotels, motels,
apartments, single family homes and shopping centers _ will not be
sold at ``firesale prices,'' the Texas Republican said after meeting
with Seidman.
   Seidman plans to announce the effort in Texas after Congress
passes President Bush's proposal to bail out the savings and loan
industry.
   Gramm said dumping the assets on the Texas market at rock bottom
prices would send real estate prices in the state plummeting.
   Flooding the market would have a ``cataclysmic impact on banks
and savings and loans that are not insolvent, stop all
construction'' and set the state's recovery back three or four years.
   Sen. Timothy Worth, D-Colo., said $7.5 billion in assets from
failed thrifts are currently being held by the Federal Savings and
Loan Insurance Corp. A large part of that portfolio is held in Texas.
   Under Bush's proposed plan to restructure the thrift regulatory
system, the FDIC would have responsibility for insuring both
commercial banks and savings and loans. FSLIC would be merged into
the FDIC, giving the FDIC responsiblity for the repossessed assets.
</TEXT>
