<FIRST>r f AM-FNNProposals     02-23 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FNN Proposals,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>FNN Chairman Reaffirms Company Has Been Considering Venture Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial News Network Inc. has been considering
several preliminary proposals for a possible joint venture or
business combination, but it may take some time to evaluate them,
FNN's chairman said Thursday.
   Chairman Earl Brian made the statement in a memo to FNN employees
that he said was issued after some of them asked about a report in
Hollywood Reporter.
   The publication on Wednesday quoted a cable industry source it
did not identify as saying ``the ownership of Financial News Network
could change hands within days.''
   FNN operates a cable television service that offers business and
sports programs. The company has been a periodic subject of takeover
speculation.
   Brian has previously acknowledged that FNN has been discussing
joint programming ventures with a number of major broadcast
companies.
   ``...it is correct that over the last several months we have
received, and have been considering, several preliminary proposals
for possible joint venture or business combination transactions
involving FNN,'' Brian wrote.
   ``We have not agreed to any proposal at this time and there is no
assurance that we will reach an acceptable agreement. We will
continue to evaluate such strategic alternatives. The evaluation
process may take some time,'' he said.
   FNN's biggest shareholder is Infotechnology Inc., a New
York-based media concern which also has an interest in a company
that manages United Press International.
   Brian, who is also chairman of Infotech, said last month he had
no plans to sell Infotech's 43 percent stake in FNN.
   In the first half of its fiscal year, FNN earned $1.2 million, or
7 cents a share, on revenue of $28.7 million for the six months
ended Dec. 31.
   In national over-the-counter trading, FNN was unchanged Wednesday
at $8.75 a share.
 
</TEXT>
