<FIRST>r f AM-HotDogFight     02-23 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hot Dog Fight,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oscar Mayer Wishes Bryan Would Stop Claiming To Be Number One, Files
Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hog dog maker Oscar Mayer Foods Corp. filed suit
Thursday against rival Bryan Foods Inc., claiming the food processor
has been running television commercials in the South that are full
of baloney.
   Bryan, a Mississippi-based subsidiary of Sara Lee Corp.,
advertises its products as the best-selling ``throughout the
South,'' and its commercials tout the Southern-exclusivity of Bryan
hot dogs, bacon and bologna.
   Oscar Mayer, a Madison, Wis.-based subsidiary of Philip Morris
Cos. Inc., asked the U.S. District Court here to force Sara Lee to
pull the ads. The suit also seeks unspecified monetary damages,
including trebled punitive damages.
   The suit contends Bryan's claims of taste superiority are based
on invalid research and that Oscar Mayer products, not Bryan's, are
the region's top sellers.
   ``Continuously since 1984, ... Oscar Mayer hot dogs, bologna and
bacon each have been the top-selling brands in the southern United
States or `the South,''' the lawsuit says. ``Continuously since
1984, ... Oscar Mayer hot dogs, bologna and bacon have had a far
greater market share in the South than Bryan's respective products.''
   Sara Lee spokeswoman Anne McCarthy said the Chicago-based company
had not seen the lawsuit and does not comment on pending litigation.
   Oscar Mayer marketing Vice President Bryan Stockton said the
company complained to the Better Business Bureau and the National
Advertising Review Board, but ``Sara Lee has continued to produce
television commercials which inaccurately portray the competitive
situation between Oscar Mayer and Bryan Foods in the southern part
of the U.S.''
   Oscar Mayer said it notified Bryan of its objections in 1984. The
company said the BBB's National Advertising Division agreed in 1985
that Bryan ``could not support a claim to market leadership
throughout the South.''
   The suit claims Bryan agreed to change its advertising to clarify
the context of its ``best-selling'' claims, but failed to honor the
promise.
</TEXT>
