<FIRST>u f AM-USAir-McDonnell     02-23 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir-McDonnell,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Agrees to Buy Up To 40 Planes from McDonnell Douglas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Group Inc. said Thursday it has agreed to
buy as many as 40 MD-82 aircraft from manufacturer McDonnell Douglas
Corp.
   USAir said it has signed a letter of intent to place firm orders
for 20 of the aircraft and take options on 20 more. The two
companies are currently negotiating a definitive contract, USAir
said in a brief statement.
   The first two of the new planes would be delivered in September
1992 and the remainder of the firm orders and options, if taken,
would be delivered to USAir at the rate of one per month starting in
January 1993.
   The planes will carry about 140 passengers.
   Washington-based USAir, the nation's ninth-largest airline, said
it is a long-time operator of McDonnell Douglas aircraft.
   The announcement marks the second victory this month for St.
Louis-based McDonnell Douglas in its competition with rival aircraft
makers Boeing Co. and the Airbus Industrie consortium of Europe.
   American Airlines said Feb. 7 it had signed an agreement with
McDonnell Douglas to acquire at least eight new long-range MD-11
jetliners with options to buy another 42. The airline also took
options on 100 MD-80s, a smaller plane designed to replace the
Boeing 727.
   Industry experts estimate the American deal could total about $7
billion, making it potentially one of the biggest aircraft orders in
history.
</TEXT>
