<FIRST>u f AM-CapitalGains 1stLd-Writethru f0291 02-23 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0291,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with Rostenkowski comment, INSERTS 1 graf after 5th
graf previous, `Bentsen has'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional tax analysts estimated Thursday
that the capital-gains tax reduction proposed by President Bush as a
revenue-raiser would actually reduce tax collections by $24.2
billion over the next six years.
   The Bush administration calculates the president's proposal would
increase revenues by $9.3 billion during the 1989-94 period.
   ``Who's right?'' Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the
Senate Finance Committee, asked in releasing the report from the
staff of the Joint Committee on Taxation. ``That's the first thing
we'll have to determine when the Finance Committee takes this matter
up.''
   Just two years ago, the Treasury Department estimated a
capital-gains cut would lose $21.8 billion over five years. ``It may
be significant that Joint Tax is far closer to what Treasury was
saying two years ago than what Treasury itself is saying today,''
Bentsen said.
   Bentsen has indicated he could live with a reduction in the
capital-gains rate if the upper-income taxpayers who would benefit
most were made to pay elsewhere for the cut. But his House
counterpart, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the Ways and
Means Committee, has vowed all-out opposition to a reduction.
   ``This assault on tax reform would be a bad idea no matter what
its deficit impact,'' Rostenkowski said in a statement Thursday.
``Now that we know of its alarming impact on the deficit, I urge the
president to reexamine the proposal,'' he said.
   Rostenkowski's committee lined up behind the chairman Thursday.
The panel by voice voice stated its opposition to any significant
change in the 1986 law. Ending the special benefit for capital gains
was a major portion of the 1986 law.
   In a message to Congress on Feb. 9, Bush said, ``I propose that
we cut the maximum tax rate on capital gains to increase long-term
investment. History is clear: this will increase revenues, help
savings and create new jobs.''
   Capital gains, which are profits from the sale of stocks, real
estate and other property, had enjoyed preferential tax treatment
unil passage of the 1986 tax overhaul. Now, capital gains are taxed
just as other income, such as wages and interest, at rates of 15
percent, 28 percent or 33 percent, depending on total income.
   Under Bush's proposal, the maximum capital-gains rate would be
cut to 15 percent for most productive assets; when fully effective
in 1995, the change would apply only to assets held longer than 36
months. A couple with adjusted gross income under $20,000 (or a
single person under $10,000) would pay no tax on such gains,
including the sale of a principal home.
   Bush's tax analysts in the Treasury Department reason that
reducing the tax on capital gains will encourage taxpayers to sell
large quantities of long-term investments, thus boosting the amount
of income subject to taxation. In the long run, they say, the lower
rate will induce greater saving.
   Despite Rostenkowski's opposition, there is considerable support
in both parties in Congress for restoring a preferential tax rate
for capital gains.
   Most of the opposition is based on the fact that almost all the
benefit from the change would go to the richest Americans and that
it would mark the first step toward undoing the big 1986 tax
overhaul.
   According to figures from the Internal Revenue Service, more than
34 percent of the $135 billion of capital gains that were reported
on returns filed in 1987 were recorded by 34,818 taxpayers whose
incomes were over $1 million apiece. Seventy percent of the gain
went to 1.5 million people with incomes over $100,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
