<FIRST>r f AM-GM-Fairfield     02-23 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM-Fairfield,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Gives Up Trying To Sell Closed Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. says it has given up
trying to sell its closed Fairfield auto parts stamping plant as an
ongoing business and instead will sell the property.
   GM spokeswoman Sharon Hines said Thursday that the automaker
tried but failed to conclude deals with two companies to sell the
factory so that it could continue as a stamping plant. No other
prospective buyers have stepped forward, she said.
   The 1.5 million-square-foot plant employed up to 2,500 workers in
this southwestern Ohio community before it closed six months ago as
part of a consolidation of GM facilities.
   GM plans to transfer some of the Fairfield plant's equipment to
other plants and then sell the property, she said.
   Darrell Bowling, co-director of a GM-United Auto Workers center
formed to help former GM Fairfield workers find new jobs, said GM's
decision was unfair to the 500 to 600 former employees who stayed in
the Fairfield area hoping to get a job when the plant reopened under
new ownership.
   ``There's still some hope that something positive will happen,''
Bowling said. ``But I think GM had this decision in mind a long time
ago. They're just playing games with our people.''
   Ms. Hines said GM plans to work with city officials to find an
alternative use for the plant.
   ``Our effort to find a buyer was probably more extensive than any
we've undertaken at other facilities,'' she said. ``Two years is a
lot of time, but we've had no other offers.''
</TEXT>
