<FIRST>r f AM-Pennwalt-Centaur     02-23 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pennwalt-Centaur,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennwalt Sells Division In Anti-Takeover Strategy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. said Thursday it will sell its
Wallace &amp; Tiernan equipment division for more than $40 million as
part of a strategy to avoid a hostile takeover by Centaur Partners.
   The sale was announced two days after Pennwalt rejected Centaur's
$110-a-share offer and announced it would explore other options.
   Wallace &amp; Tiernan, based in Belleville, N.J., is being sold to a
management-led investor group, W&amp;T Acquisition Corp., for about $44
million, Pennwalt spokeswoman Sue Kinnard said.
   Pennwalt Chairman Edwin E. Tuttle said the sale completes a
restructuring program announced last June in which the chemical
company has sold off its pharmaceutical division and most equipment
divisions.
   Pennwalt used part of the money from the sales to buy back stock.
But before the year ended, Centaur bid $100 a share for each of the
6.98 million Pennwalt common shares it doesn't own. Centaur now owns
about 1 million, or 13 percent, of the total shares outstanding.
   Pennwalt refused the initial offer, setting up a bitter battle
for control of the company.
   In rejecting Centaur's offer of $110 Tuesday, Pennwalt authorized
investment banker Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. and company management to look
for alternatives.
   The company declined to comment on how Wallace &amp; Tiernan's sale
may fit into its plans.
   Centaur had no comment on Thursday's sale. The investment group
has pledged to pursue the acquisition.
   Pennwalt closed at $118.87{, up 62.5 cents, in New York Stock
Exchange trading Thursday. Last June, when Centaur first announced
its takeover bid, the stock was trading at about $70.
</TEXT>
