<FIRST>u f BC-IBM-Settlement 1stLd-Writethru   02-23 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-IBM-Settlement, 1st Ld-Writethru,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Settles $100 Million Patent Infringement Suit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, In a..., to CORRECT that IBM counterclaim was
dismissed before settlement; SUBS last graf to note that Berkeley lawyer
returned call.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. confirmed
Thursday it has agreed to settle a $100 million lawsuit charging
that its personal computers violated a basic patent on word
processing held by a small Rockville-based company.
   The settlement calls for IBM to acquire the patent held by the
company, Berkeley Limited Partnership, IBM spokeswoman Cynthia
Stevens said. She declined to comment on how much if anything IBM
was paying Berkeley.
   Max Stul Oppenheimer, a Baltimore lawyer not involved in the
case, said it was considered important to software publishers and
other computer businesses nationwide.
   Berkeley had sought more than $100 million in lost royalties from
IBM and an injunction preventing IBM for making or selling personal
computers until the expiration of its patent on Oct. 31, one of its
lawyers, Edward Goldstein of Houston, said last year.
   In a counterclaim that was dismissed before the settlement, IBM
had accused Berkeley of trying to extort money by forcing IBM to
license its technology.
   Berkeley filed its suit in 1987, contending that IBM personal
computers, when they ran word processing software, infringed on its
1972 patent on a word processing device.
   IBM argued that the patent was invalid because the ideas in it
were widely known at the time the patent was issued, and that IBM's
computers worked differently.
   A stipulation on the settlement was signed by U.S. District Judge
Joseph C. Howard in Baltimore last week. The agreement becomes void
if its terms are not completed within 180 days.
   Goldstein, Berkeley's lawyer, said Thursday he could not comment
on the settlement. Arnold D. Berkeley, a Washington lawyer who set
up the company with some other investors, was away from his office
and unavailable for comment, a secretary said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
