<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-StockbrokerFlees     02-23 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stockbroker Flees,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stockbroker Charged With Taking Clients' Cash Wrote Of ``Lies And
Deceit''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stockbroker accused of fleeing with millions of
dollars in clients' money wrote that he ``lived in a bowl of lies
and deceit,'' according to an entry from the stockbroker's diary
read in court Thursday.
   The U.S. government has charged former Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
broker Walter F. Curran with $2.6 million in bank fraud and mail
fraud.
   Curran was arrested last week at a U.S.-Canada border crossing
carrying $32,000 in cash, with $100,000 more stuffed in a suitcase
stowed in his car trunk.
   Curran appeared Thursday before U.S. Magistrate Joyce Alexander,
who continued the detention hearing to Friday. U.S. attorneys are
arguing that Curran should be held without bail, while the defense
is seeking his release on $500,000 bail.
   Curran, 46, crossed his arms and lowered his head as prosecutor
Peter Mullin read from a diary seized when the defendant was
arrested.
   ``Everything has finally come to a head. ... There is nothing to
say to justify what I did,'' went the entry for Feb. 8. ``I tried to
capitalize on the use of other people's money. ... I know I will
have to face the consequences.''
   The silver-haired Curran showed little emotion during the all-day
hearing that was attended by friends, family members and attorneys
for his alleged victims.
   Defense attorney Thomas Troy said the diary could weaken his
client's case.
   ``It might be incriminating, but it's there and we're going to
have to talk about it,'' Troy said after the session adjourned.
   In the lengthy diary entry, Curran lamented about the struggle he
had faced since the October 1987 stock market crash and asked
forgiveness from his family for any suffering he had caused.
   The former stockbroker also instructed his former clients to
approach Dean Witter for reimbursement. ``They can claim I
misrepresented their interests,'' the diary said.
   ``I've lived in a bowl of lies and deceit hoping I could resolve
my problems with a miracle,'' Curran wrote. ``I used other people's
money to create a fantasy life and became a prisoner of my own
wishful thinking.''
   Curran was returned late Wednesday to Boston, from which he
allegedly fled last month with millions of dollars in client
investments.
   Executives at the brokerage house's New York headquarters sent
representatives to calm nervous employees after several of Curran's
clients stormed the Boston office Feb. 8 demanding to know his
whereabouts.
   Curran allegedly persuaded the investors to place their money
directly with him on the promise of higher returns.
   The stockbroker's disappearance initially sparked reports that
he'd left the country with as much as $10 million in clients' money
and $475,000 in funds owed the Bank of Boston.
   But Dean Witter spokesman James F. Flynn said Wednesday that $2.3
million was unaccounted for and no further claims were expected.
   Curran has been sued by the Bank of Boston for $260,000 in bad
checks and an unsecured loan.
   Dean Witter representatives on Feb. 9 informed federal
investigators that Curran was missing after he failed to show up for
work, court documents show.
   Federal officials captured Curran a week ago when he attempted to
re-enter the United States at an out-of-the-way town in New York.
   Customs officials alerted authorities after his Canadian rental
car aroused suspicion, and a check of his driver's license revealed
he was wanted in Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
