<FIRST>u f AM-Burlington-Pennzoil     02-23 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burlington-Pennzoil,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burlington Files Complaint Against Pennzoil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burlington Resources Inc. accused Pennzoil Co. on
Thursday of secret takeover plans and asked a federal court to force
the oil company to sell two-thirds of its Burlington stock.
   In a complaint filed in U.S. District Court in Seattle,
Burlington said Pennzoil violated federal securities laws by
``misstating its intentions with respect to its accumulation of the
company's shares and by concealing that it has violated (disclosure)
rules.''
   The complaint said Pennzoil is trying to take over the
Seattle-based diversified resource and energy company. Burlington
requested that the court force Pennzoil to disclose its intentions.
   The complaint also asked the court to make Pennzoil sell 8
million of its 12 million Burlington shares and temporarily bar
Pennzoil from buying more.
   Houston-based Pennzoil, flush with cash from a $3 billion
court-settlement with Texaco Inc. last year, has said its purchases
of Burlington shares over the past several months were for
investment purposes. Nevertheless, Pennzoil's interest in Burlington
has raised speculation it wanted to buy the company.
   Pennzoil issued a brief statement late Thursday calling
Burlington's suit ``frivolous'' and saying it ``will be dealt with
in due course.''
   On the New York Stock Exchange Thursday, Burlington closed at
$49.62{, up from $47.87{ on Wednesday. Pennzoil closed at $81.37{,
up from $80.75.
   Burlington has indicated it will reject any takeover attempt. In
December the company installed a ``poison pill'' defense designed to
make an unwanted acqusition prohibitively expensive.
</TEXT>
