<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru f0242 02-23 0950</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0242,0975</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Will Ease Way for Bank Holding Companies to Buy S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 2nd pvs, ``Greenspan testifying ...,'
with 30-year projections released by OMB; DELETES last graf pvs. Sum of
figures in graf 4 are slightly different from total in graf 3 due to rounding.
Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan,
saying a separately regulated thrift industry may not be needed in
the future, told Congress on Thursday that the Fed will make it
easier for bank holding companies to buy troubled savings and loans.
   Greenspan, testifying before the Senate Banking Committee, also
said the central bank and the Treasury Department have arranged to
support the Federal Home Loan Bank system in the event of runs on
S&amp;Ls.
   Meanwhile, the White House Office of Management and Budget late
Thursday released figures showing the government spending $264.6
billion on S&amp;L problems through the year 2018.
   It breaks down as follows: $52.2 billion to meet commitments in
the rescue of 205 institutions last year, $50 billion to shut down
350 insolvent but still open S&amp;Ls, $73.4 billion to take care of
additional S&amp;Ls slipping into insolvency from 1991 through 2018, and
$89.2 billion in interest payments from 1989 through 2018.
   Even though the outline shows continuing S&amp;L failures in the next
century, it assumes the S&amp;L industry will be basically healthy and
will be paying more than enough deposit insurance premiums to cover
the losses.
   Greenspan's comments came as opposition to President Bush's
333-page S&amp;L proposal grew among members of Congress fighting to
preserve a separate S&amp;L industry.
   At a hearing of the House Banking Committee, Rep. Richard Lehman,
D-Calif., complained that Bush would give banks preference in buying
up S&amp;Ls and turn the oversight and regulation of the thrifts over to
bank regulators.
   ``Rather than heal the wounds, your plan may actually put it (the
S&amp;L industry) out of its misery,'' Lehman told Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady.
   The secretary denied any ``intention on our part to deliver up
the S&amp;L industry to the banking industry.''
   Earlier, Brady had said that S&amp;Ls are an important part of the
nation's commitment to affordable housing and that the
administration plan ``assures the emergence of a healthy and strong
S&amp;L industry.''
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich., chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, said Brady's evaluation seems to conflict with comments
by Greenspan, who said the administration's proposal does not
prejudge whether the thrift industry will survive.
   ``My own judgment is that, at the end of the day, thrifts will
look a lot more like banks than they do now, but there will still be
thrifts,'' Greenspan said. ``Ultimately it's going to be the markets
that are going to determine the banking structure in this country.''
   ``Specialized mortgage lenders will exist because they are
profitable ... I don't think it really matters what kind of
institutional structure we put around it,'' he said.
   But Greenspan told the committee he was not saying that ``at this
stage that we should do away with the thrift industry.''
   What will not survive, he said, is a thrift industry that relies
on short-term deposits to fund long-term, fixed-rate mortgages.
   Greenspan said his board ``attaches considerable importance'' to
a planned Treasury Department study of broad questions not addressed
by the Bush plan, such as the future of deposit insurance and of
S&amp;Ls.
   Riegle expressed concern that the study could be an opening ``for
really doing away with the savings and loan industry.'' He said that
when taxpayers pay billions of dollars toward resolving S&amp;L
problems, they will demand assurance the money is being spent on a
system that serves a public purpose.
   Greenspan said it is ``vitally important'' for Congress to ``very
promptly'' enact the president's S&amp;L plan. In the meantime,
Greenspan said the Federal Reserve, as the financial world's lender
of last resort, has entered into a support arrangement with the
Federal Home Loan Bank system, which lends to S&amp;Ls.
   In November and December, a record $15 billion flowed out of the
nation's S&amp;Ls.
   ``We stand ready to make certain the liquidity needs of the
thrift institutions are met,'' Greenspan said.
   Any lending by the Fed would be secured by property from the
borrowing thrift and guaranteed by the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., which ensures deposits in S&amp;Ls. Although the FSLIC
is technically insolvent, it's backed by the full faith and credit
of the U.S. government.
   If the Fed is called upon, the Treasury Department would also
participate by lending up to $750 million to the FSLIC under a line
of credit that's been available since the 1930s.
   Meanwhile, Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the House
subcommittee with jurisdiction over S&amp;Ls, said he would offer
legislation re-creating an old-fashioned S&amp;L industry. He would
restrict 80 percent of each thrift's future lending to financing
one-to-four-family homes within a 50-mile radius of the institution.
   Brady said the administration opposes that proposal because it
would leave S&amp;Ls too vulnerable to fluctuating interest rates.
   In related topics, Greenspan:
   _Said S&amp;Ls failing to attract more private investment and meet a
6 percent capital level by June 1991 would not be put out of
business. They would, however, be forbidden to grow.
   _Sidestepped an opportunity to crticize the economic assumptions,
including a sharp drop in interest rates and steadily growing
deposits, underlying the Bush S&amp;L plan. Private analysts and members
of Congress have labeled the assumptions as too rosy.
   _Said the president's financing proposal ``should be adequate,''
but conceded ``it's conceivable that there would be the need for a
minor mid-course correction in a year or two.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
