<DOCNO> AP890223-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Tyson-ConAgra     02-23 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tyson-ConAgra,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson, ConAgra Told To Tell the Truth In Bid For Holly Farms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's two largest poultry producers
were ordered Thursday to stop spreading false information about each
other in their ``spirited corporate contest'' to acquire Holly Farms
Corp.
   Senior U.S. District Judge Richard E. Robinson issued a
preliminary injunction against both Tyson Foods Inc. of Springdale,
Ark., and ConAgra Inc. of Omaha.
   Tyson is the largest poultry producer in the United States,
ConAgra is second and Holly Farms of Memphis, Tenn., is fourth.
   Tyson and ConAgra officers have accused each other in lawsuits of
issuing false and misleading press releases about their efforts to
acquire Holly Farms.
   Robinson said in a 27-page opinion that both bidding companies
probably would succeed on the merits of their claims against each
other and each would suffer irreparable harm if the other continued
to issue misleading statements.
   ConAgra, which has offered to merge with Holly Farms, launched
the legal battle when it filed a federal lawsuit Jan. 24 asking that
Tyson be prohibited from issuing ``false, misleading, inaccurate or
incomplete'' press releases.
   The company contended that Tyson said in a press release Jan. 20
that the Holly Farms board of directors would accept a Tyson offer
of $63.50 a share for Holly stock when Tyson already knew its offer
had been rejected.
   Tyson said it had no intent to defraud and that it issued a
clarifying press release to correct what it said it perceived to be
an erroneous headline issued by a financial wire service.
   Tyson later filed a countercomplaint contending that ConAgra's
press release of Jan. 24 concerning its merger offer constituted
solicitation of proxies in violation of federal securities laws.
That press release said ``the real value'' of ConAgra's merger
agreement with Holly exceeded $64 a share.
   Robinson said Thursday that Tyson established ``a reasonable
probability'' that it would succeed in proceeding with its claim
that ConAgra violated proxy solicitation rules.
   ``It seems more than coincidental that ConAgra would cite in its
press release a figure exceeding $64 of `real value,' a figure
greater than the well-publicized $63.50 price offered by Tyson,'' he
wrote.
   Robinson said that because of the volatility of market activity
in the wake of inaccurate or misleading disclosures, ``another Tyson
transgression could irreparably hamper ConAgra's efforts at
obtaining a fair chance for shareholder approval of the merger
agreement.''
   Robinson ordered Tyson to refrain from issuing ``any information
which is false, misleading, inaccurate or incomplete'' about Tyson's
proposal to acquire Holly Farms, or about the ConAgra-Holly merger
agreement.
   He also ordered ConAgra not to solicit any more proxies without
first complying with federal securities regulations.
   ConAgra and Holly Farms officials have said their shareholders
will meet late in March to vote on the proposed merger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0311 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-89 2312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Tower 2ndLd-Writethru f0332 02-23 1119</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower, 2nd Ld - Writethru, f0332,1147</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: New thruout with additional Nunn comment; EDITS to tighten.
Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Armed Services Committee voted
Thursday to recommend rejection of John Tower's nomination as
defense secretary, splitting 11-9 along party lines as it handed
President Bush the first major defeat of his young administration.
   In Tokyo, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush
stands by the nomination which the Democratic-controlled Senate
plans to take up next week. ``We now go to the floor'' of the
Senate, Fitzwater declared.
   But Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the committee, opened the
nearly three-hour session saying Tower's ``record of alcohol abuse
cannot be ignored in my view.''
   ``I have searched in vain for several weeks for the point in time
when the nominee himself acknowledged this problem and dealt with it
decisively. The nominee made it very clear that he has never sought
medical assistance for his drinking problem,'' said Nunn at a
session that included an open discussion of Tower's drinking habits.
   Fitzwater said the committee had ``every right to look into''
allegations which included reports of heavy drinking and womanizing.
But Fitzwater also complained, ``We hear vague talk about concern
about his personal habits and we think this debate ought to be on a
slightly higher level than that.''
   If the full Senate should turn down Tower, a former senator who
used to chair the Armed Services panel, it would be the first time
in history a newly elected president had suffered a rejection of a
nominee to his first Cabinet. In all, eight Cabinet nominations have
been rejected, the most recent 30 years ago.
   Tower, in a statement, said he was ``obviously disappointed with
the outcome of the Senate Armed Services Committee vote.'' But the
statement said Tower will continue to work at the Pentagon ``and
await the vote of full Senate on his confirmation.''
   But Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., urged Bush to withdraw the
nomination before a full Senate decision.
   ``It doesn't do the nominee any good. It doesn't do the president
any good,'' Byrd said. ``It's a tremendous burden for any nominee to
go to the floor with a vote of no confidence.''
   Fred McClure, the White House liasion to Congress, attended the
committee vote and said the president told him prior to the panel's
action, ``just hang in there and I'll be back Monday.''
   Nunn opened the lengthy session by noting that in last year's
presidential campaign, Bush spoke about putting ``ethics at the
center of his agenda and promised that higher standards would be
required when he took office.''
   He said the committee also took the same steps to ensure high
ethical standards, sending a letter to Bush and former Democratic
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis stressing the need for
quality nominees.
   Tower, according to Nunn, failed to meet that standard.
   ``I cannot in good conscience vote to put an individual at the
top of the chain of command when his history of excessive drinking
is such that he would not be selected to command a missile wing, a
SAC bomber squadron or a Trident missile submarine,'' Nunn said.
   On the other side, John Warner of Virginia, the committee's
top-ranking Republican, said the allegations amounted only to a
``cobweb of fiction and fantasy,'' and said he supported the
nomination.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said, ``This committee ought to have
the courage to do what is right.'' He shouted, ``Perception should
not control this committee ... it ought to be the truth.''
   Other Republicans on the panel alleged partisanship by their
colleagues and suggested that Tower was being held to too high a
standard. ``The majority believes we are confirming a defense god,
not a defense secretary,'' said Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.
   Added Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss.: ``This is not a canonization.''
   Following the vote, GOP Sens. John McCain of Arizona and William
Cohen of Maine indicated that the panel's decision might create
serious partisanship problems in the future.
   ``This is going to make it much more difficult to put together a
bipartisan coalition for defense and foreign policy ... I think it's
going to be very damaging to the committee, the bruises deep and
long lasting,'' said Cohen. ``The emotions have been building on
this. I think it's a bad storm rising.''
   McCain said the vote signals ``an incredible increase in
partisanship. John Tower had a lot of friends on our side, and they
think he's been very badly treated.''
   As sentiment against Tower mounted, White House concerns
increased, sending Vice President Dan Quayle and other
representatives into high-gear lobbying.
   From Tokyo, the traveling White House kept tabs on the situation
by telephone, calling committee members and the GOP leadership, said
a White House source speaking on condition of anonymity.
   During the afternoon, the panel met for more than two hours in
closed-door session, then broke up briefly so Democrats and
Republicans could caucus separately.
   Tower has been dogged by allegations of excessive drinking and
womanizing as well as questions stemming from his consulting work
for defense contractors before his nomination. Even his closest
supporters concede he had a drinking problem in the 1970s, but they
say it no longer exists.
   One Democratic senator, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the FBI report contains material concerning an airplane flight from
London to Dallas in which at least one witness reported seeing Tower
drunk. But FBI invetigators were told by an unnamed flight attendant
aboard the flight that Tower was not drunk at the time.
   The panel had sought additional material from the White House, as
well as a transcript of a separate investigation by a House
subcommittee looking into alleged security lapses in an arms control
delegation in Geneva that included Tower in the mid-1980s.
   Prior to the vote, Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas
delivered an emotional appeal to his colleagues, saying the
nomination is a ``matter of minute-by-minute concern'' to Bush.
   ``This is his nominee. He didn't pick John Tower up off the
street. He didn't do it without careful consideration,'' Dole said
in a speech in the Senate chamber.
   The committee members who voted for the motion were Sens. Sam
Nunn, D-Ga.; James Exon, D-Neb.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; Jeff Bingaman,
D-N.M.; Ted Kennedy, D-Mass.; Alan Dixon, D-Ill.; John Glenn,
D-Ohio; Al Gore, D-Tenn.; Tim Wirth, D-Colo.; James Shelby, D-Ala.;
and Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
   The Republicans who voted against the motion were John Warner of
Virginia, Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, William Cohen of Maine,
Pete Wilson of California, John McCain of Arizona, Malcolm Wallop of
Wyoming, Slade Gorton of Washington, Trent Lott of Mississippi and
Dan Coats of Indiana.
  
</TEXT>
